<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rights Group Settles Spying Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Anti-Defamation League has settled a  
class-action lawsuit by agreeing to pay $25,000 to a community 
relations fund and promising not to spy on other civil rights 
groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement, approved by a federal judge Monday, resolves a  
suit filed in 1993 that accused the Jewish civil rights group of 
spying on Arab-American, pro-Palestinian and anti-apartheid groups 
and individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	The ADL, which admitted no wrongdoing, agreed to place $25,000  
in a fund to be used to repair its relationships with the other 
groups and to provide proof to plaintiffs' attorneys over the next 
four years that no such spying is taking place. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Anti-Defamation League is pleased to finally resolve the  
litigation which will now allow us to devote all our resources to 
our work,'' the organization said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The case arose out of a 1992 seizure by San Francisco police of  
more than 17,000 files from the ADL, which was monitoring 
pro-Palestinian and anti-apartheid activists. 
</P>
<P>
	The ADL later paid $75,000 to settle a lawsuit filed by the city  
accusing it of illegally obtaining confidential documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of Monday's settlement, the ADL agreed not to gather  
information from any state or municipal employee in California when 
the ADL knows or should know that the person is providing it 
illegally. The organization may still collect information for 
legitimate journalistic purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	The group also agreed to review its files and remove information  
allegedly obtained illegally. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
