<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 08:00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Philip Morris Backed Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tobacco giant Philip Morris gave $30,000 to a  
nonprofit group that financed Gov. George Pataki's trips to 
Hungary, The New York Times reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The company had never given to the group, the Hungarian-American  
Chamber of Commerce of New York and New Jersey, until shortly 
before Pataki's first trip in 1995, the newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, the company was lobbying the state to repeal  
smoking restrictions in New York City and other localities. Less 
restrictive statewide measures generally had the support of Pataki, 
a Republican, and Republican lawmakers. Democrats blocked the 
measures. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris gave the organization $10,000 a week before  
Pataki's first trip, then contributed the same amount before his 
second visit in 1996, according to the Times. In 1997, it gave 
another $10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, a Philip Morris senior executive who oversaw  
lobbying in New York and other states attended a dinner for Pataki 
in Budapest, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said the governor and his aides  
were not aware of the donations and had not asked the chamber about 
its backers. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki said his visits to Hungary were aimed at promoting trade  
and tracing his roots in the homeland of his paternal grandparents. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost of the trips has never been made public. The chamber  
would not discuss its finances or the cost of the trips, the Times 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris did not make the donations to the chamber in order  
to underwrite Pataki's trips, said Tara Carraro, a company 
spokeswoman. She told the Times the company routinely contributes 
to such trade groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki had dismissed criticism about accepting the gift of  
travel funding, saying the chamber had no business before the 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	A state ethics panel, working with information from the  
governor, concurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethics rules prohibit administration officials from accepting  
gifts of $75 or more from companies with business before the state. 
The rules also bar officials from directing a nonprofit group to 
receive a gift that they cannot legally accept. A separate state 
law requires companies to disclose all lobbying spending on state 
officials, including funds funneled through third parties. 
</P>
<P>
	One member of the ethics panel, Robert E. Eggenschiller, a  
Republican on the board from 1992 to 1997, was troubled by the 
report of Philip Morris contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Ethics Commission should at least go back and see if,  
having known that, they would have voted differently,'' he told the 
Times. ``Why was there this sudden infusion of cash? What was the 
purpose? Were they just being generous? Or was there some ulterior 
purpose? Were they, in a sense, lobbying?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an internal memorandum written shortly after the 1995 trip,  
Philip Morris described Pataki as ``pro-business and openly 
solicitous of PM and appreciative'' of the company's ``contribution 
to the state.'' The memo was among documents disclosed in 
antismoking lawsuits. 






  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
