nebula ``is accelerating particles up to the speed of light and 
flinging them out into interstellar space at an incredible rate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, Hubble Space Telescope images have shown moving  
knots and wisps around the neutron star and X-ray images have shown 
the outer parts of the jet and hinted at the ring structure. With 
Chandra's new observations the ring pattern clearly appears. 
</P>
<P>
	The pulsar within the Crab nebula, discovered by radio  
astronomers in 1968, is a neutron star rotating 30 times per 
second. Neutron stars are formed when gravity crushes the central 
core of the star to densities 50 trillion times that of lead and a 
diameter of only 12 miles. They are highly magnetic and rotate 
rapidly, creating a powerful generator. 
  	   	
</P>
