<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italians Trace Russian Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Italian prosecutors said today they uncovered a  
money-laundering scheme in Italy involving Russian crime gangs and 
the Bank of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Paolo Giovanioli said an investigation begun in 1997  
turned up evidence that Russian criminals had funneled millions of 
dollars to the Bank of New York through the accounts of the Benex 
Corp., registered in London. 
</P>
<P>
	The money was then transferred back to Italy and showed up in  
the bank accounts of Russian gangsters, including Ukrainian Yossif 
Roizis, Giovanioli told the Associated Press by telephone from his 
office in Bologna. 
</P>
<P>
	Roizis was arrested in February and is in jail awaiting trial on  
charges of extortion, kidnapping and racketeering. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the FBI has opened its own investigation. No one  
has been charged, and U.S. law enforcement agencies have refused to 
discuss it. 
</P>
<P>
	Cary Giacalone, a Bank of New York spokesman, declined to  
comment today on the statements from the Italian prosecutor. The 
bank, the 15th largest bank in the United States, has said it is 
cooperating with authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Swiss prosecutors also have been working with Russia on  
investigations into alleged bribery and money laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	Giovanioli said an Italian prosecutor traveled to New York this  
summer to discuss the case with the FBI and to request documents. 
Italy has not been able to complete the inquiry, though, as the 
documents have not yet arrived, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutor's office in Rimini, on Italy's Adriatic coast,  
opened the investigation after a Russian businessman told police 
that other Russians had harassed him, kept him captive and extorted 
money from him, Giovanioli said. 
</P>
<P>
	The inquiry found that Russian gangsters systematically  
threatened fellow traders, forcing them to turn over a part of the 
profits they made from exporting consumer goods to Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The criminal organizations then funneled the illicit funds to  
New York for laundering, Giovanioli said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
