<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Rise on Wet Harvest / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices closed higher on  
the Chicago Board of Trade Tuesday as rain in the Midwest slowed 
the harvest throughout the region. 
</P>
<P>
	With rain moving through much of the Midwest Tuesday, a wet 6-  
to 10-day forecast helped bump up soybeans prices since the harvest 
is already slightly behind analysts' expectations. The U.S. 
Department of Agriculture said Monday that soybeans were 15 percent 
harvested, down from 18 percent a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and wheat also got a boost from weather. However, analysts  
said a surge in gold prices was spurring talk of inflation, helping 
to buoy some commodities. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 6 cents to $2.85 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn rose 1 3/4 cents to $2.13 3/4 a bushel; December oats rose 
1 1/4 cents to $1.15 1/4 a bushel; and November soybeans rose 5 1/2 cents to 
$4.90 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, livestock and meat futures prices were lower on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle fell .35 cent to 66.95 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .22 cent to 79.80 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs fell .08 cent to 48.42 cents a pound; and February frozen 
pork bellies fell 1.85 cents to 63.57 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Offensive Woes Plague Cardinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- As if Arizona didn't have enough problems on  
offense, the Cardinals will be without big-play wide receiver Rob 
Moore for a while. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to be out for a significant amount of time,'' coach  
Vince Tobin said Tuesday. ``How long I don't know, but certainly he 
won't play this week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moore aggravated a pulled hamstring early in Monday night's  
24-10 loss to the San Francisco 49ers. His absence opened the way 
for Andy McCullough, the most valuable player in the World Bowl 
game for the NFL Europe title last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	McCullough didn't exactly earn Tobin's praise, though.  
</P>
<P>
	``He did all right,'' Tobin said. ``I think he needs to play  
better. He needs to block a lot better than he did. He's going to 
have to stop up now that Rob can't go and play more like a veteran 
than a rookie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver David Boston bruised his shoulder in the game, and  
his status won't be known until later in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	As his team fell to 1-2, Tobin was most upset with the  
Cardinals' ongoing turnover problems. Arizona's Jake Plummer was 
intercepted twice and the Cardinals fumbled the ball away twice 
against San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston muffed a punt to set up the 49ers' first touchdown, and  
Plummer's first interception set up the second less than a minute 
later. After Arizona's first sustained drive of the game, Frank 
Sanders fumbled on the goal line and the 49ers recovered for a 
touchback. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had four turnovers in every game we've played,'' Tobin  
said. ``You just can't consistently win games doing that. When we 
get them on defense, we can't do anything with them. When they get 
turnovers, they're scoring touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	``You look at statistics and the team that has the most  
turnovers usually is the team that loses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plummer has thrown nine interceptions compared with just one  
touchdown in three games, a rocky start for the third-year 
quarterback who signed a four-year, $25 million contract last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	But Tobin said he thought Plummer played well in the second half  
in rallying Arizona from a 17-0 deficit to cut the lead to 17-10. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had two good scoring drives in the third quarter and had us  
in a position to win the game,'' Tobin said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Plummer's biggest problem has been a lack of practice  
time because of a sprained thumb. That injury kept him out of 
almost all of the preseason and severely limited his practice time 
the first two weeks of the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now he's able to practice,'' Tobin said. ``I think he's going  
to get healthier and healthier and play better and better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plummer could have used some stronger play from the offensive  
line. He was under pressure almost every time he went back to pass. 
Arizona's struggling ground game resurrected briefly in the 
third-quarter touchdown drive, but otherwise there weren't many 
holes for the backs to run through. 
</P>
<P>
	``The offensive line didn't play very well, as most aspects of  
our team didn't,'' Tobin said. ``Jake took some hits that he 
shouldn't have to take.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
