<HEADLINE> Internet Bank of Ind. Fires Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- An Indiana bank that conducts transactions  
via the World Wide Web has dismissed its president. 
</P>
<P>
	John McCreary, president of First Internet Bank of Indiana, was  
terminated Sept. 17 from the Indianapolis-based institution, 
company officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank chairman David Becker refused to explain the reason for the  
firing, but McCreary's attorney cited other opportunities as a 
reason for the departure. 
</P>
<P>
	Banking industry observer Rick Nisbeth said McCreary's  
traditional banking background may have conflicted with the 
high-tech approaches used by First Internet, founded in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Before launching First Internet Bank, McCreary was a vice  
president with Fifth Third Bank in Dayton, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank opened seven months ago and has amassed about $80  
million in deposits. It has 3,100 accounts from customers across 
the nation, with average account balances above $25,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Until a permanent replacement is found, Becker will serve as  
interim president. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
