<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 15:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Approves StopGap Measure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With fiscal 2000 dawning Friday, Congress  
approved a resolution Tuesday to keep federal agencies open for 
three weeks as Republicans and the White House grapple over 
schools, public housing and other issues that have delayed spending 
bills. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials have said President Clinton would sign the  
bill. That would avert for now the possibility of a federal 
shutdown, which neither party -- especially the Republicans -- wants 
at this point. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-week grace period would give Republicans time to  
smoothe internal disputes over agriculture and other issues and to 
pass as many of the remaining spending bills as they can. It also 
would let both sides sharpen their political messages for what 
looms as an eventual showdown over spending priorities and 
protecting Social Security surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	Not spending Social Security money ``becomes the hard wall on  
which you play every one of these separate bills,'' House Majority 
Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Underlining that point, the House voted 417-2 for a nonbinding,  
GOP-written measure urging lawmakers not to spend Social Security 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as they voted for it, Democrats mocked the measure. They  
cited estimates by the nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office that 
GOP spending plans already erode part of next year's Social 
Security surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	``This resolution is the equivalent of saying we're going to  
quit smoking while we are lighting a cigarette,'' said Democratic 
Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	The House voted 421-2 and the Senate 98-1 for the three-week  
stopgap bill, margins that belied the partisan finger-pointing 
raging over who is to blame for Congress being delinquent on most 
of its spending work. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, lawmakers sent Clinton only the fifth of the 13  
annual bills for the imminent fiscal year when the Senate gave 
final approval to a compromise $21 billion measure financing energy 
and water programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, top Democrat on the House  
Appropriations Committee, said the spending bills had been 
``hijacked by a militant element in the Republican Party caucus 
which says, `My way or no way.''' 
</P>
<P>
	But House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla.,  
said he invited Clinton early this year to join Republicans in 
finding ways to deal with tight spending limits. Those limits, part 
of the 1997 budget-balancing deal, have haunted the GOP all year as 
it has hunted gimmicks that would let it avoid appearing to condone 
higher government spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made requests to the president: get engaged,'' Young said.  
``It was his decision not to do so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Missing the Oct. 1 deadline is practically a congressional  
tradition. Since the current budget process began in fiscal 1977, 
all 13 bills have been passed on schedule only four times, most 
recently for fiscal 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The stopgap bill will let agencies whose spending bills have not  
been enacted by Friday to function at this year's spending levels 
through Oct. 21. So far, those agencies include the departments of 
Health and Human Services, Defense, Interior and NASA. 
</P>
<P>
	It remains unclear how the two sides ultimately will resolve  
their spending disputes. Complicating their work is the GOP effort 
to find ways to claim it is not spending Social Security surpluses, 
which has become one of the party's paramount pledges. 
</P>
<P>
	Majority Leader Armey said Republicans would propose slowing  
payment of tax credits to millions of low-income Americans for a 
savings of $8 billion. The earned income credit would be paid in 
monthly installments instead of the lump sum most of the 20 million 
recipients currently receive. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Republicans dismissed the idea as too harsh when it was  
floated two weeks ago. But Armey called it ``a commonsense 
approach'' that would mainly affect recipients who pay no income 
taxes, adding, ``I would say it is denying them the lump sum 
acceptance of my money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate gave final legislative approval to the energy and  
water measure by 96-3. A veto threat against it, one of seven the 
administration has issued, was dropped after Republicans retreated 
from language that would have made it easier for developers to file 
legal appeals when the government stops them from building on 
wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
	That measure also provides more than $160 million in local water  
projects that the administration did not request, while providing 
less than half the nearly $110 million increase Clinton sought for 
the Energy Department's nuclear weapons facilities. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
