<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Debates Short-Term Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eyeing Friday's start of fiscal 2000, the  
House today moved toward passing a stopgap measure that will keep 
federal agencies functioning for three weeks as President Clinton 
and Republicans sort through spending disputes. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats blamed unyielding Republican demands for Congress'  
failure to complete most of the 13 spending bills on time, a 
failure to meet the schedule that in fact is nearly an annual 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing seven White House veto threats, he said Republicans  
``turned seven bipartisan bills into seven partisan war zones.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the House Appropriations Committee chairman, Rep. Bill  
Young, R-Fla., said he invited Clinton months ago to join 
Republicans in working through their spending differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was his decision not to do so,'' Young said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Senate was expected to approve the bill as early as today.  
White House officials said Clinton would sign it. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to complete as many of the 13 annual spending bills as  
possible by the new fiscal year, GOP leaders planned to push a 
compromise $21 billion energy and water projects measure through 
the Senate today. 
</P>
<P>
	That bill, which would be the fifth to be sent to Clinton, was  
likely to get his signature after Republicans dropped a provision 
that would have helped developers and local governments file 
quicker legal appeals when the government blocks them from building 
on wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
	The House approved the measure Monday by 327-87.  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Senate Appropriations Committee planned to vote  
today on a $324 billion social spending bill for fiscal 2000, which 
begins Friday. The measure, approved Monday by a subcommittee, 
would outspend Clinton on education by $500 million, but provide 
less than he wants for hiring teachers, after-school centers and 
some of his other favorite initiatives. 
</P>
<P>
	In another step, House-Senate bargainers approved a compromise  
$12.6 billion foreign aid measure for the new fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiators dropped language barring aid to groups that  
lobby to ease overseas abortion restrictions, a defeat for 
anti-abortion conservatives. But the bill contained $2 billion less 
than Clinton wanted, cuts that prompted an administration veto 
threat when they were proposed in earlier versions of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The president has already threatened to veto the House's version  
of the education-health-labor bill, citing its cuts in his plans 
for job training for teen-agers, hiring teachers, and other 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate bill eased many of the reductions, but not all. But  
its numbers pushed it far closer to what an eventual compromise 
between the White House and Congress was likely to look like. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe our bill is not perfect, but it's a heck of a lot better  
than what the House did,'' said the subcommittee's top Democrat, 
Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would finance the departments of Labor, Education  
and Health and Human Services for fiscal 2000. It is the most 
controversial -- and the last -- of the 13 annual spending bills to 
begin making its way through Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the measure would pay for automatically approved  
benefits such as Medicaid. The portion that lawmakers fully control 
totals $91.7 billion -- $4 billion more than this year but $1.4 
billion below Clinton's request. 
</P>
<P>
	Of that money, the Senate bill would provide $200 million less  
than the $1.4 billion Clinton wanted for hiring thousands of new 
teachers; $60 million below the $240 million he sought for GEAR-UP, 
which helps disadvantaged students prepare for college; and $200 
million below the $400 million he proposed for before- and 
after-school programs. 
</P>
<P>
	It also would provide $35.2 billion for education, $500 million  
more than Clinton; $11.4 billion for labor programs, $200 million 
less than Clinton wanted; and $37.5 billion for health and human 
services programs, $1.6 billion below Clinton's request. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would provide $17.6 billion for the National Institutes  
of Health, $1.7 billion more than Clinton; $6 billion for education 
for handicapped students, or $600 million more than Clinton; and 
$7.8 billion for Pell grants for low-income undergraduates, $300 
million more than Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	To help Republicans claim the measure would not eat into Social  
Security surpluses, they would delay $16.5 billion of the bill's 
spending until fiscal 2001. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
