<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pilots Asked To Fly 737s Faster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The nation's largest airline has become the  
second to ask pilots of Boeing 737s to speed up during takeoffs and 
landings to avoid the type of rudder malfunction believed to have 
caused a deadly 1994 crash. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Transportation Safety Board ruled this year that a  
rudder reversal most likely caused a US Airways flight to plunge to 
the ground on Sept. 8, 1994, killing all 132 people on board. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, US Airways and United have ordered 737 pilots to speed up  
by about 23 mph to give themselves more time to correct problems 
that cannot be fixed at slower speeds, according to a United 
spokesman and documents obtained by the Pittsburgh Tribune-Review. 
The newspaper reported the United change today and the US Airways 
change Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 737 is the only commercial jet with a rudder controlled by a  
single hydraulic valve. Other jets have multiple valves that can 
compensate if one jams, as the single valve has been known to do, 
according to the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	An NTSB report released in July lists 112 such ``rudder events''  
in the past two decades, malfunctions ``that could be 
catastrophic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because there are 3,111 Boeing 737s in use worldwide -- and as  
many as 800 in the air at any given time -- redesigning the rudder 
could cause severe airline disruptions, not to mention the hundreds 
of millions of dollars it would cost Boeing. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials also are reportedly investigating whether a  
United 737 incident this month was rudder-related. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sept. 15 problem was with United Flight 1253, which took off  
from Atlanta and was landing at Denver with 94 people aboard, 
United spokesman Kurt Evenhoch said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It rolled and yawed,'' said Evenhoch, who likened the movement  
to a car tipping to one side and ``fishtailing.'' ``The airplane 
landed normally and the landing was uneventful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Evenhoch said United Airlines believes wake turbulence -- wind  
forces caused by another airplane -- caused Flight 1253 to roll in 
flight. 
</P>
<P>
	The NTSB has no preliminary cause and is reviewing data from the  
plane's flight data recorder, said Ben Berman, an NTSB spokesman. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 12:40:43 </DATE_TIME>
