<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Sept. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 27.86  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks staged a stunning late-session rally  
today, with the Dow Jones industrials gaining nearly 200 points in 
the last two hours, to close with only modest declines. The 
strengthening dollar against the yen and some computerized buying 
program helped reverse the market's slide. The Dow Jones industrial 
average closed down 27.86 at 10,275.53 after having fallen more 
than 222 points early in the afternoon. It marked the Dow's fifth 
drop in six sessions. Broader stock indicators also fell slightly 
today. The Nasdaq composite index was off 5.48 at 2,756.27. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,275.53  - 27.86
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1,098  Declines 1,897  Unchgd  530
NYSE Volume:         856,586,170
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online109 1/2   + 8 3/8
S&AMP;P 500:         1282.20  - 1.11
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          772.85  - 6.38
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,756.27  - 5.48
Gold(final) -    $308.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.
Silver(final) -   $5.730  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Confidence Slips in Sept.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consumer confidence weakened in September for  
the third consecutive month, suggesting that Federal Reserve moves 
to raise interest rates are cooling off the economy. Still, 
analysts looking at the Conference Board's survey results on today 
said they expect retail sales to remain strong as the holiday 
season approaches. The Conference Board said today that its index 
of consumer confidence, which is a measure of consumers' 
willingness to spend, dipped to 134.2 in September, down 1.8 
percentage points from a revised 136 in August. Analysts had 
forecast that September's reading would be 135.4. Economists noted 
that the latest level still was not far below the June reading of 
139, which was the strongest in more than 30 years. 

</P>
<P>
	Fed Warns Banks on Easing Standards  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve today advised its bank  
examiners to watch for signs that banks may be relaxing their 
lending requirements, creating an increase in shaky loans that 
could threaten the strength of the banking system. The central 
bank's action came a day after Fed Gov. Laurence Meyer warned that 
some banks may be counting too much on continuation of the economic 
boom. Other government officials have issued similar warnings 
recently. 

</P>
<P>
	World Bank, IMF Heads Stress Aid  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Governments and international financial  
institutions must create new coalitions to help developing 
countries escape from poverty, the heads of the World Bank and the 
International Monetary Fund said today. James Wolfensohn of the 
World Bank and Michel Camdessus of the IMF said a plan to cancel as 
much as $27 billion of the debt owed by the world's poorest 
countries is only a beginning of the effort. President Clinton will 
focus on how debt relief can ease these countries' poverty burden 
when he addresses the annual meetings of the World Bank and the IMF 
tomorrow, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Denounces Bank of N.Y. Case  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A senior aide to President Boris Yeltsin said  
Tuesday that allegations of massive Russian money-laundering 
through a New York bank were invented by the West and government 
opponents at home to tarnish Russia. Russia has been reluctant to 
open a major investigation into media reports that Russians may 
have funneled as much as $10 billion through the Bank of New York. 
Deputy chief of staff Igor Shabdurasulov added his name to the list 
of Russian officials who have denounced the whole case as an 
anti-Russian plot. Shabdurasulov dismissed media reports on the 
case and allegations of bribe-taking by Kremlin officials. 

</P>
<P>
	Y2K Will Add to Russia's Woes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Past fears of an errant Russian missile launch  
can probably be put to rest, but Y2K computer problems still 
threaten serious disruptions to the U.S.-Russia crisis hotlines, a 
Pentagon official said today. Assistant Defense Secretary Edward 
Warner, testifying before the special Senate panel on Y2K, said 
Y2K-related software problems could affect full operation of six of 
the seven direct communications links between the two countries. 
But he also voiced cofidence that the fixes will be installed and 
tested by December, before the world confronts the Y2K problem on 
Jan. 1. 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Management Case Settled  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The cash-strapped group assuming management of  
much of the Internet agreed today to allow a Virginia company to 
continue for at least four years as keeper of the master list of 
World Wide Web addresses in exchange for a $1.25 million payment. 
The complex settlement aims to resolve the most contentious 
arguments surrounding transition of control over the Web from the 
federal government to the California-based Internet Corporation for 
Assigned Names and Numbers. The impact of the agreement on typical 
Internet consumers is slight. The agreement involvews largely 
behind-the-scenes management of technical issues and standards. 

</P>
<P>
	Chase Buying Hambrecht &AMP; Quist  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp., has moved to enhance its  
securities underwriting capability, announcing today that is buying 
the investment banking firm Hambrecht &AMP; Quist for $1.35 billion in 
cash. The deal will enable Chase to offer firms a wider range of 
financial services. Chase Manhattan and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist said the 
deal had been approved by both boards and is expected to be 
completed by the end of this year. Chase will pay $50 a share for 
each share of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. Chase Manhattan stock was down 
5/16 at 73 13/16 today. Hambrecht &AMP; Quist was up 7 5/8 at 48 11/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Boeing Buys Aussie Software Company  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Co. has bought The Preston Group, an  
Australian company specializing in software that simulates air 
traffic and airport use. Financial details were not disclosed in 
the acquisition announced today. Preston, based in Melbourne, has 
offices in Washington, D.C., and London. Its primary software 
product is the Total Airspace and Airport Modeler, which allows 
airlines, airports and civil aviation authorities to simulate and 
analyze air traffic and terminal use at an airport. 

</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com, P.O. Share Ad Campaign  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amazon.com and the Postal Service are  
launching a joint advertising campaign. The idea is to establish 
Amazon.com as the ultimate gift-giving destination in the United 
States and the U.S. Postal Service and Priority Mail as the 
preferred shipper of leading e-commerce companies, according to 
postal spokeswoman Judy deTorok. Postmaster General William 
Henderson said the project was initiated during a meeting of the 
postal governing board in Seattle, when officials visited Internet 
book seller Amazon.com's headquarters to discuss common interests. 

</P>
<P>
	AOL, China.com Launch AOL Hong Kong  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- AOL Hong Kong made its debut today. The joint  
undertaking of America Online, Inc. and China.com will offer 
Chinese and English-language content designed for local Hong Kong 
customers. AOL, the U.S. Internet access provider with 18 million 
users worldwide, refused to put a value on the deal. AOL Chief 
Executive Steve Case said his company hoped to expand from Hong 
Kong into mainland China, playing down recent remarks by China's 
information minister, Wu Jichuan, on enforcing a ban on foreign 
investment in Internet companies. 

</P>
<P>
	Shares Fall Across Europe  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Share prices fell across Europe today, driven down  
by losses by British banks and the decline in the Dow Jones 
industrial average in the United States before European markets 
closed. Europewide indexes fell, with the Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 
592 European companies shedding 4.00 points to close at 305.38. The 
Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in countries 
that joined the single currency, closed down 3.82 points at 319.56. 
In domestic markets, London's FTSE 100 index fell 1.2 percent, 
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index fell 2.3 percent and the Paris CAC-40 
index fell 1.1 percent. 

</P>
