<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 16:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Renews Bill Veto Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright renewed a  
veto threat Tuesday against a foreign aid bill that fails to pay 
for the Middle East peace process and deeply slashes international 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``At these levels, we would have no flexibility to deal with  
emerging threats or respond to urgent crises,'' she told an 
audience of leaders of Jewish organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	House-Senate negotiators completed work late Monday night on a  
$12.6 billion foreign aid spending bill for the fiscal year that 
begins Friday. It now awaits final House and Senate votes, with 
further amendments prohibited. 
</P>
<P>
	The amount in the bill is $2 billion below that requested by  
President Clinton, Albright complained. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright also said that while the Clinton administration hopes  
to get Israeli-Syrian peace talks back on track, it opposes any 
formula that would link progress in those talks to other 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks were suspended in 1996.  
</P>
<P>
	``The issue here is whether we can find the way to restart  
negotiations that will match the will that all sides profess to 
feel,'' Albright told the Conference of Presidents of Major 
American Jewish Organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	The day before, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy told  
Albright that Israel cannot accept an Egyptian proposal that would 
link progress in Syrian-Israeli talks to wider peace negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	During a private portion of Tuesday's meeting with Jewish  
leaders, Albright was questioned about the Egyptian position and 
told the audience she did not agree with it, a senior 
administration official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	On the foreign aid bill, Albright indicated she and other senior  
advisers still plan to recommend a veto, even though an 
anti-abortion provision strongly opposed by the administration was 
jettisoned. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation failed to provide money for implementing Middle  
East peace accords that the Israelis and Palestinians reached last 
year in negotiations at Wye River, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only has Congress ignored the administration's request for  
at least $500 million for Israel and the Palestinians to carry out 
the accords in the fiscal year beginning Friday, foreign aid 
negotiators also cut $100 million promised to Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wye River money is contained in a separate spending bill  
that Clinton has sent Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related development, the Palestinians urged the Clinton  
administration and Congress to ease U.S. restrictions that might 
make it hard for them to get their share of the peace-process 
money. Some date back to the 1980s when the Palestinian Liberation 
Organization was viewed by the United States as a terrorist 
organization, said Hassan Abdel Rahman, the PLO representative in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wish the Congress to give us this money and that President  
Clinton will do all he can to get us this money,'' Rahman said. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman David Leavy said the White House ``would  
be consulting closely with Congress in the future'' about ways of 
broadening the U.S.-Palestinian relationship, including possibly 
lifting no-longer-suitable restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	The conditions could deny U.S. assistance to the Palestinians  
unless they met a variety of free-immigration and human rights 
tests. 
</P>
<P>
	In her speech, Albright urged the Jewish leaders to help lobby  
for the separate spending measure and to support Clinton's 
prospective veto of the foreign aid bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``Diplomacy is America's first line of defense,'' Albright said.  
``It should be treated as a budget priority.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She added: ``I have eliminated the words `foreign aid' from our  
vocabulary. These two words don't seem to excite a lot of people.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
