<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chiquita Source Sues Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A former lawyer for Chiquita Brands  
International Inc. has sued The Cincinnati Enquirer, accusing the 
newspaper of breaking a promise by identifying him as a source for 
its expose of the banana company. 
</P>
<P>
	George Ventura claims former Enquirer reporters Michael  
Gallagher and Cameron McWhirter promised him confidentiality -- with 
management's knowledge -- in exchange for inside information about 
Chiquita. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura said the reporters violated the promise by secretly  
taping conversations with him and later identifying him to Chiquita 
and law enforcement authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura is seeking unspecified punitive and compensatory  
damages. His federal lawsuit accuses the Enquirer and its parent, 
the Gannett Co., of breach of contract, fraud and negligence. 
</P>
<P>
	The Enquirer and Gannett denied identifying confidential  
sources. 
</P>
<P>
	The Enquirer in May 1998 published a series of stories  
suggesting that Cincinnati-based Chiquita engaged in improper 
business practices overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The next month, the newspaper fired Gallagher, saying he had  
employed unethical means of getting information, and renounced the 
stories in a front-page apology. The newspaper also paid Chiquita 
more than $10 million to settle any legal claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher later admitted stealing Chiquita executives' voice  
mail for the series and was sentenced to five years of probation. 
He also cooperated in the prosecution of Ventura, who was 
identified in court as a source for the articles. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, Ventura pleaded no contest to supplying the secret  
codes Gallagher used to get into the voice-mail boxes. Ventura got 
two years of probation. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, 38, said the disclosure that he was a source for the  
Enquirer stories cost him his job at a Salt Lake City law firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence K. Beaupre, then editor of the Enquirer and now a news  
executive at Gannett, denied the allegations in Ventura's lawsuit. 
``The Enquirer and Gannett have never identified any confidential 
sources,'' Beaupre said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher's lawyer, Patrick Hanley, said: ``We don't believe  
that Mike Gallagher broke any promises to Mr. Ventura.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McWhirter is now a reporter for The Detroit News, another  
Gannett newspaper. His lawyer also said McWhirter did not identify 
sources for the Chiquita story. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, the Supreme Court ruled that the First Amendment does  
not protect news organizations from being sued when they publish 
the names of sources promised confidentiality. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling came in the case of Dan Cohen, a public-relations  
executive who worked for a Republican gubernatorial candidate in 
Minnesota in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen told reporters for the Minneapolis Star-Tribune and St.  
Paul Pioneer Press that the Democratic candidate for lieutenant 
governor once had been charged with shoplifting $6 worth of sewing 
material. 
</P>
<P>
	The reporters promised Cohen confidentiality, but their editors  
said his name should be used to make it clear that the information 
came from a rival campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury awarded Cohen $700,000, but that was knocked down to  
$200,000 on appeal. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
