<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Prices Rise Above $300  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Gold prices surged past the $300-an-ounce mark to a 17-month  
high Tuesday in a powerful two-day rally sustained by news that a 
group of central banks would limit their combined sales of bullion. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, soybean and grain futures rose, while most  
energy futures retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold prices began shooting higher after 15 European central  
banks announced Sunday that they would limit their combined sales 
of bullion to 400 tons per year for a total of five years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's had enormous ramifications on the market,'' said Matthew  
Ford, a metals analyst with U.S. Global Investors Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the day December gold prices flirted with the $330  
per-troy-ounce mark before settling at $310 an ounce on the New 
York Mercantile Exchange, up from $283.80 on Monday, when prices 
also rose sharply. The current contract, for September delivery, 
closed at $308 an ounce, a gain of $26.20. Exchange officials said 
the last time gold finished at this level was on April 28, 1998, 
when gold settled at $308.30. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, gold closed at $301.50 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$279.90 on Monday and the highest level since Oct. 2, 1998, when it 
also finished the day at $301.50. In Zurich the bid price was 
$301.02 an ounce, up from $280.93. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, harvest-slowing rain and predictions for more wet  
weather in the Midwest sent grain and soybean futures prices higher 
on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say the soybean harvest is already slightly behind  
schedule and will likely be further delayed if the 6- to 10-day 
forecast for rain pans out. The U.S. Department of Agriculture said 
Monday that soybeans were 15 percent harvested, down from 18 
percent a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and wheat also got a boost from weather. Analysts said the  
surge in gold prices was spurring talk of inflation, helping to 
boost some commodities prices. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Tuesday, wheat for December delivery rose 6 cents to  
$2.85 3/4 a bushel; December corn rose 1 3/4 cents to $2.13 3/4 a bushel; 
December oats rose 1 1/4 cents to $1.15 1/4 a bushel; and November 
soybeans rose 5 1/2 cents to $4.90 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, energy futures settled mostly lower on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange, confirming analysts predictions that Monday's 
surge in gasoline prices would be short-lived. 
</P>
<P>
	Light sweet crude oil for November delivery fell 28 cents to  
$24.33 a barrel; October heating oil fell .44 cent to 61.68 cents a 
gallon; October unleaded gas rose .09 cent to 72.75 cents a gallon; 
and natural gas fell .72 cent to $2.560 cents per million British 
thermal units. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent crude for November delivery fell 31  
cents to $23.76 a barrel. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
