<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Examine HMO Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to use an  
Illinois case to decide whether health-maintenance organizations 
can sometimes be sued for offering doctors financial bonuses to 
keep costs down. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said it will hear a health plan's bid to stop an  
Illinois woman, who blamed her ruptured appendix on inadequate 
care, from suing her HMO on a claim that it violated its management 
duties. 
</P>
<P>
	Cynthia Herdrich of Bloomington, Ill., sued the Carle Clinic  
Association in 1992, saying her appendix ruptured and peritonitis 
set in because her doctor delayed diagnostic tests for eight days 
so the tests could be performed at a facility owned by the HMO. 
</P>
<P>
	Herdrich was awarded $35,000 in damages under state law, but she  
also sued under a federal law, the Employee Retirement Income 
Security Act, which governs employee benefits and pensions. 
</P>
<P>
	Herdrich contended the HMO violated its management duty to its  
patients by depriving them of proper medical care and keeping the 
cost savings. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge dismissed that claim, but the 7th U.S. Circuit  
Court of Appeals said the issue could go to trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``According to the complaint, Carle doctors stood to gain  
financially when they were able to limit treatments and 
referrals,'' the appeals court said. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said such incentives do not automatically mean a plan  
has violated its duty to its patients, but that a breach of duty 
can arise ``where physicians delay providing necessary treatment 
to, withhold administering proper care to, plan beneficiaries for 
the sole purpose of increasing their bonuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, the health plan's lawyers said  
that if Herdrich could sue, ``then many, if not most, HMOs are 
unlawful.'' They said the case ``has far-reaching implications for 
all managed care plans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Herdrich's lawyers said the 7th Circuit court's ruling was more  
narrowly tailored to the facts of her case. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Pegram vs. Herdrich, 98-1949.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
