<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NEC To Sell Building, Cut Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese electronics maker NEC Corp. plans to sell  
its headquarters building, reduce its 37-member board by half and 
cut its debt over the next three years. 
</P>
<P>
	The company disclosed the plans Tuesday as it slashed its  
earnings forecast for the year, citing lower sales of memory chips 
and communications devices. 
</P>
<P>
	It expects to earn a group net profit of 10 billion yen, or $94  
million, in the fiscal year ending March 2000. It had previously 
forecast earnings of 25 billion yen. 
</P>
<P>
	NEC said that although domestic sales of cellular phones and  
personal computers have been solid, sales of memory chips and 
overseas sales of communications devices have fallen sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the company said sales are expected to be 50  
billion yen, or $472 million, below initial expectations of 5 
trillion yen, or $47 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The new sales forecast still would represent a 5 percent  
increase from the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	NEC plans to reduce its debt by $5.66 billion over three years.  
A cpmpany spokesman declined to say how much debt NEC had overall. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
