<HEADLINE> Harvest Rain Boosts Grain, Soybeans / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices moved higher in  
trading early today on the Chicago Board of Trade as rain in the 
Midwest slowed harvest progress throughout the region. 
</P>
<P>
	The sudden rise in gold prices also was stirring enthusiasm in  
the commodities market. 
</P>
<P>
	A forecast for wet weather over the next six to 10 days helped  
bump up soybean prices, with the harvest progress to date a little 
behind what analysts had expected. The U.S. Department of 
Agriculture said Monday that soybeans were 15 percent harvested, 
down from 18 percent a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn also got a boost from weather and gold. Investors said  
buyers who have no interest in corn are jumping into the market 
because of the rise in the price of gold and the new speculative 
money it is attracting to commodity markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The surge in gold also was spurring talk of inflation, helping  
to underpin commodity prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat opened higher, extending Monday's rally.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 2 1/4 cents to $2.82 a bushel;  
December corn rose 1 1/2 cents to $2.13 1/2 a bushel; December oats rose 
1/2 cent to $1.14 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans rose 2 3/4 cents to 
$4.87 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork futures were lower in early trading on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle fell .35 cent to 66.95 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .07 cent to 79.95 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs rose .35 cent to 48.85 cents a pound; February frozen 
pork bellies fell 2.32 cents to 63.10 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
