<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ralston Sells Battery Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Ralston Purina Co. is selling its line of  
Energizer rechargeable batteries, used in cellular phones, power 
tools and laptop computers, to Moltech Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale announced Tuesday to Tucson, Ariz.-based Moltech allows  
Ralston to focus on its Energizer brand batteries, which face tough 
competition from arch-rival Duracell. 
</P>
<P>
	Ralston had been seeking a buyer since April for the business --  
the Energizer Power Systems Original Equipment Manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but Ralston said its  
Eveready Battery Co. Inc. would retain a minority interest in the 
combined business. The deal was expected to be completed by late 
October. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis-based Ralston announced in June that it would separate  
its Eveready Battery subsidiary in a spinoff. The spinoff, which 
still needs government approval, was expected to be completed next 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	``For Moltech, it's a good fit,'' said Juli Niemann, an analyst  
with Huntleigh Securities in St. Louis. ``The big question is, how 
much are they selling it for -- and of course, they aren't saying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ralston stock slipped 50 cents Tuesday on the New York Stock  
Exchange to close at $28.37 1/2 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Energizer Power Systems reported $98 million in sales in the  
first nine months of the current fiscal year, down from $117 
million in the same period a year earlier. It has struggled because 
of softness in the world economy. Makers of rechargeable devices 
switched to batteries made in Asia as weakening currencies made 
their products cheaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Energizer Power Systems is based in Gainesville, Fla. It  
employes 2,100 workers worldwide with operations in Gainesville; 
Juarez, Mexico; the United Kingdom and Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	Moltech has focused primarily on developing and commercializing  
a revolutionary new chemistry and cell design for a new class of 
rechargeable batteries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Moltech and EPS are very complementary with Moltech's  
expertise in research and development and EPS's strength in 
production, marketing and sales,'' said Dr. Terje Skotheim, 
chairman and CEO of Moltech. ``Together, they will be a formidable 
competitor in the global rechargeable battery industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moltech, a private corporation, is funded by a number of U.S.  
and European investors. It was founded in 1988 as a spin-off from 
Brookhaven National Laboratory. In addition to its own scientists, 
Moltech has collaborative agreements with a number of top research 
organizations around the world. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
