<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Vexes Calif. Wildfire Fighters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIG SUR, Calif. (AP) -- Firefighters toiled in unseasonably hot  
temperatures Tuesday as they battled wildfires that have scorched 
125,000 acres of California wilderness. 
</P>
<P>
	The fires destroyed at least 49 homes in Happy Valley in far  
Northern California and threatened others in the coastal mountains 
of Big Sur on Tuesday. One fire crewman died late Monday night 
after suffering a heart attack while being evacuated in the Trinity 
Alps Wilderness. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures soared past 90 degrees on Tuesday in Monterey  
County, where 3,300 firefighters were battling two large wildfires 
that had consumed 48,608 acres in the Los Padres National Forest on 
the scenic central California coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents have been evacuated from the area, where up to a dozen  
homes and numerous other buildings are at risk. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest problem was the Hare Fire, which had burned 20,158  
acres as of Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``That fire is very active,'' fire information officer Juanita  
Freel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another fire in the region had burned 28,450 acres and was 45  
percent contained. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the higher temperatures, the higher winds and the low  
humidity, you do have more active fires,'' Freel said. ``But that's 
not the main difficulty in fighting these fires. It's the terrain. 
It's steep and rugged.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
