<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Expands Intelligence in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRNS, Australia (AP) -- The United States is beefing up its  
intelligence support for the Australian-led peacekeeping contingent 
in East Timor this week but is unlikely to offer significant 
additional troops, U.S. officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen arrived tonight in this resort  
city off the Great Coral Reef for a series of meetings with 
Australian officials, including Defense Minister John Moore. They 
were to discuss the progress so far in restoring order in East 
Timor and ways in which the United States can increase its support, 
Cohen told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials traveling with Cohen told reporters en route to  
Cairns today that the Pentagon sent seven more intelligence 
officials to Darwin, the jumping off point for the peacekeepers in 
East Timor, to assist Australian intelligence. Also, Australia is 
now getting support from the U.S. Joint Intelligence Center in 
Hawaii, the officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 27 Americans are being dispatched, apparently to Darwin,  
``in support of special intelligence requirements,'' the Pentagon 
said without elaborating. Furthermore, a six-man special 
communications team from Hawaii is heading to the area to provide 
secure communications and unspecified ``specialized intelligence 
capabilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N.-sanctioned peacekeeping effort on the ground in East  
Timor is comprised several thousand forces mainly from Australia 
and Southeast Asian nations. Washington has said it has no plans to 
offer combat forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the additional contributions Cohen is considering:  
increased use of U.S. Air Force C-17 and C-141 transport aircraft 
for flights into Darwin or Bauccau, which is an air field in East 
Timor east of the capital Dili. Eventually the Pentagon intends to 
send a nine-member airlift control squad to Baccau for aircraft 
loading and unloading operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met in New York  
with Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer to discuss the 
peacekeeping operation in East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	``They discussed how we continue to need to have close  
coordination with the Australians and with all interested 
parties,'' said a senior administration who spoke on the condition 
of anonymity. They agreed ``there was a long way to go'' before 
peace is restored, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	The official said Downer did not say that more troops were  
needed for the Australian-led force. 
</P>
<P>
	As of Monday there were about 260 Americans in Darwin, including  
a handful in East Timor, Cohen told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview aboard his plane headed from Washington on  
Monday, Cohen said Indonesia must swiftly investigate its army's 
involvement in the atrocities committed in East Timor as a first 
step toward regaining normal military ties to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen said Indonesia's democratic aspirations demand that it  
hold the military responsible for any misdeeds. 
</P>
<P>
	``They should make an inquiry. They should do it as quickly as  
possible, as thoroughly as possible,'' Cohen said, adding that he 
would not prejudge the outcome. ``It's apparent that there were 
activities that were taking place in East Timor that are simply 
unacceptable,'' he said, and the Indonesian army ``is going to have 
to be accountable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Geneva, the U.N. Human Rights Commission voted Monday for an  
international inquiry into atrocities in East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Cohen will visit Jakarta to meet with Gen. Wiranto,  
the Indonesian defense chief who some foreign diplomats say has 
become the principal power broker in the country. Cohen also will 
meet with President B.J. Habibie and Megawati Sukarnoputri, 
daughter of Indonesia's founding president and widely expected to 
be the next head of state. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States broke off military relations with Indonesia in  
early September in response to the violence in East Timor, which 
was triggered by an Aug. 30 referendum vote in favor of 
independence from Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen said that before the United States will restore relations,  
the Indonesians must show they have established civilian control of 
the army, some elements of which supported and reportedly 
participated in militia violence in East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indonesian government must ``find out who participated in  
what activities,'' Cohen said. When asked whether he believed that 
those officers found responsible should be purged from the 
military, he replied, ``If individuals engaged in activities that 
are a clear violation of human rights then there should be some 
consequences, yes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later this week Cohen intends to discuss East Timor and other  
topics -- including the state of efforts to repair U.S.-Chinese 
relations -- during stops in Thailand, Singapore and the 
Philippines. Thailand is the second-biggest contributor of troops 
to the East Timor operation, behind Australia, and has a 
long-standing military relationship with the United States. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
