<HEADLINE> Delta, Singapore Sell Stakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta Air Lines and Singapore Airlines are  
selling their financial stakes in each other as the two carriers 
formally end a 10-year business relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta disclosed Tuesday it sold its 35.2 million shares of  
Singapore Airlines stock, about 3 percent, and realizing a 
before-tax gain of $140 million. Delta also is repurchasing 5 
million shares of Delta stock held by Singapore. Singapore said it 
will receive the equivalent of a total $309 million from the Delta 
stock sale as well as from the sale of stock in Swissair. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Swissair pulled out of the three-way alliance with  
Delta and Singapore and sold its 8 million shares of Singapore 
stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta still owns a minority stake in Swissair, which it also  
plans to sell. The company would not say when. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta also disclosed that it sold 1.8 million shares of stock in  
Priceline.com last month, realizing before-tax proceeds of about 
$115 million. Priceline.com is an Internet company that lets buyers 
set their own prices for everything from groceries to air travel. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
