<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Praises Female Accomplishments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate  
Elizabeth Dole praised women's accomplishments Tuesday and plugged 
the American Red Cross' role in helping Hurricane Floyd's victims. 
</P>
<P>
	While president of the relief organization for eight years, Dole  
said she had seen many disasters ``that will haunt me for the rest 
of my life all around the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is especially difficult to see the effects of Hurricane  
Floyd right in my own home state,'' the Salisbury native told about 
500 people at a women's business conference. 
</P>
<P>
	In a brief interview after the speech, Dole urged people to make  
donations to the Red Cross to help buy relief supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been devastating for North Carolina, and it just  
breaks your heart,'' she said. ``My thoughts and prayers are 
certainly with the families. I think that if we can just give to 
that effort, it will make a tremendous difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Casting herself as a woman who battled the male establishment  
before and during the women's liberation movement, Dole said women 
now are a dominant force in the nation's economy, especially as the 
owners of independent businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was growing up, most men and women lived in a different  
America altogether,'' and women were expected to get married and 
limit business aspirations to teaching or clerical jobs, Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole, 63, received a bachelor's degree from Duke University in  
1958, and master's and law degrees from Harvard University. 
</P>
<P>
	``While great progress has been made, there's still much work to  
be done, I'm sure you all agree, before all the barriers are down, 
before the glass ceiling meets the same fate as the Berlin Wall,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement released earlier Tuesday, Dole said Scott  
Malyerck, Dan Quayle's top South Carolina organizer, had signed on 
to her campaign. Quayle abandoned his White House bid Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is now a two-person race, and Elizabeth Dole has the  
highest favorability rating. She can beat any Democrat in any 
scenario,'' said Malyerck. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
