<HEADLINE> Australia Set To Boost Drug Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Drug testing for Australian athletes  
leading up to and during the Sydney Olympics will increase by 25 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian Sports Drug Agency chief executive Natalie Howson  
said Tuesday the agency will administer more than 6,000 tests 
during the 1999-00 financial year, along with 1,500 tests in the 
weeks before the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government-funded program will be the largest ever  
conducted with nearly 50 percent more tests than in the leadup to 
the 1996 Atlanta Olympics,'' Howson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The testing will involve Australian athletes training in the  
country and abroad, as well as foreigners competing in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have already negotiated a number of arrangements with  
Canada, Denmark, New Zealand, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland and the 
United Kingdom that will facilitate reciprocal testing,'' Howson 
said. ``That is a good start and there is more to come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Latest figures from ASDA on testing results indicate Australian  
athletes are doing well. Despite an increase of 12 percent in the 
number of tests to 4,801 for the one-year period that ended in June 
1999, there were only 43 positive tests -- one more than the 
previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It suggests Australian sport is in fairly good condition,  
taking into account it must be appreciated that EPO and human 
growth hormone are non-detectable at this point,'' said ASDA 
spokeswoman Vicky Kapernick. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
