<HEADLINE> Stocks Move Lower; Dow Down 56.67 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell in early trading today as the  
markets were unable to sustain Monday's timid rally. Technology and 
Internet stocks were mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was down 56.67 at 10,246.72. 
</P>
<P>
	yesterday, the Dow rose 24.06 to 10,303.39, halting a four-day  
retreat as bargain-hunters entered the market. But the blue chip 
index finished well below its highs of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also fell. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was down 8.44 at 1,274.87, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
off 23.65 at 2,738.10. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board, a research group, today said consumer  
confidence dipped in September for a third consecutive month, 
although forecasters expected a moderate increase. The report may 
indicate consumer spending may be slowing, and thus, reduce the 
need for the Federal Reserve to boost interest rates to cool of the 
economy. The Fed's policy-setting Open Market Committee meets next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	But the consumer confidence report did little to move the  
markets, probably because most analysts expect the Fed to leave 
interest rates alone for now. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar, whose recent weakness was a factor in the market's  
big decline last week, has held steady against the Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, off 1 1/16 to 77 1/8, and Microsoft, off 7/8 to 90 9/16,  
helped depress technology issues today. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 105.28 million 
shares, up from Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index fell 1.63 at 420.23.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 3.0 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 1.85 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.93 percent, and France's CAC-40 was 
down 1.06 percent. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
