<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. Players Attend Watson Memorial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Pat Watson, the Georgia assistant football  
coach who died of a heart attack Saturday night, was lauded for a 
life of hard work and love of family during an hour-long memorial 
service on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the most unbelievable perfectionist you have ever  
seen,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan told the crowd of 500 packed into 
the Prince Avenue Baptist Church. 
</P>
<P>
	``He gave of himself unselfishly for others'' and didn't seek  
recognition for what he did,'' Donnan said. ``He was just 
interested in the bottom line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watson's 22-year-old son, Cal, also spoke, saying it was the  
hardest thing he ever did. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'd tell me to suck it up and do it, and that's what I'm  
going to do,'' Watson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we could have asked for a better scripted  
departure,'' the son said. ``When my father died, he had all his 
ducks in a row. My father went out a winner -- undefeated on the 
field and in the game of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attending the memorial service were his fellow assistants at  
Georgia and the Bulldogs football team, along with some of his 
former players when he was an assistant at Georgia Tech and 
Virginia Tech. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Dooley, brother of Georgia athletic director Vince Dooley,  
had Watson and Donnan on his staff at North Carolina in 1967-68. 
Other former coaches attending were Ray Goff, who preceded Donnan 
at Georgia; and Paul Davis, who coached at Auburn and Mississippi 
State, where Watson was an offensive lineman and linebacker in the 
early 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Bill Ricketts, pastor of the church, said Watson put a  
lot into his 56 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a man who knew the value of hard work,'' the minister  
said, as well as a loving family. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson was stricken only hours after Georgia's 24-23 victory  
over Central Florida, shortly after having dinner with his family 
at his home. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson will be buried on Thursday in the Pine Hill Cemetery at  
Enterprise, Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Meridian, Miss., Watson played two years in the CFL  
before becoming an assistant at such schools as North Carolina, 
Furman, Mississippi State, Virginia Tech, Georgia Tech and Texas 
before joining Donnan's Georgia staff as offensive line coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the service, quarterback Quincy Carter said Watson's  
death was ``a reality check on life for all of us. Football is 
important to all of us, but life is first. Right now our focus in 
on coach Watson and his entire family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During his weekly news conference before the service, Donnan  
said the team would attend and then have a brief workout later in 
the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to handle adversity that comes,'' Donnan said. ``This  
is just another detour here. It's a tragic one. We've got to 
separate our grief and our sorrow and come back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
