<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Temperament Bars Man From Law Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Paul Converse may not be the nicest guy in  
the world, but does that mean he cannot become a lawyer? 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Denne, Converse's attorney, put that question to the  
Nebraska Supreme Court on Tuesday in an effort to reverse the state 
bar commission's refusal to let Converse take the bar exam. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can a person be prevented from taking the bar exam and  
becoming a lawyer in this state for basically being a pain in the 
neck?'' Denne asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Converse, 47, graduated from law school at the University of  
South Dakota in 1998. But his application to take the exam was 
denied because he was consistently ``abusive, disruptive, hostile, 
intemperate, intimidating, irresponsible, threatening or 
turbulent'' while in school, the Nebraska State Bar Commission said 
in a letter to Converse last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission said that, among other things, Converse created  
T-shirts with an obscene caricature of the law school's dean, 
threatened to sue over various situations, and put up a photograph 
of a nude woman's backside at his work station. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Lessmann, attorney for the bar commission, said Converse  
appears unwilling to change his behavior, which could lead to 
sanctions if he were allowed to practice law. 
</P>
<P>
	``Converse should be encouraged to expend his energies in  
positive directions which could be considered as indicative of 
rehabilitation or reform of his character or fitness, if he is 
allowed by this court to reapply for admission,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Denne, however, said keeping Converse from taking the bar exam  
violates his freedom of speech and his due process rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has no criminal history, no history of fraud or other types  
of dishonesty and no history of violence,'' he said. ``Paul 
Converse is a vigorous advocate for causes he believes in. He has 
an absolute right to champion those causes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The high court did not say when it would rule.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
