<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dealers See Threat in New GM Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Car buyers looking for a deal on a General Motors  
Corp. car or truck may soon be able to shop at a company-run 
dealership -- an idea that might not sit well with 7,700 dealers 
already selling GM vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said Tuesday it has set up an independent subsidiary to own  
and operate dealerships across the country. General Motors Retail 
Holdings will buy or partner with dealerships in the largest 130 
markets across the country, and could own from 5 percent to 10 
percent of GM's dealerships in 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	A GM executive said the new arrangement was the best way for GM  
to get closer to customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is critical to GM's future competitiveness that we improve  
our market performance where we lag, enhance our revenues, 
understand our customers better and look for ways to reduce 
distribution costs and improve the customer's buying experience,'' 
said Roy S. Roberts, group vice president of GM North American 
Vehicle Sales, Service and Marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	But the chairman of the National Automobile Dealers Association  
said the move was ``a huge threat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think its terrible,'' said James Willingham, who owns two GM  
dealerships in California. ``This announcement was made without any 
consultation of dealers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GMRH is the latest in a series of moves by GM and Ford Motor Co.  
aimed at improving how their vehicles are sold. In recent years the 
automakers have bought out some dealers and consolidated others, 
hoping to trim the number of dealerships and increase sales at 
those remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	The move comes as more and more dealers have sold out to  
publicly-owned companies such as Republic Industries Inc. and 
United Auto Group. Those groups hope economies of scale will allow 
them to offer better selection, lower prices and better service. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford has made its own stab at such an arrangement. In five  
cities so far, Ford has consolidated as many as 14 stores into 
three or four big outlets. Ford owns a major stake in what it calls 
the Ford Retail Network, but a dealer or group of dealers manage 
the stores. 
</P>
<P>
	The results have been disappointing, said Art Spinella, an  
analyst with CNW Marketing Research, because automakers don't know 
how to sell cars. 
</P>
<P>
	GMRH ``is a disaster waiting to happen,'' Spinella said. ``There  
has never been an auto dealership owned by the factory that has 
ever made a dime. ... GM needs to concentrate on one thing and one 
thing only: manufacturing good product.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The move may add to dealer anger at GM that has been simmering  
for months. GM reorganized its sales division last year, cutting 
field personnel and asserting more control over a $500 million fund 
used for dealer advertising. Some dealers sued, saying GM was 
taking money from them and using it in other parts of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In a NADA survey of dealer satisfaction earlier this year, all  
of GM's divisions except Saturn ranked at the bottom. 
</P>
<P>
	GM emphasized that GMRH would be treated the same as any dealer  
and not get special favors. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that promise, Willingham said there were any number of  
ways a GMRH dealership could get a little boost, from getting more 
hot-selling models to better finance rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Willingham said if necessary, dealers would go to state  
legislatures and ask for stronger laws against factory-owned 
stores. Some states already have such laws in place. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Vaccine Reduces Pneumonia Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The first pneumonia vaccine designed for  
infants appears to sharply reduce severe childhood cases and could 
save thousands of lives worldwide, according to researchers who 
heralded a ``triumph for kids.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vaccine, which will be considered soon for approval in the  
United States, is intended to protect youngsters from a variety of 
illnesses caused by the pneumococcus bacteria. 
</P>
<P>
	Results were released Tuesday from a major study of the  
vaccine's effect on childhood pneumonia. The vaccine has already 
been shown to lower the risk of earaches, meningitis and blood 
poisoning resulting from the germ. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a triumph for kids,'' said Dr. Steven Black, who  
presented the data at an infectious-disease meeting sponsored by 
the American Society for Microbiology. 
</P>
<P>
	Around the world, pneumonia caused by pneumococcus results in an  
estimated 600,000 deaths annually. Black estimated that the vaccine 
could prevent 450,000 of them. 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, the bacteria is rarely fatal. However, it  
does account for 100 to 150 deaths each year. 
</P>
<P>
	An adult vaccine for the germ has long been available, but it  
does not work in youngsters. The new vaccine was developed by 
Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories, which paid for the testing. An advisory 
committee of the Food and Drug Administration is scheduled to meet 
Nov. 4 to consider whether to recommend its approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Black and colleagues from the Kaiser Permanente health plan  
tested the vaccine on 37,830 children in California. Half of them 
got the shots at two, four and six months, and again between 12 and 
15 months. The rest got a different experimental vaccine that has 
no effect on pneumococcus. 
</P>
<P>
	During three years of follow-up, 1,309 of the children were  
diagnosed with pneumonia. The vaccinated youngsters were one-third 
less likely to get moderately severe pneumonia that was bad enough 
to show up on X-rays, and they were 75 percent less likely to get 
severe cases, which occurred in 33 children. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier data released from the study showed that vaccinated  
youngsters were 89 percent less likely to get bacterial blood 
poisoning or meningitis. And they were about 20 percent less likely 
to have inner ear infections bad enough to require insertion of 
drain tubes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a remarkable vaccine that will have a dramatic effect,''  
said Dr. Henry Shinefield, another of the Kaiser researchers. 
</P>
<P>
	About 90 types of the bacteria cause illness. The new vaccine is  
designed to guard against seven varieties that are most common in 
children. These are also types of the bug that are frequently 
resistant to common antibiotics. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Cynthia Whitney of the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and  
Prevention noted that about one-quarter of victims of severe 
pneumococcus infections in the United States have bacteria that are 
resistant to penicillin, and nearly 15 percent are impervious to at 
least three drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	She noted that the new vaccine makes youngsters less likely to  
carry and spread the bacteria. This could reduce the spread of the 
bacteria even to adults who are not vaccinated. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no question that for severe pneumococcal disease,  
this vaccine is excellent,'' said Dr. Edward Janoff of the 
University of Minnesota. ``It would be hard to get one better. For 
less serious disease, such as ear infections, it is less 
effective.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another study on 1,662 children, conducted by Dr. Juhani Eskola  
and others from the National Public Health Institute in Finland, 
looked at the risk of earaches caused by the varieties of 
pneumococcus bacteria specifically covered by the vaccine. The 
shots reduced the number of these episodes by 57 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 12:40:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Offers $65B Health Care Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Drawing lessons from his father's experience  
with a painful spinal disorder, Democratic presidential candidate 
Bill Bradley offered a $65 billion plan today for universal access 
to health insurance that would require coverage for all children, 
with subsidies for families that cannot afford it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every American deserves what my father got -- the helping hands  
to a productive life,'' Bradley said, outlining the proposal in Los 
Angeles. Under Bradley's plan, individuals of all ages and incomes 
also would be able to exclude from their taxable income whatever 
they pay for health premiums. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it comes to America's health, this is not the time to be  
timid,'' said the former U.S. senator from New Jersey. ``It 
requires bold action and a national commitment from the president 
on down to make certain that every American has what should be a 
basic birthright.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daring in his contest with Vice President Al Gore to take on an  
issue doomed since the Clinton-Gore administration's first term, 
Bradley would require parents to obtain health insurance for their 
children -- much like drivers are required to buy auto insurance -- 
and would offer full or partial premium subsidies to low-income 
families. Poor adults also would be eligible for subsidies. 
</P>
<P>
	All adults would get the option of buying into the same health  
plan provided to members of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech at the Los Angeles Valley College, Bradley  
recalled how neighbors in his tiny Missouri home town pitched in to 
help his late father with daily routines made excruciating by 
calcified arthritis in his lower spine. 
</P>
<P>
	Rounding out his ``life-stage'' approach to health reform,  
Bradley's plan separately would expand Medicare to provide senior 
citizens with an uncapped prescription drug benefit for 
catastrophic and chronic illnesses. Medicare also would provide a 
new system of integrated medical and social services -- such as 
housekeeping and transportation -- that would cut down on 
nursing-home admissions, Bradley maintained. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can commit ourselves to the proposition that, when it comes  
to health care, everyone will have the American dream,'' Bradley 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said the plan's estimated annual cost of between $55  
billion and $65 billion would be paid for out of the projected 
federal budget surplus, leaving the Social Security trust fund's 
surplus protected and reserved for the retirement program. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley took a veiled swipe at Gore, his only rival for the  
Democratic nomination, who has not yet provided cost estimates for 
any of his major policy proposals, including a narrower plan for 
health coverage of all children by 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore aides have promised that such costs -- and how to pay them --  
will later be revealed in the context of a balanced budget. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bradley said today: ``I believe it is irresponsible to  
commit to new programs without also laying the costs before the 
public so that we can decide together how to pay for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore policy adviser Elaine Kamarck alternately blasted Bradley's  
plan as ``wildly unrealistic'' and ``wildly expensive.'' She 
singled out the proposal for tax deduction for premium costs: 
``You're talking about giving Donald Trump tax deductions for his 
insurance premiums.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kamarck also said Bradley's plan does nothing to fortify the  
solvency of Medicare. ``No place in there does he have Medicare 
protection. You need to lay aside a big chunk of money at the 
get-go for Medicare,'' Kamarck said. 
</P>
<P>
	With his long-promised health plan, Bradley was fleshing out  
what he's called his ``big ideas'' policy agenda at a time when 
polls suggest a tightening race against Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	And, as if to guard against association with first lady Hillary  
Rodham Clinton's unpopular and bureaucratic plan in 1993 for 
universal health care, Bradley emphasized that his proposal would 
not change the private health insurance system. 
</P>
<P>
	``For those who are now insured and satisfied with their plans,  
nothing will change,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley noted that an estimated 45 million Americans are  
uninsured -- 34 million of them adults without access to affordable 
health coverage -- and suggested the administration was at fault for 
being too easily scared away from the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that making health care available to all will not be  
easy. But the difficulty is a challenge not a reason to avoid 
engagement,'' Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	He drew important political praise from the 1.3 million-member  
Service Employees International Union, the nation's largest union 
of health care workers. SEIU president Andrew Stern, whose 
endorsement Bradley is courting, called the plan a ``serious 
proposal'' and one that is ``particularly welcome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, in addition to expanding eligibility for the Children's  
Health Insurance Program for low-income families, has proposed 
giving senior citizens and self-employed people a 25 percent 
refundable tax credit for health insurance premiums if they do not 
have employer-based coverage. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 16:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Takes Pass on Buchanan Book </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole  
sidestepped a pointed question Tuesday on Pat Buchanan's views on 
World War II. But neither does he plan to buy Buchanan's book, he 
told a Senate hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole, the 1996 Republican presidential nominee, was testifying  
before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on Balkans policy. 
</P>
<P>
	After Dole said he believed Kosovo should be independent of  
Yugoslavia, Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., asked whether he also 
believed Montenegro should seek self-determination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Should that be our policy?'' Smith asked.  
</P>
<P>
	``Well, that would be my policy,'' Dole said. ``I don't know  
whether it would be 'our' policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't speak -- I don't belong to any organized group anymore.  
I'm a Republican,'' Dole said, paraphrasing humorist Will Rogers' 
famed comment about the Democratic party. ``And I'm not in the 
Senate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``As a Republican, do you share my view that it was OK to stand  
up to Adolph Hitler?'' Smith asked. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a clear reference to the controversy surrounding  
Buchanan's views on America's entry into World War II, spelled out 
in his book, ``A Republic, Not an Empire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole chuckled at the question.  
</P>
<P>
	``Well, yes,'' he said. ``I thought World War II was a fairly  
noble cause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Dole, a World War II Army veteran who was severely wounded  
in Italy, added: ``You know, I haven't read anyone's book so I 
can't really comment on it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Interrupted Smith: ``I haven't read it either. But I don't like  
what I've heard, read, of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``And I don't want to buy it,'' Dole said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
