<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Classified Marketplace Urged on Web </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A joint classified advertising service on the  
Internet should be the next venture for newspapers, says the 
chairman of the Newspaper Association of America. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am issuing a call to all newspaper owners and publishers.  
Let us put our classified advertising online and build a national 
classified marketplace,'' William S. Morris III said Tuesday in a 
speech at the National Press Club. 
</P>
<P>
	``Classified is where we are most vulnerable to new competitors,  
and conversely, where major opportunity awaits us,'' said Morris, 
chairman of Morris Communications Group, which publishes 31 daily 
newspapers, 11 nondailies, 17 shoppers and 13 magazines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let us offer the New Jersey computer user the opportunity to  
view homes for sale in Colorado,'' he said. ``Let us enable the 
unemployed auto worker in Flint, Mich., to scan employment 
opportunities in the Sun Belt. 
</P>
<P>
	``Imagine the commercial marketplace we will create by combining  
the new technology with our traditional classified pages,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Newspaper Association of America represents more than 2,000  
newspapers in the United States and Canada, most of which are daily 
newspapers and account for 87 percent of U.S. daily circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris' recommendation comes as more and more newspapers are  
taking advantage of online technology. Thousands of papers now have 
online editions; some even have separate staffs to produce online 
stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Already, more than 750 newspapers publish classified ads on  
their individual Web sites, Morris said. Some individual newspapers 
have formed limited alliances to compete nationally. And the NAA 
has already trademarked a classified symbol to help viewers and 
readers quickly recognize classified advertisements that originate 
with a daily newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans are ready for a national classified advertising  
service, Morris said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Think about it. We have the ads. We are the portals. We have  
the public trust and brand recognition. We have the technology and 
the technical standards,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris said that while he was urging newspaper executives to  
join the effort, ``there is no way I can enforce anything on the 
Web.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is very much a work in progress,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite advances on the Internet, Morris says he doesn't  
envision newspapers becoming extinct. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see nothing in the new technology -- nothing coming out of  
Silicon Valley that eliminates the need for newspapers and 
certainly for trained, responsible, ethical and aggressive 
journalists,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
