<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YOUNG SPENDERS: People aged 12 to 22 believe in saving for the  
future, but relatively few are actually doing it, according to a 
survey conducted for Phoenix Home Life Mutual Insurance Co. The 
survey of 1,176 students nationwide found 91 percent believe young 
people should save. But 56 percent said they consider themselves to 
be spenders rather than savers. One reason why many may not worry 
about putting money aside is they're optimistic about being 
prosperous as adults -- half said they expect to be wealthier than 
their parents, but only 15 percent said they expect to have to work 
harder than their parents. 

</P>
<P>
	PULLING UP STAKES: With jobs more plentiful these days, many  
out-of-work executives are more willing to take a chance and move 
to another city for a new job, reports Challenger, Gray &AMP; 
Christmas, an employment consulting firm. Challenger Gray found in 
a survey that nearly a third, or 31 percent, of discharged 
executives who had earned $100,000 in their former jobs moved for 
the next position they found. That's a change from the past, when 
many executives were worried about leaving a community or area 
where they had established business contacts, the company said. The 
availability of jobs for their spouses has also made many 
executives willing to take on the risks of relocating. 

</P>
<P>
	IT LOOKS SO EASY: That's what a lot of people think when they  
see the proliferation of Web sites where people sell goods and 
services. But according to Inc. magazine, there are a lot of 
potential legal problems that would-be Internet entrepreneurs need 
to be aware of. For example, the magazine reports in its October 
issue, one Internet company ran into trouble with competitors after 
inserting their names into coding that helps the company's site to 
be picked up by online search engines. Linking one company's site 
to another's can cause problems if there's no agreement between the 
two sides over how it's done. And many sites have found themselves 
vulnerable to copyright infringement because the material on their 
Web pages hasn't been registered with the government. Inc. suggests 
Web site operators be sure they're complying with federal and state 
laws before getting started. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
