<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 08:35:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Lawyers Lay Out Pinochet Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Gen. Augusto Pinochet is not to blame for torture  
and disappearances that occurred under his regime, his lawyers are 
contending in their bid to prevent his extradition to Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	``His hand is not on these deeds,'' Pinochet's lead attorney,  
Clive Nicholls, said during the opening day of the long-delayed 
extradition hearing Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholls is to present his full arguments today.  
</P>
<P>
	The 83-year-old general, under arrest in Britain since last  
October, is accused by Spanish judge Baltsar Garzon of heading a 
regime that used torture to silence and intimidate opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chilean government has acknowledged that 3,197 people died  
in the years after Pinochet ousted elected Marxist President 
Salvador Allende in a 1973 coup. The campaign of terror allegedly 
continued until Pinochet relinquished power in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Garzon -- who initially had been investigating the alleged deaths  
of Spanish citizens under Pinochet's regime -- wants to extradite 
the former dictator to Spain to stand trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet faces charges including 34 counts of specific incidents  
of torture against Chileans dating from December 1988 to December 
1989, and one count of ongoing conspiracy to commit torture. 
</P>
<P>
	Alun Jones, a British lawyer who is representing Spain, said the  
conspiracy count encompasses not only the 1,198 people who 
allegedly disappeared during Pinochet's rule but also their 
families who continue to suffer from their disappearance. 
</P>
<P>
	He read a letter in court from a 73-year-old Chilean woman whose  
five family members disappeared in April 1976. It read: ``For 23 
years I've suffered the torture of not knowing what happened to 
them ... we desperately need to find our families -- even if just 
their remains.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones outlined the 34 torture allegations, saying many of the  
victims were subjected to beatings and electrical shocks and 
deprived of food and sleep. And he argued that the disappearances 
have caused ongoing mental torture for surviving relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	While the lawyers for Spain spent considerable time Monday  
outlining the allegations against Pinochet, they are not required 
to submit evidence. An extradition hearing is primarily a legal 
formality, where extradition law and issues of jurisdiction take 
precedence. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholls, Pinochet's lawyer, said that constrained the general's  
defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a sense, Sen. Pinochet is before you today with his hands  
tied behind his back,'' said Nicholls. 
</P>
<P>
	The case against Pinochet has already proved to be a legal  
minefield. Aspects of it have been considered again and again by 
Britain's highest courts. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, the House of Lords threw out all but the charges of  
torture and conspiracy to torture after Dec. 1988 -- when Britain 
adopted an international law making torture a crime that can be 
prosecuted anywhere. In throwing out the pre-1988 charges, the 
House of Lords dismissed all the allegations involving Spanish 
citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholls said he would attempt to show today that Spain has no  
jurisdiction because no Spanish citizens are now involved, that 
there is no evidence linking Pinochet to the alleged crimes and 
that the charges are politically motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	If Deputy Chief Magistrate Ronald Bartle rules against Pinochet,  
the general's lawyers can appeal. And after all legal options are 
exhausted, the case would return to Home Secretary Jack Straw for a 
final ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet, who is not attending the hearing, remains defiant.  
</P>
<P>
	In a statement read to the court in April, Pinochet declared,  
``I do not agree with this ... I have nothing to do with any of 
these charges .... I am being humiliated. I am a general with 64 
years service and I am a gentleman who knows about honor.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
