<HEADLINE> Steelers Rookie Zereoue Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Pittsburgh Steelers rookie Amos Zereoue was  
charged with drunken driving early Tuesday and released into the 
custody of teammate Pete Gonzalez, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brentwood police chief George Swinney said Zereoue was stopped  
at about 2 a.m. after an officer saw his GMC Yukon fail to stop at 
a stop sign in Brentwood, a suburb a few miles southeast of 
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	As patrolman William Meisel spoke with Zereoue, he smelled  
alcohol on the player's breath and asked him to perform a field 
sobriety test. The running back failed, Swinney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Zereoue, a running back, was taken to Jefferson Hospital for a  
blood test and charged with drunken driving, pending the results of 
the blood analysis. Test results from the Allegheny County Crime 
lab are expected in about a week. 
</P>
<P>
	Zereoue, a third-round draft pick from West Virginia, was  
released on his own recognizance into the custody of Gonzalez, a 
third-string quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	Steelers coach Bill Cowher refused comment on Zereoue's arrest.  
</P>
<P>
	Swinney said Meisel's report gave no indication of any problem  
during Zereoue's arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	``It didn't matter who he was. It's just a normal DUI arrest for  
us,'' Swinney said. ``It was nothing out of the ordinary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, black motorist Jonny Gammage, a cousin of former  
Steeler Ray Seals, died in a struggle with officers from Brentwood 
and neighboring Whitehall following a traffic stop. The officers, 
who were white, were charged but not convicted in Gammage's death, 
which raised concerns that Gammage had been targeted because of his 
race. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
