<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Status of Congress Spending Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Status of the 13 spending bills for fiscal 2000, which begins  
Oct. 1: 
</P>
<P>
	--Agriculture: $70 billion total. House-Senate bargainers seemed  
near resolution of differences over lifting some trade sanctions 
with Cuba and whether to change federal milk pricing rules. 
</P>
<P>
	--Commerce, Justice, State: $38 billion. House-Senate negotiators  
seeking compromise. It faces a veto threat because it cuts 
President Clinton's proposals for hiring new police officers, civil 
rights enforcement, other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	--Defense: Nearly $270 billion. House-Senate bargainers still  
divided over whether Air Force should be allowed to purchase F-22 
stealth fighters. 
</P>
<P>
	--District of Columbia: $429 million in federal funds. Approved  
by Congress. Veto expected because of ban on providing hypodermic 
needles for drug addicts, other restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	--Energy and Water: $21 billion. Final congressional approval  
voted Tuesday by the Senate. Removal of language helping developers 
trying to build on wetlands means Clinton signature likely, despite 
earlier veto threat. 
</P>
<P>
	--Foreign aid: $13 billion. House-Senate bargainers agreed to  
comomise Monday night. Clinton veto likely because it cuts his 
request by $2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Interior: $14 billion. House-Senate bargainers haven't  
completed compromise. Veto threat because of cuts in his proposals 
for land purchases, plus provisions helping oil and mining 
companies using federal lands. 
</P>
<P>
	--Labor, health, education: About $320 billion. Approved by House  
and Senate subcommittees. Veto threat because of cuts in Clinton 
plans for hiring teachers, workplace safety, other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	--Legislative branch: $2.5 billion. Sent to Clinton, signature  
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	--Military construction: $8.4 billion. Signed into law Aug. 17.  
</P>
<P>
	--Transportation: $51 billion. House-Senate bargainers seeking  
compromise amid internal GOP fights on whether to return some 
gasoline tax revenue to states. 
</P>
<P>
	--Treasury: $28 billion. Sent to Clinton, signature expected.  
</P>
<P>
	--Veterans, housing, environment: $97 billion. House-Senate  
bargainers seeking agreement. Veto threat because of cuts in 
Clinton proposals for public housing, environment, NASA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
