<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grenade Kills Two in Kosovo Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Attackers fired two rifle-propelled  
grenades into a suburban market packed with shoppers today, killing 
two Serbs and injuring 39 other people, NATO said. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack occurred in the outdoor market in Kosovo Polje, just  
west of the provincial capital of Pristina, said Emma Salle, 
spokeswoman of Britain's Irish Guards. Several people were detained 
for questioning, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Four of the injured were said to have been gravely wounded. It  
was not know who fired the grenades. 
</P>
<P>
	International officials also announced today that NATO  
peacekeepers have arrested nine Serbs in the past three days on 
suspicion of murder, cracking down on paramilitaries accused of 
committing atrocities against ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	Four of the Serbs were taken into custody after French  
investigators exhumed 28 bodies from a burial site just west of 
Kosovska Mitrovica, NATO said. The others were arrested by German 
and Dutch troops near the southern town of Orahovac, according to 
the U.N. war crimes tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement today, French police said the bodies of more than  
20 ethnic Albanians who disappeared during the NATO bombing 
campaign against Yugoslavia have been exhumed from the mass burial 
site in Vidomiric. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven bodies have been identified; they were among 23 ethnic  
Albanian men rounded up during a paramilitary raid in Kosovska 
Mitrovica on April 14, three weeks after the start of the 78-day 
NATO bombing campaign, the French statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Netherlands, war crimes tribunal spokesman Paul Risley  
said investigators from the U.N. court provided some of the 
evidence leading to the arrests. 
</P>
<P>
	Serb militia members are suspected of killing thousands of  
people during an 18-month crackdown that ended in June when 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic accepted a U.N.-backed peace 
plan for Kosovo and 45,000 peacekeepers to enforce it. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of ethnic Albanians whose relatives disappeared in the  
April raid gathered Monday at the library in Kosovska Mitrovica, 
where the local prosecutor announced the deaths had been confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	The French believe the victims were separated from their  
families on April 14 by Serb forces, the daily newspaper Kosova Sot 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other developments, the U.S. diplomatic office in Pristina  
also warned Americans today to be on alert to ``a potential 
terrorist threat'' against U.S. citizens, but did not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO said 100 Serbs staged a demonstration Monday in Ugljare,  
just west of Pristina, to protest the shooting of a Serb. An ethnic 
Albanian man who drove into the crowd was dragged from his car and 
severely beaten, NATO said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Belgrade, a Serb official claimed more than 300 non-Albanians  
have been killed, about 500 kidnapped and some 250,000 have fled 
Kosovo since the arrival of the international peacekeeping mission. 
</P>
<P>
	The official, Veljko Odalovic, accused the NATO-led peacekeeping  
force of siding with ethnic Albanian rebels and allowing ``Albanian 
gangs'' to roam the province. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
