<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Slightly Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar edged slightly higher against the yen  
Tuesday, continuing its rise from the day before on hopes that 
Japanese financial authorities may take steps to curb the yen's 
recent ascent. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's central bank disappointed markets last week by refusing  
to yield to pressure from its own government to inject money into 
the banking system as a way of easing interest rates and weakening 
the yen's strength against other currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	But hopes for some kind of action to rein in the yen were  
renewed after a weekend meeting in Washington, where senior 
financial officials from the Group of Seven countries said they 
shared Japan's concern over the yen's rapid rise against the 
dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	An overly strong yen could harm Japanese exporters by crimping  
the profits they earn from overseas sales. That in turn could 
threaten a nascent economic recovery in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 106.10  
Japanese yen, up from 106.00. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar fell against the euro as traders hoped that some  
emerging signs of strength in the European economy could lead the 
European Central Bank to push interest rates higher. The euro was 
quoted at $1.0554, up from $1.0468 late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5175 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5303, and 1.4613 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4703. The British 
pound rose to $1.6502 from $1.6472. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8534 German 
marks, down from 1.8680; 6.2159 French francs, down from 6.2651; 
and 1,834.63 Italian lire, down from 1,849.35. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
