<HEADLINE> Coke Produces Some Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Coca-Cola Co., which has already turned over more  
than 37,000 documents pertaining to a racial discrimination 
lawsuit, is insisting that another 93 documents should remain 
private. 
</P>
<P>
	Four current and former Coke employees are suing the company in  
federal court, alleging they were denied raises and promotions 
because they are black. The plaintiffs are seeking class-action 
status, which would cover almost all of the company's 1,500 other 
black salaried employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Company representatives said they would be willing to make 1  
million additional documents available if plaintiff attorneys wish 
to look them over. 
</P>
<P>
	But Coke reserves its right to keep 93 more documents private,  
the company said Monday. The documents involve communications 
between the company and its lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	A motion from the plaintiffs filed last month said the documents  
``likely contain evidence that senior company officials had 
knowledge of and failed to prevent ... barriers to equal employment 
opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Richard Story has yet to rule on their  
admissibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``An uninformed reader might conclude ... that Coca-Cola has  
been unreasonably stingy ... jealously guarding even the most 
fundamentally discoverable documents,'' the company said in a 
statement. ``Nothing could be further from the truth.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
