<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Brewers GM Hires David Wilder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- New Milwaukee Brewers general manager Dean  
Taylor hired Chicago Cubs executive David Wilder on Tuesday to a 
newly created position of vice president of player personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor said Wilder, who becomes the highest ranking black  
executive the Brewers have had, will be involved in ``every player 
personnel decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hiring is another move in Taylor's shakeup of the player  
development system, considered one of the team's weak spots for 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilder, 38, who knew Taylor when both with the Atlanta Braves,  
said the Brewers personnel system needs some fixing but isn't 
completely broken. 
</P>
<P>
	``This system has gone through some dry spells,'' Wilder said,  
``but the nucleus of the major league club has a lot of young, 
pretty talented players. The lack of pitching is something you have 
to address. But it's not a situation where the system is bare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor said when hired as general manager a week earlier that he  
would make improving personnel development his top priority, and he 
soon began reshaping the organization by reassigning several top 
executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilder will be the primary talent evaluator for the club at the  
major and minor league levels and will oversee scouting and player 
development, Taylor said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The system,'' Wilder said, ``is not overwhelmingly talented.  
What you need to do is to instill a sense of pride and work ethic, 
the foundation of every successful organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilder was the Cubs' farm director for three years before  
becoming assistant general manager this season. 
</P>
<P>
	An outfielder for seven seasons in the minor leagues with the  
Cubs and Oakland Athletics, Wilder retired in 1989 and began a 
career in player development. He started as a scout with Oakland 
and worked his way up by 1995 to become assistant director of 
scouting and player development for Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Major league baseball for years has been trying to get teams to  
hire more minorities in the front office, and Wilder said he's 
happy that some progress is being made. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's positive,'' Wilder said. ``I would say there are still  
too few, but I'm happy they are addressing it. We've got a lot of 
people in different positions today that they never had in the 
past. That's good. I hope I can do something that will help other 
minorities to advance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor last week demoted Fred Stanley, an assistant general  
manager who headed the player development and scouting departments, 
and Ken Califano, director of scouting. They will be offered other 
jobs with the club. 
</P>
<P>
	Cecil Cooper, the former Brewers star who was director of player  
development, was reassigned as a special assistant for player 
personnel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
