<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rules on Freelance Writers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A new court ruling is raising questions about  
compensation for freelance writers whose work appeared in 
electronic databases without their permission. 
</P>
<P>
	Copyright law ``does not permit the publishers to license  
individually copyrighted works for inclusion in the electronic 
databases,'' according to the unanimous ruling issued Friday by a 
three-judge panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals' Second Circuit in 
Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit was filed in 1993 by six writers and the National  
Writers' Union, which represents 5,000 freelance writers. The suit 
was filed against The New York Times Co., Newsday, Time Inc. 
Magazine Co., Mead Data Central Corp., and University Microfilms 
International and The Atlantic Monthly Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The authors had claimed, according to the ruling, ``that the  
copyright each owns in his or her individual articles was infringed 
when the publishers provided them to the electronic databases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the years since the lawsuit was filed, most large publishers  
have made the purchase of electronic rights, which include use of 
stories on the Web, a standard part of contracts with freelance 
writers. Typically they do not provide extra compensation for the 
electronic rights, although a big-name author might be able to 
negotiate additional fees. 
</P>
<P>
	But it is unclear what, if any, recourse might be available to  
writers whose work was purchased for publication only in a print 
format and was then later archived in an electronic format without 
express permission -- for example, in Nexis, which is comprised of 
stories from hundreds of periodicals over many years. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute applies mainly to electronic news databases such as  
Nexis, and predates the widespread use of the World Wide Web as a 
publishing medium by several years. Nexis had been owned by Mead 
Data at the time the suit was filed but is now owned by Reed 
Elsevier PLC. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to two dozen major media companies, Jonathan Tasini,  
president of the National Writers' Union, warned that the ruling 
``potentially puts your company at great financial and legal 
risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Thousands of writers are now positioned to hit the industry  
with thousands of new claims,'' Tasini said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear how the defendants will respond. ``We just got  
the decision Friday,'' said Carolyn Shurr, general counsel for 
Newsday. ``We are reviewing it and looking into our options. We 
have not decided how to proceed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One option would be to appeal the ruling, requesting that the  
decision by the three-judge panel be evaluated by the entire Second 
Circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	If the ruling is not appealed, it will be up to a lower court  
judge to decide what the plaintiffs' obligations are. The original 
lawsuit did not specify any monetary damages. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a real open question,'' said George Freeman, general  
counsel for The New York Times. ``There's no significant money 
involved with the articles'' that were written by the individual 
authors who filed the claim. 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``From The New York Times' point of view, when we  
looked at whatever evidence there is, we found the monetary value 
to be insignificant. Millions more people read the piece in The New 
York Times the day it's printed than ever read it on line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he believed researchers using electronic databases  
were more likely to want articles by staff writers than Op-Ed 
pieces or magazine articles written by freelancers, and that it 
would be very difficult for freelancers to prove that publishers 
profited from the electronic use of their material. 
</P>
<P>
	Tasini has proposed resolving the electronic rights issue  
through a collective licensing system, called the Publication 
Rights Clearinghouse, similar to the system governing royalties for 
the use of copyrighted music. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a writer you license your work to the PRC and then we make  
it available for anyone to buy it and use it legally for a fee,'' 
Tasini said. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman said he wasn't sure publishers would be interested. ``I  
don't know that the model really works for this,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-year statute of limitations pertains to copyright  
infringements. But Tasini believes there is a legal basis for 
claims going back more than three years because if they are 
available electronically, ``there is a notion of continuous 
infringement'' from the time the item was archived. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 01:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos on Wrong End of Three-Peat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Their offense has gone from superlative to  
stagnant, and the Denver Broncos' definition of a big play has 
become anything going more than 10 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Mike Shanahan is not contemplating a quarterback change  
after an 0-3 start that marks Denver's longest losing streak since 
he took over as coach in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brian Griese's our starter,'' Shanahan said Monday as he  
defended the second-year quarterback who has been given the 
unenviable task of replacing John Elway. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he's taking a lot of heat right now, but that's the  
nature of this business. What I've got to do is evaluate who I 
think is the best to go in there and execute. I've been dealing 
with the quarterbacks for a long time,'' Shanahan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of Denver's poor start, Shanahan has been vulnerable to  
criticism for his preseason decision to demote veteran quarterback 
Bubby Brister. 
</P>
<P>
	Shanahan also has been accused of being stubborn and unwilling  
to admit a mistake now that the Broncos are in last place in the 
AFC West. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope my ego is not that strong where I couldn't look at  
something and make a decision,'' he said. ``I'm doing what I think 
is best for the football team and gives us the best chance to 
win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brister, 4-0 as an emergency starter last season, did not  
comment on the quarterback situation Monday, and Griese deferred 
all questions to his Wednesday press conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Third-string quarterback Chris Miller shrugged off suggestions  
that he be given a chance to start. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't pay attention to that,'' Miller said. ``Sure, I'd love  
to be playing. We'd all like to be playing, but right now, that's 
not my role. I've just got to support Brian and keep my arm in 
shape and be ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Denver's improbable start -- the worst for a defending Super Bowl  
champion since 1987 -- has blindsided the Broncos, who play host to 
the New York Jets (0-3) on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody expected this. Everybody believes we're better than  
this,'' defensive end Harald Hasselbach said. ``I can't really come 
out and say that we are. It's up to us to show that we are. We're 
searching for the answers from within. We'll know them when we get 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Broncos have had few answers defensively, allowing 155 yards  
rushing per game. Kansas City's Kimble Anders ran for a career-high 
142 yards against them in Week 2, and Mike Alstott had a 
career-best 131 yards Sunday for Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Denver's running game has disappeared. Reigning  
league MVP Terrell Davis, who ran for 2,008 yards last year, is 
averaging 64 yards per game. 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of a running threat has prompted opponents to challenge  
Griese to beat them through the air. The results have been dismal 
as Denver has scored 41 points -- 62 fewer than through three games 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just stuck in the mud,'' fullback Howard Griffith said.  
``We need to win games. That's the bottom line. ... If we can get a 
win, it's not going to be a cure-all, but at least we have some 
positive momentum going into the next week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	History says it might be too late for the Broncos to get back in  
the race for a third straight championship. No NFL team has started 
the season 0-3 and won a divisional playoff game, let alone a Super 
Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am personally not a guy who likes to draw from history,''  
Hasselbach said. ``I believe that anything is possible. I think we 
create our own fate, so to speak. It's up to us how good we want to 
play.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 15:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL's Run in Charlotte Is Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- The Indy Racing League's foray into the  
heart of stock-car country is finished. 
</P>
<P>
	The promoter of the suburban Charlotte track where three  
spectators were killed during an IRL event in May has decided 
against bringing back the series, racing sources said Tuesday, 
speaking on the condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Speedway Motorsports Inc. had been leaning in recent weeks  
against renewing its three-year contract to hold IRL races at 
Lowe's Motor Speedway at Charlotte. The company finalized its 
decision as it draws closer to finishing plans for its 2000 
calendar. 
</P>
<P>
	SMI officials declined to discuss their decision Tuesday, saying  
they preferred that the announcement come from the IRL. The 
sanctioning body also would not speak publicly about losing the 
Charlotte race from its calendar. 
</P>
<P>
	The Charlotte stop was one of five SMI-controlled races on the  
IRL's 11-event schedule for 1999. The company's agreement to stage 
races at Charlotte expired after this year's race, but SMI still 
has pacts in place to hold events at Atlanta, Las Vegas and Texas 
motor speedways. 
</P>
<P>
	When the IRL announces its 2000 schedule in the coming weeks, it  
is expected to include two races at Texas and one each at Atlanta 
and Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL's long-term future at SMI tracks could depend on how the  
series responds to the company's concerns of car design. 
Concord-based SMI raised questions of design and safety after a 
wheel and other debris from a multicar wreck flew into the stands 
during the VisionAire 500 on May 1, killing three spectators 
instantly and injuring eight others. 
</P>
<P>
	After the accident, SMI raised the height of the safety fences  
surrounding the racing surfaces at its tracks, and the IRL slowed 
its cars and instituted a tethering system designed to keep wheels 
from flying off during crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	But SMI wants the IRL to do more, including a move to larger  
cars that would provide more protection for wheel assemblies and be 
more visible to fans. The IRL said it is studying additional 
changes but is not yet ready to commit to any. 
</P>
<P>
	The fledgling IRL came to Charlotte in 1997, hopeful of tapping  
into the passions of a region where stock-car racing was born 
decades ago and is still home to most NASCAR Winston Cup teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlotte routinely draws crowds of 170,000 for Winston Cup  
races, and SMI officials were encouraged when more than 72,000 
showed up for the inaugural IRL event at the 1.5-mile, high-banked 
superspeedway. But that number slipped to about 50,000 in 1998 and 
to less than 40,000 for this year's race, which was canceled after 
the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the accident, SMI officials had expressed concern  
about the IRL race's shrinking attendance, high promotion costs and 
low revenue stream. The fatal crash, which prompted several 
lawsuits by the families of victims, heightened those concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	In its bid to find alternate revenue sources, SMI is building  
dirt tracks of about four-tenths of a mile in length at Charlotte 
and Texas and will begin holding World of Outlaws races on the 
tracks next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL also is looking elsewhere. The league's 2000 schedule is  
expected to include new races in Nazareth, Pa., and Covington, Ky. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 08:03:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Hires 1st Science Adviser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department hired its first chief  
science adviser Monday -- Donald Prosnitz, a physicist from the 
Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in California. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosnitz will be on a two-year detail as the department's chief  
science and technology adviser from the lab where he was the chief 
scientist for the Nonproliferation, Arms Control and International 
Security Directorate. 
</P>
<P>
	``This newly created post enables us to consolidate the  
responsibility for technology policy in one position,'' Attorney 
General Janet Reno said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosnitz is the second physicist drawn from the Energy  
Department's nuclear weapons laboratories to take a top Justice 
Department job. By coincidence, the laboratories currently are a 
focus of an FBI investigation into whether China stole secrets 
about U.S. nuclear warheads in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	In October 1997, Donald M. Kerr Jr., a physicist-engineer who  
spent six years as chief of the government's Los Alamos National 
Laboratory, where nuclear weapons were designed, became assistant 
FBI director in charge of the bureau's crime laboratory. 
</P>
<P>
	In a brief interview, Prosnitz said ``familiarity with the  
government'' might be the reason Justice has twice turned to the 
national laboratories for a scientist. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosnitz will advise Reno on research, development, procurement  
and legislation relating to technological issues like computer 
crime or the use of DNA evidence. Indeed, his first task was to 
attend a meeting of the department's advisory Commission on the 
Future of DNA Evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	He also will serve as the department's liaison to the scientific  
community. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dr. Prosnitz's wealth of education, experience and management  
in the scientific community make him the right person for the 
job,'' Reno said. ``He is well-suited to coordinate the Justice 
Department's efforts on complex and novel technological issues such 
as investigating computer crimes and threats to our critical 
infrastructure, the use of DNA evidence and forensic analysis 
issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was graduated from Yale University with a degree in  
engineering and applied science in 1970 and received his doctorate 
in physics from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1975. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 06:10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Troubled Japanese Bank To Be Sold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- An international investment group plans to acquire  
debt-laden Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan Ltd. in what would be the 
first foreign acquisition of a major Japanese bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal disclosed today represents a step forward in the  
government's efforts to clean up loan problems that has suffocated 
the banking industry since Japanese property prices collapsed in 
the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Reconstruction Commission announced it had  
approved the deal, and that the investment group organized by the 
private U.S. equity firm Ripplewood Holdings LLC had signed a 
memorandum of understanding on the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripplewood, based in New York City, has specialized in buying  
struggling small-to-midsize companies and making them profitable. 
It hopes to reach a final deal for LTCB by the end of November. 
</P>
<P>
	Other proposed investors in the New LTCB include GE Capital  
Corp., Mellon Bank Corp., ABN-Amro Bank, PaineWebber Group and 
Deutsche Bank. Former U.S. Federal Reserve chairman Paul Volcker is 
a senior advisor to the group. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese companies like Chuo Trust and Banking Co. and Mitsui  
Trust and Banking Co. had been in the running to acquire LTCB. 
</P>
<P>
	LTCB, once one of Japan's biggest banks, was nationalized last  
October after regulators determined it would never recover from a 
mountain of bad loans. It was the first time the Japanese 
government had taken over a bank since World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to restore LTCB to its former status as a premier  
financial institution as quickly as possible, so it can contribute 
to the financial stability of Japan,'' said LTCB's new chairman and 
chief executive, Masamoto Yashiro. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese government will inject $2.26 billion into a  
reformed LTCB on condition that the Ripplewood group continue loans 
to the bank's troubled borrowers, according to an FCR official who 
briefed reporters on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The new owners will acquire LTCB shares by paying $9.43 million  
to the Deposit Insurance Corp., the Japanese government finance 
body which is now LTCB's sole shareholder, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yashiro, formerly a non-executive chairman of Citicorp Japan,  
said that the new bank will try to expand its individual and 
corporate business. It will remain a Japanese-oriented bank in the 
initial years, Yashiro said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said eight of the 15 top board members are expected to be  
Japanese ``because they would understand the Japanese market 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Timothy Collins, founder of Ripplewood who will join LTCB's  
board, said he hoped to play a role in Japan's economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins said that although there are structural problems in  
Japan's economy, he wanted to ``find an area to restructure the 
Japanese economy and provide strategic advice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the deal was likely to have a positive impact on  
Japan's inefficient banking industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ripplewood will take it through restructuring you haven't seen  
here, and there will be big pressure on others to follow suit,'' 
said James Fiorillo, a banking analyst at ING Barings in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	FRC chief Hakuo Yanagisawa welcomed the deal. ``Japanese  
financial institutions are far worse than Western counterparts in 
profitability,'' he said. ``New LTCB made it clear they will focus 
on fixing this problem. We hope this will become reality and affect 
(other Japanese financial institutions) positively.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LTCB and the Ripplewood group hope to reach a final agreement by  
Nov. 30, and the government may extend the period if needed. 
</P>
<P>
	The FRC, a Japanese government body overseeing banking industry  
reform, has been discussing LTCB's transfer since the middle of 
this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale is likely to speed up the process of opening Japan's  
financial industry to foreign firms, a pillar of the country's 
financial reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shows the government's commitment to creating a level  
playing field, and that it and won't even let nationalism get in 
the way of what needs to be done,'' ING Barings' Fiorillo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of LTCB's bad debt was the result of aggressive lending to  
real estate developers before property prices in Japan collapsed in 
the early 1990s. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 08:16:24 </DATE_TIME>
