<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 16:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Uremovich Glad To Be Back With Tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- When Matt Uremovich compared himself to other  
college linebackers, he was overwhelmed by the desire to get bigger 
and stronger. 
</P>
<P>
	Barely 200 pounds, he felt out of place. Impatient, he didn't  
want to take the time to put on the extra weight through 
conventional methods. So, he purchased a muscle-building supplement 
banned by the NCAA and hoped he wouldn't get caught. 
</P>
<P>
	He was.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was all a mental thing,'' said Uremovich, who is back at  
middle linebacker for No. 9 Georgia Tech after being suspended for 
nearly a year. ``It's how you play and how hard you play, not how 
much you weigh. Ten pounds is not going to make or break you. It 
was just a stupid mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a redshirt freshman, Uremovich earned a starting role at  
outside linebacker and had the best game of his career last Oct. 
10, a 10-tackle performance against North Carolina State. 
</P>
<P>
	Four days later, he was suspended for testing positive for an  
over-the-counter substance similar to androstenedione, the 
supplement made famous by Mark McGwire. 
</P>
<P>
	Uremovich missed the final seven games of Georgia Tech's 10-2  
season, and also was forced to sit out the first two games this 
year. He finally returned for Tech's 41-10 victory over Central 
Florida, starting at middle linebacker, calling the defensive 
signals and making eight tackles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a long time coming,'' he said. ``It felt good to get  
out there. The first two weeks of this season felt almost as long 
as the seven games I missed last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even though McGwire was breaking home run records while using  
andro, a substance legal in baseball, Uremovich doesn't feel 
victimized by a double standard. He took a chance and got caught. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a rule and you can't break the rules,'' he said. ``I paid  
the price for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach George O'Leary was furious at Uremovich for using a banned  
substance, especially when two other Tech players had already been 
suspended for similar offenses prior to last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, it's a lesson learned in life,'' O'Leary said. ``I  
had his parents in and we talked about taking shortcuts in life. 
Eventually, it's going to get you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Uremovich was forthright with his coaches, who encouraged him to  
use the suspension time to improve his strength in the weight room 
and devote more time to academics. He now weighs 225 pounds and 
made the dean's list two quarters in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to make the most of every game, every practice, every  
day,'' Uremovich said. ``You never know when it's all going to be 
over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Leary noticed that newfound maturity and demonstrated his  
faith in Uremovich by starting him in his first game back, 
providing the extra responsibility of calling signals. 
</P>
<P>
	``That meant a lot,'' Uremovich said. ``They want me to show  
some leadership and I'm trying to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the extra weight, Uremovich still looks a bit  
undersized to play such a physically demanding position as middle 
linebacker. But he fits right in with the Grim Reaper tattoo on his 
right arm and a seemingly perpetual cut on the bridge of his nose, 
caused by his helmet tending to slip down on his head while making 
tackles. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not a very big guy, but he plays like he's 260 pounds.  
He's an animal on the field,'' said tight end Conrad Andrzejewski, 
who practiced against Uremovich when he was on the scout team. 
``It's not fun to hit him. He has a hard head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Uremovich's pedal-to-the-floor style has been compared to Keith  
Brooking, a former Tech linebacker who now starts for the Atlanta 
Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was definitely an idol to me,'' said Uremovich, who was  
redshirted while Brooking played his final year at Tech. ``As far 
as me being him, there's not much comparison. He's an unbelievable 
athlete. If I'm half the player he was, I'll have a pretty good 
career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At this point, Uremovich lacks the rare combination of size and  
speed that made Brooking so special. Intensity-wise, they're 
impossible to distinguish. 
</P>
<P>
	``Keith was special as far as the speed he had,'' O'Leary said.  
``Matt is going to get better and better, but that's the thing 
separating those guys right now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 16:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Says Chargers End Assaulted Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Police are investigating a 23-year-old man's  
claim that San Diego Chargers defensive end Chris Mims hit him 
twice with his belt and stole his food following a verbal 
confrontation outside a downtown taco shop early Monday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Mims left the scene before officers arrived and hadn't yet been  
contacted by police, spokesman Bill Robinson said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Police were called to a Del Taco at about 2:40 a.m. Monday, some  
10 hours after the Chargers lost their home opener, 27-19 to the 
Indianapolis Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael J. McKinney told police that Mims threatened him, shoved  
his head into a wall, took his four tacos and then chased him, 
striking him twice with his belt. 
</P>
<P>
	Police likely will talk again with McKinney and a Del Taco  
employee, who recognized Mims as being a member of the Chargers, 
before deciding whether to send the case either to the city 
attorney or district attorney, Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chargers players had Tuesday off and Mims, the team's  
first-round draft pick in 1992, was not available for comment. 
General manager Bobby Beathard was on a scouting trip and Mims' 
agent didn't immediately return a phone call seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Del Taco employee Rasean Johnson told police that a black  
limousine pulled up to the drive-through window and Mims got out 
and started urinating in the parking lot. 
</P>
<P>
	McKinney, who was at a walk-up window, said something to Mims,  
who then came over and said: ``I'll beat you with my belt,'' the 
police report said. McKinney told police he tried to ignore Mims, 
but was attacked. 
</P>
<P>
	McKinney sustained bruises and welts on the left side and back  
of his neck from being struck with a belt, and had small cuts on 
his lower lip, left side and the back of his right hand, the report 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson told KGTV that Mims said to McKinney: ``I'm going to  
keep your damn tacos.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a million dollar man right here, who gets a nice  
paycheck, taking this man's $2 tacos,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mims, in his second stint with the Chargers, makes the league  
minimum of $400,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Mims battled his weight and had legal and financial problems off  
the field during his first five seasons with the Chargers. He was 
released in April 1997 and signed by the Washington Redskins. The 
Chargers re-signed him in June 1998, and he's been a reserve ever 
since. 
</P>
<P>
	After the 1995 season ended with a 35-20 home playoff loss to  
the Colts on New Year's Eve, Mims showed up almost an hour late to 
the team's final meeting the next morning, emerging disheveled from 
a limousine. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 15:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Tigers Outfielder Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Former Detroit Tigers outfielder Ron LeFlore on  
Tuesday avoided 45 days in jail on charges he failed to make child 
support payments. 
</P>
<P>
	LeFlore was arrested Monday after Tiger Stadium's closing  
ceremonies on charges he failed to pay more than $50,000 in back 
child support to DeBorah Lewis of Detroit. He was ordered to pay 
$3,000 or go to jail. 
</P>
<P>
	``He evidently paid it or made arrangements for payment,'' a  
spokesman from the Wayne County Sheriffs Department said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 51-year-old LeFlore has been living in St. Petersburg, Fla.  
He returned to Michigan to take part in the events surrounding the 
last game at Tiger Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	His adopted son and nephew, Gerald LeFlore, said his father has  
paid $300 a month in Florida for at least a year. Ron LeFlore also 
made lump sum payments after various court orders, but Judge Mary 
Beth Kelly ruled that LeFlore still owed Lewis about $52,000 to 
$56,000 for their daughter, LaRonda LeFlore, now 23. 
</P>
<P>
	LeFlore testified that his only source of income is a $20,000  
major league pension. He also said that he has a wife and two other 
children to support, and he has problems with a hip and knee. 
</P>
<P>
	David J. Allen, the lawyer representing LeFlore on Tuesday, said  
the numbers still need to be reviewed. 
</P>
<P>
	``He recognizes that there's an arrears, whether it's that  
amount is questionable,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen said LeFlore's attorney in Florida will examine the  
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis said she was upset by the possibility he could be freed  
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's some crock again,'' she said. ``This man makes money  
signing autographs. He'll pay the money, and he'll be gone again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LeFlore family friend and former publicist Jack Taylor said he  
was ``disgusted'' by the ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``This whole situation was created by a lack of communication  
and correlation of facts and figures,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The court decision extends Lewis' fight to get money from her  
former common-law husband. The two have been apart since 
Thanksgiving 1977, Lewis said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been chasing him ever since he left Michigan,'' she said.  
``All I ask is, `Take care of your kids.''' 
</P>
<P>
	LeFlore was considered one of baseball's best baserunners when  
he played with the Tigers from 1974-79. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis said she called the Wayne County Sheriff's Department on  
Monday to tell them LeFlore would be attending Tiger Stadium's 
closing ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	He was named in a Wayne County Circuit Court bench warrant in  
1993, Wayne County Sheriff Robert Ficano said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis works as a mechanical engineer. Her daughter has been  
working as a bank teller, but she said she wants to finish college. 
LaRonda LeFlore said she still has about $4,000 in loans to pay 
off. 
</P>
<P>
	``My mom raised me and sent me to private school by herself,''  
LaRonda LeFlore said. ``I feel he should've paid something. I feel 
a father should be willing to take care of his kids if he's willing 
to have them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About six years ago, LaRonda LeFlore said, her father didn't  
recognize her when he walked into the Woolworth's where she was 
working. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't know who I was,'' she said. ``I tapped him on the  
shoulder and told him my name. His eyes bugged open. He was 
surprised.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LaRonda LeFlore said she has a 1-year-old son whom her father  
has never seen. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron LeFlore's wife, Emily, also sat in the courtroom but  
declined to talk to reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	She, LeFlore's mother, and Gerald LeFlore were all present when  
LeFlore was arrested at the stadium Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``My grandmother was really torn up,'' Gerald LeFlore said.  
``She was crying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before joining the Tigers in 1974, Ron LeFlore served time in  
prison for armed robbery. His story was the basis for a movie, 
``One In A Million'' in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1973, then-Tigers manager Billy Martin heard about a young  
man playing on the ball team in the Southern Michigan Prison in 
Jackson. He went and watched him play a couple times and urged the 
Tigers to sign him. LeFlore went to Detroit Eastern High School, 
but didn't play ball before prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Once he was paroled, he signed with the Tigers and jumped from  
Class A to the major leagues in less than two seasons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
