<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Confidence Fell in Sept. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consumer confidence slipped in September for the  
third consecutive month, and by much more than analysts had 
expected, suggesting that the Federal Reserve's 
higher-interest-rate strategy is cooling off the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board said today that its index of consumer  
confidence, which is a measure of consumer's willingness to spend, 
dipped to 134.2 in September, down 1.8 percentage points from a 
revised 136 in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had forecast that September's reading would be 135.4.  
</P>
<P>
	Economists noted, however, that the latest level still was not  
far below the June reading of 139, which was the strongest in more 
than 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite the September dip, confidence levels are still at  
historically high levels,'' said Lynn Franco, director of the 
Conference Board's consumer research center. 
</P>
<P>
	``The latest figure is only five points off the June reading,  
with consumer generally optimistic about both the economy and job 
prospects. We anticipate no dramatic shifts soon in consumer 
spending patterns,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve has twice this year raised interest rates to  
try to keep the economy from overheating and to head off a 
resurgence of inflation. Fed policy-makers meet next on Oct. 5, and 
some economists are not ruling out a further increase if retail 
sales continue to show the strength they have in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer sentiment is an important economic indicator since  
consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the nation's overall 
economic activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board's report, which is based on a sample of  
5,000 American households, said consumer expectations about the 
future also weakened in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The index of expectations slipped to 105.7 this month from 109.2  
in August and was the lowest reading since March's 105.5. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 7.1 percent of respondents said they expected business  
conditions to worsen in the next six months, while 16.4 percent 
expected them to improve. The rest said they expected no change. 
</P>
<P>
	Those figures were more pessimistic than in August. Employment  
expectations also declined. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey by the Conference Board, a business-financed research  
group, uses a baseline of 100, set in 1985. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
