<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dealers See Threat in New GM Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. said Tuesday it has set up  
an independent subsidiary to own and operate dealerships across the 
country -- a move the head of a national dealers' association vowed 
to fight. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said the company, General Motors Retail Holdings, would buy  
or partner with dealerships in the largest 130 markets across the 
country, and could own from 5 percent to 10 percent of GM's 7,700 
dealerships in 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	A GM executive said the new arrangement was the best way for GM  
to get closer to customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is critical to GM's future competitiveness that we improve  
our market performance where we lag, enhance our revenues, 
understand our customers better and look for ways to reduce 
distribution costs and improve the customer's buying experience,'' 
said Roy S. Roberts, group vice president of GM North American 
Vehicle Sales, Service and Marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	But the chairman of the National Automobile Dealers Association  
said the move was ``a huge threat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think its terrible,'' said James Willingham, who owns two GM  
dealerships in California. ``This announcement was made without any 
consultation of dealers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GMRH is the latest in a series of moves by GM and Ford Motor Co.  
aimed at improving how their vehicles are sold. In recent years the 
automakers have bought out some dealers and consolidated others, 
hoping to trim the number of dealerships and increase sales at 
those remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	The move comes as more and more dealers have sold out to  
publicly-owned companies such as Republic Industries Inc. and 
United Auto Group. Those groups hope economies of scale will allow 
them to offer better selection, lower prices and better service. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford has made its own stab at such an arrangement. In five  
cities so far, Ford has consolidated as many as 14 stores into 
three or four big outlets. Ford owns a major stake in what it calls 
the Ford Retail Network, but a dealer or group of dealers manage 
the stores. 
</P>
<P>
	The results have been disappointing, said Art Spinella, an  
analyst with CNW Marketing Research, because automakers don't know 
how to sell cars. 
</P>
<P>
	GMRH ``is a disaster waiting to happen,'' Spinella said. ``There  
has never been an auto dealership owned by the factory that has 
ever made a dime. ... GM needs to concentrate on one thing and one 
thing only: manufacturing good product.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The move may add to dealer anger at GM that has been simmering  
for months. GM reorganized its sales division last year, cutting 
field personnel and asserting more control over a $500 million fund 
used for dealer advertising. Some dealers sued, saying GM was 
taking money from them and using it in other parts of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In a NADA survey of dealer satisfaction earlier this year, all  
of GM's divisions except Saturn ranked at the bottom. 
</P>
<P>
	GM emphasized that GMRH would be treated the same as any dealer  
and not get special favors. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that promise, Willingham said there were any number of  
ways a GMRH dealership could get a little boost, from getting more 
hot-selling models to better finance rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Willingham said if necessary, dealers would go to state  
legislatures and ask for stronger laws against factory-owned 
stores. Some states already have such laws in place. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
