<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Medicare Reference Books Coming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new guidebook the government is mailing out  
this fall to all 39 million Medicare beneficiaries has prompted a 
flood of questions from senior citizens and the disabled about 
their health care choices. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of weekly calls to Medicare's national toll-free help  
line has quadrupled to 20,000 since the first batch of guides were 
mailed out Sept. 15, according to the program's director of 
beneficiary services, Carol Cronin. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect that will probably continue to increase as more  
beneficiaries get their handbook,'' Cronin said, adding that the 
deluge of calls was no surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is our first comprehensive effort to get information to  
beneficiaries to help them make decisions,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new guides are similar to Medicare handbooks that in the  
past have been sent to those newly eligible to the national health 
insurance program and available to others upon request. 
</P>
<P>
	But this year, Medicare is sending them to 32 million households  
in an attempt to reach all 39 million Medicare beneficiaries 
nationwide. From now on, the massive mailing will be an annual fall 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	Also for the first time, the guidebooks come in 26 different  
regional editions, offering specific information about the private 
health plans open to Medicare beneficiaries in each state. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls to the help line have included many requests for more  
details about such health plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The new information campaign, which cost $133 million this year,  
was required by Congress in 1997 legislation aimed at encouraging 
more Medicare beneficiaries to enroll in private health plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The government can save money when senior citizens choose  
private plans -- mainly HMOs -- that accept a flat, monthly 
per-patient fee from Medicare regardless of the amount of care 
provided. In contrast, the government must pay each medical bill 
directly for patients who stay in the traditional Medicare program. 
</P>
<P>
	The new guidebook provides general information about how  
Medicare works and also explains tradeoffs for those considering 
joining an HMO. For example, people who choose an HMO may get extra 
benefits, such as prescription drug coverage, that are not normally 
offered by Medicare. At the same time, however, they may have less 
freedom to choose their doctors. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
