<HEADLINE> FBI Fund-Raising Notes Being Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate committee will investigate the  
disappearance of an FBI agent's notes that were written at a time 
of internal strife in a campaign fund-raising investigation, Sen. 
Fred Thompson said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson, R-Tenn., chairman of the Governmental Affairs  
Committee, said FBI and Justice Department officials were ``wholly 
unprepared'' last week to discuss details of their ongoing internal 
investigations into the disappearance. Thompson said he wouldn't 
wait for the Clinton administration to finish before launching a 
Senate probe. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberta Parker told members of Thompson's committee during a  
public hearing last week that the 27 pages of notes covered a 
period in 1997 when the agents, and Justice Department attorneys, 
had strong disagreements about tactics in the investigation of 
presidential friend Yah Lin ``Charlie'' Trie. Trie was a major 
Democratic fund-raiser who pleaded guilty to campaign finance 
violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The notes had been subpoenaed by a House committee. The agent  
said they could only have been torn from her spiral notebook. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson said sworn depositions would be taken from government  
officials who handled the notes. 
  	   	
</P>
