<HEADLINE> Boeing Buys Aussie Software Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Co. has bought The Preston Group, an  
Australian company specializing in software that simulates air 
traffic and airport use. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial details were not disclosed in the acquisition  
announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	Preston, based in Melbourne, has offices in Washington, D.C.,  
and London. Its primary software product is the Total Airspace and 
Airport Modeler, which allows airlines, airports and civil aviation 
authorities to simulate and analyze air traffic and terminal use at 
an airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Preston also makes the Terminal Management System software, a  
planning tool that helps airport operators allocate gate, check-in 
and other resources. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing, the world's largest producer of commercial aircraft, has  
used Preston's software since 1994 to support its sales efforts and 
to project airspace usage. 
</P>
<P>
	Preston will operate as a wholly owned subsidiary of Boeing and  
will maintain its current offices and management staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``The addition of The Preston Group's products and aviation  
software development expertise provide an excellent opportunity for 
Boeing to add value for customers, and to expand our comprehensive 
portfolio of support products and services,'' said Tom Schick, 
executive vice president of Boeing Commercial Aviation Services. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
