<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Ginsburg Home From Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg  
returned home from the hospital Tuesday, 11 days after surgery for 
colon cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Court spokeswoman Kathy Arberg said part of Ginsburg's colon was  
removed during the surgery. In a generally upbeat statement, she 
said the cancer had not spread to any lymph nodes. 
</P>
<P>
	A small tumor had invaded Ginsburg's colon and ``minimally  
penetrated the outer muscle,'' according to a statement released by 
Arberg. There was no speculation as to when the justice might 
return to her court chambers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg, 66, participated in consideration of cases that were  
granted review Tuesday and in several death penalty cases acted on 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Arberg said, ``All lymph nodes proved negative for cancer and  
there was no metastasis evident. A small tumor, 2 centimeters by 3 
centimeters size, had invaded her sigmoid colon and minimally 
penetrated the outer muscle.'' The sigmoid colon is one of four 
areas of the colon. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg fell ill this summer while teaching in Crete, and  
initially was treated for acute diverticulitis, a gastric disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	``Extraordinarily, the severe abdominal inflammation for which  
Justice Ginsburg was first treated ... was unrelated to her colon 
cancer,'' Arberg said. ``It did, however, lead to discovery of the 
tumor ... two weeks ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg's surgeon, Lee Smith, found a perforation higher in the  
bowel -- separate from the site of the cancer and determined to be 
non-cancerous -- that was the source of Ginsburg's abdominal 
infection, Arberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg, who had been a pioneering advocate for women's rights,  
became the second woman ever to serve on the nation's highest 
court, joining Justice Sandra Day O'Connor on the bench, when 
appointed by President Clinton in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	She since has found an ideological home somewhere left of center  
on a conservative court dominated by Republican appointees. 
</P>
<P>
	Colon cancer is one of the most common cancers in the United  
States and the second-leading cancer killer, behind lung cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	The common treatment is surgical removal of the cancerous part  
of the colon and any nearby lymph nodes where the cancer has 
spread. Post-surgical chemotherapy and radiation are often 
prescribed to kill any leftover tumor cells and decrease the 
chances of recurrence. 
</P>
<P>
	Arberg's statement did not mention additional treatment.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 01:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tigers Win at Ballpark's Last Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The memory palace had one last treasure left.  
</P>
<P>
	With Al Kaline, Ernie Harwell and a sellout crowd bidding  
farewell, the Tiger Stadium went out with a bang Monday, just the 
way it came in. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 20, 1912, the park opened with some 24,384 fans jammed  
into a place with a listed capacity of 23,000. The Tigers rallied 
to beat Cleveland 6-5 in 11 innings. The game included a steal of 
home by Ty Cobb. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sept. 27, 1999, Robert Fick, wearing the No. 25 of former  
Tigers favorite Norm Cash, hit his first career grand slam in the 
eighth inning -- a towering shot off the top of the right-field roof 
-- and Detroit beat Kansas City 8-2 in the final game at the corner 
of Michigan and Trumbull. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd of 43,356 sensed something special might be about to  
happen after Kansas City reliever Jeff Montgomery loaded the bases 
with no outs. Thousands of flash bulbs went off around the old park 
on every pitch during Gabe Kapler's at-bat. 
</P>
<P>
	When his grounder forced Dean Palmer at the plate, bases were  
still loaded for Fick. Now, the crowd was really into it, cheering 
itself hoarse as Fick strode to the plate. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium was a sea of flashing camera lights as Montgomery  
threw his first pitch to Fick. The roar from the fans was deafening 
as the ball exploded off Fick's bat, bouncing off the roof and back 
down to the field. 
</P>
<P>
	After he circled the bases, the crowd chanted Fick's name,  
demanding a curtain call. He stepped shyly to the top of the dugout 
steps and doffed his cap as thousands of flash bulbs popped once 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something I'm never going to forget,'' Fick said. ``It's  
something nobody here is ever going to forget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Emotions ran high for the fans as well as the players, but order  
prevailed. Only a few fans jumped over the fence and tried to run 
across the field after Doug Jones struck out Carlos Beltran to end 
it at 7:07 p.m. But they were quickly escorted from the grounds, 
and a security force of both mounted and foot police ringed the 
warning track for postgame ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	Home plate was dug up immediately after the final out and  
carried to Comerica Park, where it was relocated in the new 
facility being built about a mile away. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tiger Stadium may be laid to rest and we may be moving to  
Comerica Park,'' catcher Brad Ausmus said, ``but the people, the 
players and the memories of Tiger Stadium will never be 
forgotten.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So went this one last sentimental journey for the ballpark built  
on the site of a haymarket, a place that was once home to Cobb, 
Mickey Cochrane, Hank Greenberg, Denny McLain and Kaline. It opened 
as Navin Field five days after the sinking of the Titanic. Fenway 
Park opened in Boston the same day, making them the two oldest 
ballparks in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's finale was the 6,873rd regular season game at the  
stadium, which also has played host to 35 postseason games and 
three All-Star games. The sellout put the Tigers over the 2 million 
mark in attendance for just the sixth time in club history, and the 
first time since 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	For the final Tiger Stadium game, Detroit's players all wore  
numbers of Tigers who played through the years. The starters wore 
the numbers of the Tigers' all-time team. Center fielder Gabe 
Kapler wore a uniform without a number, honoring Cobb -- the 
greatest Tiger of them all -- who played in an era before uniforms 
were numbered. 
</P>
<P>
	Special baseballs were used, and the bases were changed after  
each inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaline, a Hall of Famer, exchanged lineup cards with Royals Hall  
of Famer George Brett. Both wore their familiar uniforms, Kaline 
with his No. 6, Brett with No. 5. Harwell, the beloved broadcaster, 
emceed pregame festivities. 
</P>
<P>
	``The great times we've experienced in Tiger Stadium we'll  
cherish forever,'' Mayor Dennis Archer told the crowd. ``Now, let's 
create some new memories in Comerica Park.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers won 3,764 games in the old ballpark, lost 3,090 and  
tied 19 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was home to us for a long time,'' said Eddie Mayo, a member  
of the 1945 World Series champions. ``Old friends are hard to 
slough off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kaline, with the Old English ``D'' on his breast, was saluted  
with a two-minute standing ovation during the pregame festivities 
and again during postgame ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have spoken many times about the first day I ever saw this  
ballpark, as an 18-year-old kid fresh off the train from 
Baltimore,'' Kaline said. ``I again find myself humbled and a bit 
overwhelmed by the events unfolding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Rogell, a shortstop from 1930-39, threw out the ceremonial  
first pitch as the crowd roared. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a good day, but a sad day,'' said U.S. Sen. Jim  
Bunning of Kentucky, a Hall of Fame pitcher who was with the Tigers 
from 1955-63. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Bill Freehan, selected by Detroit fans as the greatest  
Tigers catcher ever: ``Bittersweet is the perfect word for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The weather cooperated, with pale blue skies, gentle sunshine  
and a pleasant breeze coming off the Detroit River as thousands of 
fans came through the old ballpark's turnstiles one last time. 
</P>
<P>
	What they saw was what they no doubt remembered from their  
youth. By the middle of the game, the setting sun was casting long, 
loving shadows across the verdant outfield, bathing the players and 
the field in glow. 
</P>
<P>
	And, of course, the Tigers won. The Tigers almost always win in  
the memories of the true believers. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Levine, a 53-year-old fan, flew in from Chicago. In his  
wallet were ticket stubs from the 1968 game when the Tigers 
clinched the AL pennant and the game when McLain got his 30th win. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coming out here on the plane this morning, probably 80 percent  
of the people were coming here to see a ballgame for the last 
time,'' he said. ``I have tons of feelings about this old place. I 
used to skip school regularly to attend opening days here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Moehler, the starting and winning pitcher, was just like  
any other fan when it came to saying goodbye to this revered mass 
of rusting girders. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took my video camera around and I could see where people  
were trying to take the signs down,'' Moehler said. 
</P>
<P>
	In moving postgame ceremonies emceed by Harwell, 65 former  
Tigers -- from Eldon Auker, who played in 1933, to Brad Ausmus of 
the 1999 squad -- formed a chronological line from home plate to the 
flag pole in center field. 
</P>
<P>
	Many in the stands remained for as long as they could, taking in  
one last, loving look. Some, who were close enough, leaned over the 
rail and scooped handfuls of dirt. 
</P>
<P>
	With music from the movie ``Apollo 13'' playing in the  
background, Harwell's voice began to choke with emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Farewell old friend, Tiger Stadium,'' Harwell said. ``We will  
remember.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before the game, former pitching sensation Mark Fidrych, who was  
famous for talking to the baseball during his starts, was asked 
what he might say to the stadium on its final day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank you, stadium, for all the excitement you gave me. I had  
fun here. I had a lot of memories here,'' he said. ``But it's like 
everything in life, you have to go. You can't be around forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not the stadium, maybe. But the memories will live forever.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
