<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USA Today in Italian Web Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOLOGNA, Italy (AP) -- Italian publisher Poligrafici Editoriale  
SpA and USA Today's internet service, USA Today.com, joined forces 
Tuesday to develop an internet venture. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the agreement, the on-line versions of the Italian  
publisher's four daily newspapers -- the Bologna-based Il Resto del 
Carlino, the Florence-based La Nazione and the Milan-based Il 
Giorno -- will be displaying their homepages on U.S. internet sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Poligrafici Editoriale will also be displaying on U.S. internet  
sites, an on-line national daily, Il Quotidiano.net, which will be 
updated with news reports throughout the day. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Poligrafici Editoriale plans to target the U.S.  
market by developing an English-language channel covering topics 
like tourism, art, food, cars and a guide on how to use the Italian 
internet system. The channel will also include a special section 
called ``Fashion Trends'' with news from Italy's top designers. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal allows USA Today to enjoy permanent access to the  
Italian and European internet through Poligrafici Editoriale's 
internet sites and the two companies plan to generate income by 
developing and offering on-line shopping and advertising services. 
</P>
<P>
	This latest venture comes barely 10 days after Italian publisher  
Editoriale L'Espresso SpA and CNN Interactive announced the 
creation of the first 24-hour internet news service in Italy on 
Sept. 15. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
