<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Total, Elf Focus on Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARiS (AP) -- French oil companies Total Fina and Elf Aquitaine  
will focus on completing their merger rather than seeking further 
alliances, Total Fina's chairman said in an interview published 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``For us, the issue of complementary alliances is not in the  
agenda in the coming months,'' Thierry Desmarest told the Le Figaro 
daily. ``We have a lot of work this year to make sure this merger 
is a success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Total Fina came out the big winner earlier this month in its  
2-month takeover battle for Elf to create the world's 
fourth-largest oil company. 
</P>
<P>
	Total Fina's offer for Elf shares is set to close Oct. 14.  
</P>
<P>
	Although the merger would create the largest company on the  
French stock market in terms of capitalization, it still lags way 
behind Royal Dutch Shell AG, BP Amoco PLC and the planned 
combination of Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation has already arisen that Total may pursue more  
alliances, notably with Italian energy giant ENI, which held merger 
talks with Elf before Total Fina launched its own bid back in July. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said he would  
evaluate the possibility of linking ENI with the Total Fina-Elf 
group once the French companies have completed their merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Total Fina is already a product of industrywide consolidation,  
the result of Total's 1998 acquisition of Belgium's Petrofina. 
</P>
<P>
	``The movement of concentration has been so rapid over the past  
15 months that it must slow down,'' Desmarest said. ``The number of 
possible combinations is limited as well because we will come up 
against the opposition of the competition authorities.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
