<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Article Spurs Medical Journal Flap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- An article in the current New England Journal of  
Medicine that praises two popular baldness medicines was written by 
a doctor who has served as a paid consultant to the drugs' makers, 
highlighting questions about conflicts of interest in journal 
reviews. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Vera H. Price, who concludes that the ``treatment of hair  
loss has been advanced'' by the drugs Rogaine and Propecia, 
disclosed her previous positions with the drug manufacturers to 
journal editors when they invited her to write the review article. 
</P>
<P>
	Readers were not told of the affiliation.  
</P>
<P>
	Editor-in-chief Dr. Marcia Angell maintains the publication has  
``the most stringent conflict-of-interest policy'' of any medical 
journal in the country, prohibiting review authors like Price 
``from having any financial connection with a company that benefits 
from a drug or device discussed in the editorial or review 
article.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Angell acknowledged the policy's language is open to  
interpretation by editors, barring authors who have ``current, 
recent past, or planned future financial associations'' with 
companies that could gain from a positive plug. 
</P>
<P>
	``How recent is recent? ... There are adjectives in this  
statement that necessarily involve some measure of judgment,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Readers are not told of an author's past affiliations with drug  
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	That raises questions about one of the nation's most  
well-respected medical publications, said Sheldon Krimsky, a Tufts 
University professor of environmental policy who has studied 
journal conflict-of-interest policies. 
</P>
<P>
	``When they print the article -- but don't print the disclosure --  
one could say they don't have the most stringent policy,'' he said. 
``It's certainly something readers and other scientists would want 
to know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Angell said Price's affiliations with Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn Inc.,  
the maker of Rogaine, and Merck &AMP; Co., which manufactures Propecia, 
were not ``relevant'' and did not merit disclosure to readers. 
</P>
<P>
	Price's office said she was out of the country and could not be  
reached for comment. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
