<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Noise Rule End Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House asked the transportation and  
commerce secretaries on Monday to do all they can to rescind a 
European Union regulation that could ban many U.S. aircraft from 
landing or taking from European airports. 
</P>
<P>
	The regulation would ban any aircraft equipped with engine  
mufflers known as ``hush kits'' or engines altered to reduce air 
noise. EU officials contend that while reducing noise pollution, 
the kits are ineffective at controlling pollution. 
</P>
<P>
	Some members of the House called the regulation a  
discriminatory, anti-American trade action thinly disguised as 
environmental protection. The EU restriction would apply only to 
American airliners, although they in some cases are quieter than 
their European counterparts, the said. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the House resolution, approved 402-2, said that if  
the regulation is allowed to go into effect, the restriction could 
cost U.S. industry $1 billion in sales of spare parts and engines 
and reduce the resale value of more than 1,600 U.S. aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress has threatened to retaliate by imposing a U.S. flight  
ban on the noisy Concorde jetliner, the pride of European aviation 
and the world's only supersonic passenger jet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
