<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Promises To Rebuild Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole promises to rebuild the  
military, develop a defensive missile system and, when necessary, 
have America act alone when force must be used in the world's 
trouble spots. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole, in the third foreign-policy address of her Republican  
presidential campaign, said the Clinton administration seems to 
think ``the United States should act only in concert with its 
allies and can only use force if it is authorized by international 
organizations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole said that will change if she is elected president.  
</P>
<P>
	``When it is necessary to act, we will build coalitions with our  
friends and allies,'' Dole said Monday. ``But, if necessary, we 
will act alone. In short, America will be there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She told a standing-room crowd of about 800 people at the  
College of Charleston that America will be strong ``because peace 
and security can only endure through strength.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Leadership, strength and resolve have been sadly lacking''  
under the Clinton administration, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The themes were similar to those Texas Gov. George W. Bush  
touched on during a speech last week across town at The Citadel, 
South Carolina's military college. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Republican hopefuls have been campaigning in the state in  
advance of South Carolina's first-in-the-South Republican primary 
on Feb. 19. Sen. John McCain of Arizona was to campaign here today. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole's three-day swing through the Carolinas included a Sunday  
night fund-raising stop in Myrtle Beach, a fund-raiser in 
Charleston and stops today in Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Her South Carolina campaign also announced the addition of  
Lexington County business executive Scott Malyerck, a state 
organizer for former Vice President Dan Quayle, who withdrew from 
the presidential race Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	During her campaign stops, Dole promised to develop defensive  
missile systems that can be used to protect the nation or in battle 
areas. She would end the United States' adherence to the 
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, which she said was outdated and 
invalid. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said last week he would create an antiballistic missile  
system and spend an additional $20 billion on researching new 
weapons systems. Dole, however, did not mention specific spending 
figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have the money to do that,'' she said later. ``There are  
surpluses on the operating side. You've got to set your priorities 
as to what you feel is most important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said cutting wasteful government spending and privatizing  
some government services also could provide money. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole promised to improve security at the nation's weapons labs  
and said she opposed making the United States a party to the 
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, which she said was neither effective 
nor verifiable. 
</P>
<P>
	A Dole administration would forge stronger relations with major  
powers, open China to American trade and ``treat authoritarian and 
totalitarian states such as North Korea as rogue regimes, not as 
our equals,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole, asked where she differed with Bush on defense policy,  
replied, ``I think I would focus on where we differ with the 
Clinton-Gore administration.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
