<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Ridicules Reagan's Biographer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former President Bush rejects an author's  
claim that the Bushes were unwelcome ``upstairs'' in the Reagan 
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's ridiculous. Upstairs? I mean that's a kind of English,  
upstairs-and-downstairs approach to life,'' Bush said in an 
interview aired today on NBC's ``Today.'' ``I don't even use the 
terminology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan,'' Edmund Morris writes of  
a Christmas Eve 1988 conversation he said he had with Bush and wife 
Barbara, a month before Bush would become president. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really love that guy, he's such a terrific fellow,'' Bush is  
quoted as saying about the man he had served as vice president. 
Morris then quotes Bush as commenting about Reagan and his wife, 
Nancy: ``I kinda wished they'd shown -- 'y'know, a little 
appreciation. Didn't seem to want us upstairs in the White House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said in the NBC interview that he never felt unappreciated.  
``Ronald Reagan had and Nancy had friends that were closer friends 
than the Bushes. ... We never felt we were unwelcome some place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Morris' characterization of Reagan as an ``airhead,''  
Bush said: ``That is brutal and grossly unfair and untrue. ... I 
just find that outrageous, outrageous and grossly mean and 
unfair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said his working relationship with Reagan was ``heaven,  
total access, a totally relaxed relationship. From my point of view 
I couldn't have asked for a better mentor. He was a joy to work 
with.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
