<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amends Eyed for False Imprisonment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- How do the innocent collect when they are released  
from prison after spending years behind bars for crimes they didn't 
commit? 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, they sue for reparations. In California and  
Massachusetts, they petition lawmakers for relief. But what they're 
paid differs wildly. 
</P>
<P>
	A bill before Massachusetts lawmakers proposes an examination of  
how the state should make amends. Rather than leave monetary 
judgments to a jury or the Legislature, Rep. Thomas P. Kennedy has 
proposed establishing a commission to investigate and recommend 
possible solutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Civil libertarians say the system must compensate victims of its  
mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that when there's been a miscarriage of justice, the  
state does owe the person who has been harmed,'' said Norma 
Shapiro, an American Civil Liberties Union legislative specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	But the idea of a public policy for compensating former convicts  
has raised concerns. Michael Sullivan, president of the 
Massachusetts District Attorneys Association, said payments 
shouldn't be made to those freed on a technicality. 
</P>
<P>
	``It should really be truly set up and only considered for those  
that are clearly innocent and wrongly accused, charged, convicted 
and sentenced,'' he said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen states, the District of Columbia and the federal  
government have statutes addressing compensation for those wrongly 
imprisoned, according to an article in a recent publication of the 
American Bar Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Two states -- New York and West Virginia -- do not limit damages.  
Elsewhere, caps range up to $300,000, while the federal limit is 
$5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	California, for example, allows up to $10,000, which former  
Marine Kevin Lee Green received after spending 17 years in prison 
after being convicted of beating his wife and killing their unborn 
child. Citing DNA evidence, a judge ruled in 1996 that Green did 
not commit the crime; earlier this year, the actual killer was 
convicted after confessing. 
</P>
<P>
	Green is appealing to lawmakers to pass a bill that would give  
him $650,000, equivalent to about $100 a day for every day he spent 
behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	``How do you compensate for that kind of time?'' Green said.  
``For the things I missed that I can't get back?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ACLU's Shapiro said people like Green often lack political  
clout or the money to win their fight for compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have only just begun to recognize that those who have been  
wrongly convicted are also victims,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 08:35:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wants More Mideast Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said today  
the Clinton administration still hopes stalled Israeli-Syrian and 
Israeli-Lebanese peace talks can be restarted although obstacles to 
an overall peace remain daunting. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issue here is whether we can find the way to restart  
negotiations that will match the will that all sides profess to 
feel,'' she told an audience of leaders of Jewish organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright suggested that both Israel and Syria, in particular,  
``clearly want to find a way forward. Both are treating the other 
with unusual trust and respect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright also denounced congressional efforts to slash foreign  
aid, saying a spending bill in Congress that would cut $2 billion 
from President Clinton's budget remains a veto candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Diplomacy is America's first line of defense,'' Albright said.  
``It should be treated as a budget priority,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, as an aside, she added, ``I have eliminated the words  
'foreign aid' from our vocabulary. These two words don't seem to 
excite a lot of people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $12.6 billion bill makes deep cuts in many international  
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration also is unhappy that negotiators rejected its  
request to provide funds for carrying out the Wye River Middle East 
peace accords. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only has Congress ignored the administration's request for  
at least $500 million for Israel and the Palestinians to carry out 
the accords in the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, but foreign aid 
negotiators also cut $100 million that had been promised to Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	The final version of the bill has been held up over a  
House-Senate dispute over an unrelated provision denying U.S. funds 
to international family-planning programs that support or advocate 
abortion rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright, here for the two-week opening session of the U.N.  
General Assembly, made a breakfast address to the Conference of 
Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	She expressed optimism for peace talks, not only those between  
the Israelis and the Palestinians, but also efforts to resume 
Israel's suspended negotiations with Syria and Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright has met in New York, on the sidelines of the U.N.  
meetings, with the foreign ministers of both Syria and Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy told reporters  
after his meeting with Albright that any efforts to link wider 
Mideast peace talks to progress made in resuming talks with Syria 
was ``not acceptable to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright today asserted that ``the key is to establish a basis  
on which to resume negotiations that neither side sees as 
prejudicing the negotiation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both she and Clinton will remain ``actively engaged with both  
sides,'' Albright said. ``If we did not think an agreement were 
possible, we would not be making the effort to bring them 
together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Over the weekend, Egypt's foreign minister, Amr Moussa, sought  
to pressure Israel to make concessions by saying Arabs would not 
resume multilateral peace talks until Israel resumed negotiations 
with Syria and Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	The multilateral talks were launched in 1992, covering such key  
issues as disarmament, Palestinian refugees, the environment and 
economic cooperation before being suspended in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	But Levy said that whether the talks with Syria are resumed  
should have no bearing on the multilateral talks. 
</P>
<P>
	During a closed-door portion of today's meeting, Albright was  
questioned about the Egyptian position and told the audience she 
did not agree with it, said a senior administration official who 
spoke on the condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright urged that the multilateral talks go forward regardless  
of progress or lack of progress in other negotiations, the official 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The official said that, during the closed session, the subject  
of new construction in West Bank Jewish settlements, a divisive 
issue in the Israeli-Palestinian talks, did not come up. Nor did 
Albright mention the settlements in her public remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who took power July  
6, has called for the resumption of talks, Syria's insistence that 
the Golan Heights be returned first has placed new obstacles in the 
way of new talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Golan Heights were captured from Syria in 1967.  
</P>
<P>
	Albright said the Clinton administration remains committed to  
working with the parties toward a comprehensive peace. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we cannot make the hard decisions that will produce peace  
itself,'' she added. ``Only those who live in the region can do 
that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
