<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Black Stuntworkers Claim Bias </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Minority stuntworkers are accusing Hollywood  
of discrimination, saying the industry is hiring whites to stand in 
for black actors such as Eddie Murphy, Samuel Jackson and Louis 
Gossett Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference Monday, several stuntworkers asked viewers  
to boycott all Viacom products Oct. 8-10. Viacom owns CBS, MTV, 
VH-1 and Nickelodeon, as well as the Paramount studios and the 
Blockbuster chain of video-rental stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayne King Jr., who doubled for Michael Jordan in ``Space Jam,''  
said he can count on one hand the number of days he's worked as a 
stuntman this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm feeling it,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	In industry parlance, a ``paint down'' refers to a white  
stuntworker who dons dark make-up and wigs to stand in for a 
minority actor. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have paint downs, you're taking jobs away from  
African-Americans,'' said Marvin Walters, a retired black stuntman. 
``I don't care what they say, this is discrimination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The protest follows the criticism of TV networks for their  
largely white casting this season. The lack of roles for minorities 
in Hollywood has been a contentious issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Walters estimated that of some 65 black stuntworkers in  
Hollywood, only 15 work on a regular basis. Walters said ``we hold 
SAG ultimately responsible,'' referring to the Screen Actors Guild, 
which represents nearly 96,000 actors, including stuntworkers, 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Katherine Moore, a SAG spokeswoman, said the guild has an  
aggressive diversity campaign and has published for the second year 
a directory called ``Stunt Performers of Color.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walters said a white stuntwoman stood in for the female Asian  
lead of CBS's ``Martial Law'' and complained over the hiring 
choices on Paramount's ``Shaft,'' a spin-off of the 1970s TV 
detective series. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS spokesman Chris Ender said ``Martial Law'' star Kelly Hu has  
a regular Asian stuntwoman but that one time the woman didn't want 
to do a stunt where she had to fall off a cliff. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shaft'' director and producer John Singleton, who is black,  
said he simply ``hired the best people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Any allegations that anyone is being hired on a racial basis  
is unfounded, totally erroneous and very offensive to me,'' he said 
in a statement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
