<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Redstone: Don't Offend Governments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- International news organizations should  
report the truth but avoid being ``unnecessarily offensive'' to 
foreign governments, the head of the company poised to take over 
CBS said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The comments by Sumner M. Redstone, the chairman of Viacom Inc.,  
were significant in light of Viacom's impending purchase of CBS and 
the venue -- a forum of global business leaders in China. 
</P>
<P>
	As they expand their global reach, media companies must be aware  
``of the politics and attitudes of the governments where we 
operate,'' Redstone said at a news conference at the Fortune Global 
Forum. 
</P>
<P>
	``Journalistic integrity must prevail in the final analysis,''  
he said. ``But that doesn't mean that journalistic integrity should 
be exercised in a way that is unnecessarily offensive to the 
countries in which you operate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The communist government in Beijing has jailed domestic  
political critics and journalists. It tries to keep tight control 
on information and has tried to curb access to its media markets by 
foreign firms, especially those seen as unfriendly. 
</P>
<P>
	Viacom -- whose $35 billion takeover of CBS will mark its entry  
into the news-gathering business -- has encountered resistance from 
Chinese regulators. Its MTV music video network has been relegated 
to secondary cable channels and poor time slots in many Chinese 
media markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Time magazine also has had recent troubles in China.  
</P>
<P>
	The news magazine -- whose parent company, Time Warner Inc.,  
organized the business forum -- has had its latest edition pulled 
from the international hotels in China where it is normally sold, a 
senior Time executive said. Although no reason was given, the issue 
contains articles written by exiled dissidents. 
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner chairman Gerald M. Levin, speaking at the  
conference, said the magazine ``raised some concerns'' within the 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	``While I don't necessarily agree with that, it's not going to  
change the conduct of our journalism or the nature of our business 
in China,'' said Levin, who appeared with Redstone at the gathering 
of 300 senior executives from foreign companies. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
