<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airline Fined For Moving Passenger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A first-class passenger who refused to sit  
next to a seeing-eye dog prompted America West Airlines to move a 
blind passenger and her dog to coach class. And that led to a 
$1,000 government fine against the carrier, the Transportation 
Department announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The department levied the penalty because its rules state that  
America West should have instead moved the objecting passenger or 
taken him off the airplane. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will work with the carriers to ensure that our air  
transportation system is inclusive in its service and, therefore, 
accessible to all travelers,'' Transportation Secretary Rodney 
Slater said in announcing the settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident occurred Sept. 16, 1998, when Sherry Layne of  
Phoenix, Ariz., and her seeing-eye dog, a golden Labrador named 
``Faith,'' boarded an America West flight from Baltimore to 
Phoenix. Layne was using a first-class ticket she bought at a 
reduced rate through a relative who was an America West employee. 
</P>
<P>
	When she arrived to take her window seat -- intending to have the  
dog rest at her feet -- the aisle seat passenger objected to flying 
next to a seeing-eye dog and blocked Layne from sitting down. 
</P>
<P>
	The case docket -- which did not include that passenger's name --  
said America West flight attendants tried both to change his mind 
and to find a different seat in the first-class compartment. 
</P>
<P>
	When he held firm and no other first-class passenger would move,  
Layne was switched to coach, where she and Faith could sit 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	``To make matters worse, while I was standing in full view of  
everyone who saw this total rejection of me in first class because 
I was visually impaired, the captain began `playing' with my guide 
dog,'' Layne wrote in her initial complaint to the airline in 
October 1998. ``I politely but firmly asked him not to touch my 
guide dog, yet he kept doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Transportation Department rules say travelers have the right to  
bring service animals on airplanes and the animal must be 
accommodated near the passenger. If another passenger objects, the 
carrier must outline the disabled passenger's rights and find 
another seat for the objecting passenger, if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	If that fails, the airline must remove the objecting passenger  
from the flight, the rules say. 
</P>
<P>
	In a Dec. 1, 1998 letter of apology to Layne, America West said  
it would use the incident in its training materials, but it also 
said that passengers traveling with a company-discounted ticket are 
not guaranteed a specific seat. 
</P>
<P>
	``While I regret the passengers in first class were not willing  
to sit next to your guide dog, our personnel were able to 
accommodate you on the flight. I'm sorry you feel this constitutes 
a violation of your rights,'' wrote Dee L. Mann, special assistant 
to America West Chairman William Franke. 
</P>
<P>
	Layne's attorney, Ellen Sue Katz of the Arizona Center for  
Disability Law, said she and Layne did not know of the settlement 
before it was announced Tuesday. She said they were undecided about 
whether to appeal, although Layne's complaint did not seek monetary 
damages other than legal fees. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted them to change their practices and policies so their  
staff knew how to treat people with service animals, that the 
airline have a compliance officer and when complaints are made, 
they are handled appropriately. We don't think any of that happened 
in this case,'' Katz said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fine will not be paid to the government. Instead, the  
department and America West agreed to put the money toward the 
airline's program for training guide dogs to handle airplane 
flight. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 06:10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Falcons Look Like the Same Ol' Birds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUWANEE, Ga. (AP) -- Bob Whitfield, walking toward the meeting  
room to watch video from another Falcons loss, summed up the plight 
facing the defending NFC champions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll bet you if we go 13-3, we'll have the best record in  
football,'' Atlanta's offensive tackle said Monday. ``We've just 
got to win the rest of our games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dirty Birds may have been able to pull off such a feat.  
However, these guys look like the same ol' Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	In a mere eight months, Atlanta (0-3) has gone from Super Bowl  
to super trouble, threatening to ruin all the goodwill that built 
up during that magical run to Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Hey, is it hockey season yet?  
</P>
<P>
	``It's fun playing in front of a lot of people,'' Whitfield  
said. ``If we lose a couple of games and the people don't want to 
come out, so be it. I guess we'll have to play in front of 
nobody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons sank further into the abyss Sunday, when a St. Louis  
team that was 4-12 a year ago routed the Falcons 35-7. The game 
wasn't even as close as the score, the Rams converting on their 
first four possessions and outgaining Atlanta 311-67 in the first 
half. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looked like they were playing a different speed than we  
were,'' coach Dan Reeves said. 
</P>
<P>
	After falling behind 17-0 in each of their first two games, the  
Falcons trailed 28-0 to the Rams. The injury-depleted offense, 
averaging 9.3 points per game, struggled once again, only this time 
it was complemented by a complete breakdown on defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ran into a buzz saw in St. Louis,'' Marty Carter said.  
``Wow. It was bombs away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rams' dominance was epitomized by a three-play sequence in  
the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	With his team already leading 7-0, Kurt Warner threw a 38-yard  
touchdown pass to Torry Holt on third-and-18. After Todd Lyght 
intercepted a pass from Chris Chandler, Warner capitalized on the 
very next play with a 46-yard scoring strike to Isaac Bruce. On the 
first play of St. Louis' next possession, Marshall Faulk broke off 
a 58-yard run to set up another TD. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just gave up way too many big plays,'' Reeves said. ``On  
the road, where your defense has to play well, we just didn't get 
the job done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More troubling, the Falcons secondary ``looked like the Keystone  
Kops,'' in the words of free safety Eugene Robinson. During a bye 
week, St. Louis came up with a game plan that caught Atlanta 
completely off guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``They took chances downfield and caught us with different  
formations we didn't expect,'' Carter admitted. 
</P>
<P>
	Granted, the Falcons have been plagued by factors beyond their  
control. All-Pro running back Jamal Anderson is out for the season 
with a knee injury, while Chandler is hobbling on a sore hamstring. 
</P>
<P>
	Chandler missed one game, tried to come back too soon Sunday and  
wound up being knocked out again before halftime. He is 
questionable for next weekend's game against the Baltimore Ravens. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not very good,'' Chandler said Monday. ``I'm just trying  
to get it better before it gets worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Already worse for the Falcons is the situation on the defensive  
line, where tackles Shane Dronett and Ed Jasper are both out for 
2-to-4 weeks. Dronett pulled his right calf muscle, while Jasper 
sustained ligament damage in his left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Mentally, the entire team is suffering a severe case of  
shellshock. Although the Falcons have never put together 
consecutive winning seasons during their 34-year history, no one 
expected a start like this. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning breeds confidence,'' Reeves said. ``Losing brings  
around the wrong kind of things: people second-guessing you, people 
talking about how bad you are playing. That is all you hear and all 
you read.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Certainly, this is not what Carter had in mind when he signed  
with the Falcons as a free agent after eight mostly losing seasons 
in Tampa Bay and Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe it wouldn't be so bad if we didn't have such high  
expectations,'' he said. ``That's the most difficult thing. We're 
on every sports show, every channel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only five teams have rebounded from an 0-3 start to make the  
playoffs, and it's little consolation that the Super Bowl champion 
Broncos are also winless after three games. 
</P>
<P>
	Falcons owner Taylor Smith is confident Reeves can get things  
turned around, as he did during his first season in Atlanta. In 
1997, the Falcons were 1-7 at the midway point but won six of their 
final eight games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dan is so consistent,'' Smith said. ``He knows how to handle  
things like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He better hurry.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 15:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dean Settling Watergate Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A settlement has been reached in a seven-year  
libel lawsuit that former White House counsel John W. Dean III 
filed against the author of a book portraying him as the mastermind 
of the Watergate conspiracy. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Emmet G. Sullivan signed a one-page order  
Monday dismissing the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The dismissal came after State Farm Insurance Cos., the author's  
personal liability insurance carrier, decided to pay the Deans an 
undisclosed sum to resolve the dispute, insurance company spokesman 
Joe Johnson said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate deal, he said State Farm agreed to pay Leonard  
Colodny of Tampa, Fla., the author of the 1991 book titled ``Silent 
Coup,'' an undisclosed amount of money for fees and expenses that 
Colodny incurred in defending the suit. The sum is ``well up into 
the six figures,'' according to Colodny's attorney, Martin Lobel. 
</P>
<P>
	The book claims Dean orchestrated the 1972 burglary at the  
Democratic National Committee headquarters in Washington. The book 
says the break-in at the Watergate complex was an effort to obtain 
information on an alleged link between Democrats and a prostitution 
ring run by a friend of Dean's future wife, Maureen. 
</P>
<P>
	The book says Dean planned the break-in to collect damaging  
information on the Democrats to heighten his own influence at the 
White House and then concocted the cover-up without consulting 
superiors. Dean's damaging testimony to congressional investigators 
further unraveled the Watergate affair, which forced President 
Nixon to resign in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're thrilled about the settlement and we feel we have ample  
evidence proving his story is false,'' said John Garrick, the 
Deans' attorney. ``The Deans have repeatedly refuted the claim that 
there was a call girl ring linked to the Democratic National 
Committee and that Mr. Dean's wife was friends with the madam of 
the call girl ring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colodny, however, says Dean agreed to accept a settlement and  
sign an agreement not to sue the author again on the same grounds 
because he wanted to avoid a public courtroom drama. Colodny wanted 
the court to hear the case because he was confident that a public 
trial would validate his reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted it heard,'' Colodny said. ``We had source after  
source after source for what we wrote and Dean knew it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
