<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikings Trade Colinet for Ball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- The Minnesota Vikings got defensive  
tackle Jerry Ball back from the Cleveland Browns on Tuesday in a 
trade for defensive end Stalin Colinet and an undisclosed draft 
pick. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's a great opportunity to get a player that was  
with us before,'' Vikings coach Dennis Green said. ``We will miss 
Stalin. He was a player who was making progress as a young player. 
However, taking advantage of the opportunity to bring Jerry back is 
something we thought we should do. We look forward to Jerry helping 
our team be successful for the next two years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ball will be reunited with college defensive linemate Joe  
Phillips. The two starred at Southern Methodist in the mid-1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns signed Ball in April. He was the third important  
defensive free agent the Browns lured away from the Vikings. 
Cleveland earlier signed cornerback Corey Fuller and defensive end 
Derrick Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
	Ball started all three games for the expansion Browns this  
season, posting four tackles and notching a sack against Baltimore 
on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12-year veteran and three time Pro-Bowl selection had 15  
tackles for losses last season. He started 25 consecutive games at 
nose tackle for the Vikings over the last two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Ball started his career with Detroit, then played for the old  
Browns in 1993, before moving on to the Raiders and then Minnesota. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Showers and thunderstorms spread across the Southeast and  
mid-Atlantic states Tuesday and parts of the Midwest and Plains 
also had rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Scattered showers and thunderstorms hit Georgia and Virginia as  
well as South Carolina and North Carolina. The additional rain 
caused flooding over a large part of eastern North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides a few showers and thunderstorms along the Gulf Coast,  
most of the lower-Mississippi Valley and Tennessee Valley had fair 
to partly cloudy skies. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong cold front extending from the Great Lakes through the  
mid-Mississippi Valley into the southern Plains continued to bring 
showers and thunderstorms to the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers and thunderstorms lined up along the front from eastern  
Wisconsin, northern Illinois, northern Missouri and Kansas. The 
heaviest thunderstorms, with heavy rainfall, were found from 
northwestern Illinois into northern Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow fell over parts of eastern Colorado and in the Denver  
metropolitan area, with about an inch by early afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Fair and dry conditions were found over much of the western  
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures around the continental United States ranged from a  
morning low of 9 in West Yellowstone, Mont., and Stanley, Idaho, to 
a midday high of 90 in Memphis, Tenn. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
