<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Urges Use of DNA Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Justice Department advisory panel warns  
police officers collecting DNA evidence to wear gloves, avoid 
sneezing on the sample and keep it in new paper bags or envelopes, 
not plastic bags. 
</P>
<P>
	Plastic bags retain moisture, which could damage cells of human  
tissue containing DNA genetic material. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Commission on the Future of DNA Evidence also urged  
federal and state prosecutors Monday to agree to and pay for DNA 
tests that could exonerate convicts, even if the deadline for 
appeals has passed. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission of prosecutors, defense lawyers, judges, police  
executives, forensic scientists and academics was set up last year 
at the request of Attorney General Janet Reno. It issued its first 
recommendations Monday in two publications: a pamphlet for police 
officers and a 117-page book for prosecutors, defense attorneys, 
judges and lab directors titled ``Postconviction DNA Testing: 
Recommendations for Handling Requests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Associate Attorney General Ray Fisher said his department's  
research arm, the National Institute of Justice, would distribute 
the pamphlet to every police officer in America. 
</P>
<P>
	The pamphlet, ``What Every Law Enforcement Officer Should Know  
About DNA Evidence,'' also lists places where such evidence can be 
found: hats, dirty laundry, toothpicks, used cigarettes, licked 
stamps, pillow cases, even baseball bat handles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the widespread dissemination of this pamphlet starts us  
down a path toward eliminating the need for the other publication 
on how to deal with postconviction DNA test requests,'' Fisher told 
a commission meeting. ``By committing ourselves to more accurate 
and effective investigative processes through the use of DNA 
technology, we work toward elimination of the real tragedy of 
wrongful convictions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher said the Justice Department now knows of 65 people  
wrongly convicted and later exonerated by DNA testing. 
</P>
<P>
	DNA, an acid that contains an individual's genetic makeup, is  
found in almost every cell in the body. Except for identical twins, 
each person's DNA is unique and can be used for identification, and 
it often can be found where no fingerprints are left. 
</P>
<P>
	The growing number of convictions overturned by DNA evidence has  
weakened the legal presumption that verdicts are correct, the panel 
noted. 
</P>
<P>
	Time limits were imposed on federal and state appeals because,  
as the memory of witnesses fades, ``questions of guilt or innocence 
become more uncertain with the passage of time,'' the panel wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``But the results of DNA testing do not become weaker over time.  
... To the contrary, the probative value of DNA testing has been 
steadily increasing as technological advances and growing databases 
amplify the ability to identify perpetrators and eliminate 
suspects.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission recommended that requests for DNA tests after  
conviction be divided into one of five categories, ranging from 
those that clearly could exonerate a convict to totally frivolous 
requests. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with a request that clearly could exonerate a convict, the  
prosecutor should join the defense attorney in requesting tests and 
pay for them if the convict is cleared, the panel recommended. 
</P>
<P>
	Only two states, New York and Illinois, have passed laws  
specifically authorizing late appeals based on DNA tests. The panel 
said if the time for appeals based on new evidence has expired, 
both sides may agree to waive the time limit or the judge can use 
inherent powers ``to prevent what may be a miscarriage of 
justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission's findings are recommendations and have no force  
of law. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
