<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HMO Bill Stresses Insurance Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A package of tax cuts aimed at improving  
access to health insurance was offered today by House Republican 
leaders hoping to blend the measure with bills giving people rights 
to sue managed care health plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said each of the bills giving  
patients a host of new legal rights is missing two key pieces: 
improving health care access and affordability for an estimated 44 
million uninsured Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be impossible to move forward with patient protection  
and not do something about the uninsured,'' Hastert said. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP measure, which includes numerous tax breaks costing $43  
billion over 10 years, is expected to be debated in the House next 
week. It is an attempt to put a Republican stamp on one of several 
popular, Democratic-driven measures aimed at increasing patient 
rights through lawsuits or independent appeal boards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frankly, all the lawsuits in the world won't do a thing for a  
worker struggling to buy health insurance for themselves or their 
family,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the Ways and 
Means Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax breaks, most of which were part of the 10-year, $792  
billion GOP tax cut vetoed last week by President Clinton, are 
strongly supported by small businesses and the self-employed. They 
include: 
</P>
<P>
	--A 100 percent health insurance premium deduction for people who  
purchase their own policies and the self-employed. It could be 
claimed whether or not a taxpayer itemizes deductions. 
</P>
<P>
	--A similar 100 percent deduction for people who purchase  
long-term care insurance for elderly family members and an 
additional personal exemption -- worth $2,750 this year -- for people 
who care for elderly family members at home. 
</P>
<P>
	--An expansion of medical savings accounts to allow employers and  
employees to contribute and to permit all individuals, not just 
small employers and the self-employed, to take part. 
</P>
<P>
	--Additional long-term care insurance and medical savings  
accounts benefits for workers whose companies offer ``cafeteria'' 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Several provisions added by Rep. Jim Talent, R-Mo.,chairman of  
the Small Business Committee, would enable more small businesses to 
pool risks and buy health insurance more cheaply and form local 
purchasing cooperatives for the same purpose. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed changes, Talent said, would enable small businesses  
``to offer employees the same kinds of health care options big 
corporations have offered for years.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
