<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Backed in Rival's Backyard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Republican front-runner George W. Bush claimed an  
endorsement Tuesday from the governor of a rival's home state, 
setting the stage for what could be a fierce Arizona presidential 
primary. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe we have a common vision,'' Gov. Jane Hull said in  
announcing her support for the Texas governor. She cited Bush's 
support for low taxes, open international trade markets, small 
government with local control and a strong military as well as his 
character and experience as governor as reasons for her decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the winning combination,'' Mrs. Hull said. ``In baseball  
they call it a grand slam.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The endorsement could mean trouble for Sen. John McCain,  
R-Ariz., who has been gaining on Bush in New Hampshire, site of the 
nation's first primary next year. 
</P>
<P>
	But McCain also is counting on his home state to boost his  
campaign heading into the critical California primary less than 
three weeks later. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, Bush picked up the endorsement of another  
prominent Arizona Republican, former congressman John Rhodes. New 
York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani also was set to endorse Bush, 
possibly this week, a top New York Republican said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said Hull's support will ``make a difference for me in this  
state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got some advice for anyone who decides to run for  
president,'' he said. ``If you decide to run, get the governor on 
your side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also said he intends to campaign hard in Arizona.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know it's an important state and I intend to be  
competitive,'' he said. ``I know I've got a lot of work to do in 
Arizona.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's visit Tuesday was scheduled well in advance and was not  
set up to embarrass McCain, Mrs. Hull said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have nothing but the highest respect for John McCain,'' she  
said. ``No matter what happens he and I will work together for the 
betterment of Arizona.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush agreed, calling McCain a good man, a good senator and an  
American hero. ``We just have a difference of opinion and the 
difference is who should be the nominee of the Republican Party.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
