<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Gains, Japanese Stocks Surge / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar gained against the yen Tuesday on hopes  
that the Bank of Japan will ease monetary policy. Tokyo share 
prices surged on the back of the greenback's recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was trading at 106.52 yen on the Tokyo foreign  
exchange market at 5 p.m. (4 a.m. EDT) Tuesday, up 2.38 yen from 
late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up 504.64  
points, or 3.00 percent, to 17,325.70 Tuesday. On Monday, the 
average closed down 50.67 points, or 0.30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar gained in part on expectations  
that the Bank of Japan will ease monetary policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, Japan's Economic Planning Agency head Taichi  
Sakaiya said he disagreed with the BOJ's stance that further easing 
would be ineffective. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakaiya said that increasing reserves in the money market could  
lower mid- to long-term interest rates, thus encouraging corporate 
activities and support further economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded in a relatively narrow range from 105.43 yen  
to 106.72 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback also continued to be supported on the expectations  
of coordinated efforts by leading industrialized countries to buy 
up the U.S. currency against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Last weekend, finance ministers and central bankers from the  
Group of Seven industrialized nations met in Washington and agreed 
to ``continue to monitor developments in exchange markets and 
cooperate as appropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Japan failed to obtain a clear pledge from other G-7  
members for coordinated action to weaken the yen. The G-7 includes 
the United States, Japan, Britain, France, Germany, Italy and 
Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, traders said investors were encouraged by  
the dollar's gains against the yen to buy up export-oriented 
blue-chip shares in particular. 
</P>
<P>
	A weaker yen helps Japan's exporting companies by making their  
products cheaper abroad and thus more competitive, which government 
officials fear could hurt the country's budding economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section of the Tokyo stock exchange was  
estimated at 350.45 million shares, up from 347 million shares 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancers outnumbered decliners 843 to 335, while 149 issues  
remained unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan's message  
overnight from Washington urging Japan to develop more vibrant 
stock and bond markets also gave Japanese investors an impetus to 
buy shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnight rises in U.S. stocks also reduced fears of a possible  
downturn on Wall Street, which could prompt foreign investors to 
take profits on Japanese stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 24.06  
points to 10,303.29, led by gains in some high-technology and 
consumer issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section closed up 39.91 points, or 2.79 percent, to 1,469.29. 
The TOPIX closed down 1.04 points, or 0.07 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 111.61 yen, up  
sharply from 109.13 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.7150 percent from Monday's finish of 1.6850 percent. Its price 
fell 0.26 point to 99.87. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
