<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush's Fitness Called Outstanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Republican presidential front-runner George  
W. Bush is in excellent health, his doctor said Tuesday, with a 
fitness level among the top 1 percent of men in their 50s. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper of Dallas, who has treated the 53-year-old  
Bush since 1989, said the Texas governor has ``no history of any 
alcohol, drug, mental or psychiatric treatment or rehabilitation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a three-page written statement issued by Bush's campaign, and  
in a later telephone interview, Cooper said the candidate, who is 
an avid runner, has an ``outstanding level of fitness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's cardiovascular fitness is rated excellent to superior,  
there are no signs of coronary artery disease, he has a low to very 
low coronary risk profile, and his test for prostate cancer was 
excellent, Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush suffers from stiffness in his left knee, which he  
attributes to his exercise program. Some back stiffness also was 
noted, particularly with running, but stretching controlled the 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has a mild high-frequency hearing loss likely due to flying  
jets, the doctor said, and his hearing tests excellent in the 
speech frequencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper said Bush's level of fitness would put him among the top  
1 percent of men in their 50s and the top 5 percent of men in their 
40s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been very, very pleased with his outstanding level of  
fitness,'' the doctor said. ``His state of health at the time of 
his most recent examination was excellent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That exam was conducted on June 17, 1999. The governor is 6 feet  
tall, weighed 192 1/2 pounds, had blood pressure ``in the right arm 
sitting position'' of 104 over 80, pulse 38. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper said Bush's pulse rate -- determined from both wrists and  
an electrocardiogram -- is considered normal ``for a highly 
conditioned athlete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush regularly runs three to four miles, five times a week, his  
doctor said. He's been exercising regularly since 1972, the doctor 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his written statement, Cooper said Bush ``has totally  
abstained from alcohol during the past 13 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has said he made ``mistakes'' in his youth and that he  
stopped drinking after his 40th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	There has been no evidence or credible allegation that he ever  
has used cocaine or other illegal drug. When pressed on the 
question last month, Bush said he had not used illegal drugs in the 
past 25 years. He declined to elaborate further. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper said that from questionnaires filled out by Bush as well  
as medical examinations, he's seen no signs of drug or alcohol 
abuse while treating Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no knowledge of any drug use. I have no knowledge of  
any alcohol abuse,'' Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said there were no indications from other tests and  
examinations that Bush ever abused drugs, and he said that in 
consulting with the doctor who previously treated Bush, nothing 
came up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't pursue that further because I didn't see any  
indication for doing that,'' Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked specifically if Bush ever had undergone drug or alcohol  
treatment, campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said Tuesday: ``As 
part of his complete disclosure of his medical history, he neither 
needed nor ever received mental, emotional, drug or alcohol 
treatment or rehabilitation -- ever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's medical history includes minor surgery to his chest wall  
at age 13, an appendectomy at age 10, and arthroscopic knee surgery 
in 1997. Two benign polyps also were surgically removed from his 
colon in July 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush is taking no prescribed or self-prescribed medications,  
except supplemental vitamins and minerals, his doctor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's campaign said the medical summary was made public ``in  
accordance with past presidential campaigns.'' Spokeswoman Mindy 
Tucker said the campaign had received two or three requests from 
news organizations seeking the records. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican presidential hopefuls Elizabeth Dole, Gary Bauer,  
Steve Forbes and Sens. Orrin Hatch of Utah and John McCain of 
Arizona are in good health and plan to release health evaluations 
in the future, campaign spokesmen said Tuesday. Aides for 
Republicans Pat Buchanan and Alan Keyes and Democrat Bill Bradley 
could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore also is in good health and plans to  
release a health evaluation in the future, a spokesman said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
