<HEADLINE> Watson, Irwin Tee Off for TV  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) -- Tom Watson shot a 4-under-par 68 to beat  
Hale Irwin and take home the $100,000 first prize on Tuesday in a 
made-for-television match at the Jasna Polona golf course. 
</P>
<P>
	About 2,000 people watched the two play on a sunny, unseasonably  
warm day. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson, a five-time British Open winner, led throughout the  
friendly match. His lead was as large as six strokes at one point. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin, 1998 Senior PGA Tour Player of the Year, and winner of  
three U.S. Opens, finished with a 1-under-par 71. He received 
$50,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The match was played for a segment of ``Shell's Wonderful World  
of Golf,'' to be aired Oct. 26 on ESPN. 
</P>
<P>
	Down six strokes, Irwin closed the gap to three on the 17th when  
he birdied and Watson had a double-bogey 5. Both parred the 18th. 
</P>
<P>
	This is only the second time the show, in its nearly 40-year  
history, has shot a match in New Jersey. The other was in 1960 at 
Pine Valley in the Pine Barrens, according to Fred Raphael, who 
produced the show from 1960 to 1971. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
