<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deutsche Telekom May Get Brit Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union regulators Tuesday  
approved Deutsche Telekom's $11 billion takeover of British 
mobile-phone operator One2One. 
</P>
<P>
	``The acquisition will not lead to any overlap on the market,''  
for mobile phones in Britain since Deutsche Telekom was not 
previously active there, the European Commission said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU executive body said its investigation also showed the  
takeover will not lead to a creation of an unfairly dominant 
position in Germany or on mobile calls between Britain and Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom's acquisition of One2One was announced last  
month following the German company's failed attempt to merge with 
Telecom Italia. The deal with the smallest of Britain's four mobile 
phone companies was seen as a first step in a new international 
expansion effort by Deutsche Telekom in the increasingly global 
telecommunications market. 
</P>
<P>
	About 95 percent of Telekom's annual sales come from the German  
market. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 15:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns Offense Looking for Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEREA, Ohio (AP) -- In training camp, Cleveland Browns coach  
Chris Palmer presented his team with a playbook big enough to pass 
as a college textbook. 
</P>
<P>
	But after three games, it looks like his offense has only read  
the introduction. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland's offense has sputtered this season, and while each  
week's performance has been noticeably better, the Browns are still 
a long way from becoming a serious threat to most NFL defenses. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not a whole lot we've done that's been effective,''  
said fullback Marc Edwards. ``What is our bread and butter? We 
haven't found that yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's for sure. The winless Browns are averaging just 6.3  
points a game, an offensive output equaled by baseball's Cleveland 
Indians, who have averaged 6.3 runs a game this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the Browns' woes come down to poor execution.  
</P>
<P>
	Dropped passes, a harried quarterback and a poor running game --  
89 of Cleveland's paltry 192 yards rushing have come on scrambles 
by rookie quarterback Tim Couch -- all have kept Cleveland from 
developing an offensive rhythm. 
</P>
<P>
	A couple of veterans even questioned Palmer's offensive  
strategy, which was supposed to be his strength coming into the 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	Receiver Leslie Shepherd, guilty of a couple of drops in  
Sunday's 17-10 loss to Baltimore, stopped short of calling the 
Browns predictable, but said Cleveland has to adjust better to how 
it's being defended. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have a certain amount of plays you run each Sunday and the  
other team prepares to stop them,'' Shepherd said. ``If they throw 
a defense at you, you've got to make adjustments. Right now, we're 
not doing a good job of making adjustments. 
</P>
<P>
	``We run a lot of the same plays. I'll tell Tim (Couch) they  
gave us a certain defensive look on one play and I was open. He'll 
come back and call the play again, and they'll roll the coverage 
over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer has made no secret he's simplified his offense to  
accommodate Couch taking over for Ty Detmer after an opening 43-0 
loss to Pittsburgh, but he said Cleveland's problem ``isn't as much 
a matter of adjustments as it is execution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Palmer's offensive decisions have been criticized by some  
as too conservative for an expansion team with nothing to lose, 
while others have second-guessed him for taking bad risks. 
</P>
<P>
	On their second possession Sunday, the Browns punted on  
fourth-and-1 from Baltimore's 39-yard line. Palmer explained later 
he thought the game would be low-scoring and didn't want to give up 
field position. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second quarter, Lomas Brown gave up a critical sack of  
Couch on the Browns 2 when Peter Boulware beat him with an outside 
rush. Couch fumbled, the Ravens recovered and went on to score a 
touchdown that made the score 10-0. 
</P>
<P>
	But Brown questioned Palmer's decision to have Couch pass out of  
the shotgun with Cleveland facing a third-and-26 deep in its 
territory. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't put a young quarterback in that position, having to  
make something big right there,'' Brown said. ``I know I'm going to 
get in trouble for this, but my whole thing is, we needed to run 
the ball, try a draw and kick it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are too many things going against you. You can't audible  
because the linemen can't hear you. It's all about punt and playing 
defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately for Cleveland, punting and playing defense have  
been what most of the first three games have been about. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
