<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Confidence Slips in Sept. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consumer confidence weakened in September for  
the third consecutive month, suggesting that Federal Reserve moves 
to raise interest rates are cooling off the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, analysts looking at the Conference Board's survey results  
on Tuesday said they expect retail sales to remain strong as the 
holiday season approaches. 
</P>
<P>
	The report added to jitters on Wall Street, where stocks tumbled  
in afternoon trading, at one point pushing the Dow Jones industrial 
average down 222 points before it roared back, recovering nearly 
all its lost ground bit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow ended the day down 27.86 at 10,275.53.  
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the consumer confidence report was not a major  
influence on trading. Stocks have been retreating from record 
heights on worries about upcoming corporate earnings, interest 
rates and the decline of the dollar against the Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board said its index of consumer confidence,  
which is a measure of consumers' willingness to spend, dipped to 
134.2 in September, 1.8 percentage points lower than a revised 136 
reading in August. 
</P>
<P>
	That was a greater drop than analysts had expected; their  
prediction was 135.4. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists noted, however, that the latest level wasn't far  
below the June index peak of 139, which was the highest reading in 
more than 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite the September dip, confidence levels are still at  
historically high levels,'' said Lynn Franco, director of the 
Conference Board's consumer research center. ``We anticipate no 
dramatic shifts soon in consumer spending patterns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rosalind Wells, chief economist for the Washington-based  
National Retail Federation trade group, agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Employment is strong, income is strong, (consumer) confidence  
is still very high,'' she said. ``I don't see anything that will 
stop consumers from buying. I see a good holiday season upcoming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer sentiment is a closely watched indicator because  
consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the nation's overall 
economic activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve has twice this year raised interest rates to  
try to keep the economy from overheating and to head off a 
resurgence of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Fed policy-makers meet next on Oct. 5, and some economists  
believe they could raise rates again if retail sales continue to 
surge as they have in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerald D. Cohen, a senior economist at Merrill Lynch in New  
York, said September's consumer confidence reading was consistent 
with predictions ``for some moderation in consumer spending over 
the next couple of quarters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``'Moderation' is the key word here,'' he added, suggesting  
there won't be a steep drop-off in retail sales this Christmas 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen also expects the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates  
again before year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary R. Thayer, chief economist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in  
St. Louis, said the September index ``shows some cooling'' in 
consumer confidence and added that ``I won't be surprised to see 
some further weakness in October.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This, he said, should be ``good news for the Fed'' and said  
there was just a 50-50 chance the Fed would raise rates before 
year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board's report, which is based on a sample of  
5,000 American households, said consumer expectations about the 
future also weakened in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The index of expectations slipped to 105.7 this month from 109.2  
in August and was the lowest reading since March's 105.5. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 7.1 percent of respondents said they expected business  
conditions to worsen in the next six months, while 16.4 percent 
expected them to improve. The rest said they expected no change. 
</P>
<P>
	Those figures were more pessimistic than in August. Employment  
expectations also declined. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey by the Conference Board, a business-financed research  
group, uses a baseline of 100, set in 1985. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
