<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Paul A. Andrulonis    	
</P>
<P>
	WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Dr. Paul A. ``Tony'' Andrulonis, an  
internationally known expert in child and adolescent psychiatry, 
died Sunday of a heart attack. He was 53. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrulonis was director of child and adolescent psychiatry at  
Hartford Hospital's Institute of Living and the Connecticut 
Children's Medical Center in Hartford. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was a consultant to the state Department of Children and  
Families and was involved in improving psychiatric services in 
former Soviet Bloc countries and in Haiti. 
</P>
<P>
	He was working with the state to upgrade programs at Long Lane  
School for juvenile offenders in Middletown. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrulonis also worked with the Wallingford-based Albert  
Schweitzer Institute to help organize academic conferences in 
Eastern Europe designed to help improve psychiatric care for 
children. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Jim Foxworthy    	
</P>
<P>
	LEESBURG, Ala. (AP) -- Comedian Jeff Foxworthy's father, Jim  
Foxworthy, was killed Monday when the car he was driving collided 
with a truck on a rain-slickened road in this east Alabama town. He 
was 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Chief Terrell Ransum said Foxworthy was alone in his  
vehicle at the time of the accident. Two men in the truck suffered 
minor injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Ransum said the elder Foxworthy owned a restaurant and was  
co-owner of a campground. 

</P>
<P>
                         *U.C. Ferguson Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Retired golf pro U.C. Ferguson Jr., who  
taught former Women's U.S. Open champion Susie Maxwell Berning, 
died Sunday. He was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferguson was credited with building Lincoln Park Golf Course  
into one of the country's best public courses. He worked at the 
course for 61 years and taught many of Oklahoma City's junior 
golfers how to play the game. 
</P>
<P>
	One of his most notable proteges was Berning, who won the  
Women's U.S. Open in 1968, 1972 and 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferguson was inducted into the Oklahoma Sports Hall of Fame in  
1996. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Don Sanders    	
</P>
<P>
	JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Don Sanders, a former Senate lawyer  
who revealed the existence of a recording system in Richard Nixon's 
White House, died Sunday after a long battle with cancer. He was 
69. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders had returned to his home state in the 1980s after more  
than two decades of federal government service -- as a lawyer for 
congressional committees, as an FBI agent and as an assistant 
secretary of defense under President Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders was the GOP staff lawyer on the Senate Watergate  
Committee who first asked then-presidential aide Alexander 
Butterfield whether there was a recording system in Nixon's White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	After Butterfield confirmed that there was, Sanders said he  
rushed to tell Fred Thompson, the lead minority counsel and now a 
Republican senator from Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1959 to 1969, Sanders was an FBI agent. In 1969, he started  
working as a lawyer for congressional committees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
