<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Down, Gold Continues Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mostly lower today against  
other major currencies in European trading. Gold prices extended 
Monday's sharp increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0473, up from $1.0440 Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Monday included 106.17  
Japanese yen, down from 106.19; 1.5298 Swiss francs, down from 
1.5340, and 1.4666 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4694. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6475, down from $1.6478.  
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8675 German marks, down from 1.8743; 
6.2633 French francs, down from 6.2855; 2.1042 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.1120, and 1,848.82 Italian lire, down from 1,855.55. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold dealers in London fixed a recommended price of $288.25 per  
troy ounce at midmorning, up from $279.90 on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid was $288.50, up from $280.93.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold rose $5.75 in Hong Kong to $288.75.  
</P>
<P>
	The rebound in gold prices followed the announcement on Sunday  
by 15 central banks that they would limit their combined sales of 
bullion to 400 tons per year for a total of five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver opened in London at $5.37 per troy ounce, up from $5.36.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
