<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Sept. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Grandparents Rights To Be Decided  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court set the stage today for a  
ruling on grandparents' rights to see their grandchildren even when 
parents object -- a case that could affect laws in all 50 states. 
The nine justices -- six of them with grandchildren of their own -- 
agreed to decide whether a state can give visitation rights to 
grandparents when, after a divorce or other family split, the 
children's parents say no. The case involves Washington state, 
where the state's highest court ruled that such a law violates 
parents' ``fundamental right'' to rear their families without 
governmental interference. All other states have similar laws. 

</P>
<P>
	Supreme Court To Review Rape Law  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court agreed today to review the  
constitutionality of a federal law that lets rape victims sue their 
attackers. It may test how far Congress can go in fighting sex 
discrimination. The justices, who have curtailed Congress in recent 
years, will decide whether a former Virginia Tech student, Christy 
Brzonkala, can sue two college football players under the 1994 
Violence Against Women Act. She says they raped her. A federal 
appeals court had thrown out the lawsuit. 

</P>
<P>
	Encephalitis May Migrate Via Birds  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A rare African strain of encephalitis that has  
already killed four people around New York City could spread to 
other parts of the country as infected birds fly south for the 
winter, health officials said. The virus is transmitted to humans 
by mosquitoes that have bitten infected birds. New York City and 
New Jersey have been spraying pesticides to kill mosquitoes, and 
scientists in southern states are testing dead birds there for the 
virus. The African strain has never before been seen in the Western 
Hemisphere. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Offers Health Care Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley  
proposed a $65 billion plan today for universal access to health 
insurance. His plan would require coverage for all children, with 
subsidies for families that cannot afford it. Under Bradley's plan, 
individuals of all ages and incomes also would be able to exclude 
from their taxable income whatever they pay for health premiums. 
Parents would also be required to obtain health insurance for their 
children. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Moved by Forgiveness  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A year after confessing to sin and apologizing  
for scandal, President Clinton said today he has been profoundly 
moved ``by the pure power of grace'' and forgiveness from his 
family, associates and American citizens. ``Last year was one of 
the most difficult years in my life,'' Clinton told ministers 
gathered at the White House for Clinton's annual prayer breakfast. 
At the same event last September, a moist-eyed Clinton apologized 
for the Monica Lewinsky sex-and-cover-up scandal that later led to 
his impeachment in the House and acquittal in the Senate. 

</P>
<P>
	House OKs Stopgap Spending Measure  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eyeing Friday's start of fiscal 2000, the  
House today approved a stopgap measure that will keep federal 
agencies functioning for three weeks as President Clinton and 
Republicans sort through spending disputes. Prior to the vote, 
Democrats blamed unyielding Republican demands for Congress' 
failure to complete most of the 13 spending bills on time, a 
failure that is nearly an annual event. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Students Can't Write Well  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About three-fourths of the nation's school  
children demonstrated only partial mastery of the knowledge and 
skills needed to write proficiently for their grade level, the 
Education Department reported today. Testers asked 60,000 
fourth-graders, eighth-graders and 12th-graders to write stories, 
personal essays, reports about events or experiences and persuasive 
pieces. Roughly one-fourth of the students in each grade level were 
at least proficient. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 27.86  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- At the close on Wall Street, the Dow was down  
27.86 at 10,275.53 after having fallen more than 222 points early 
in the afternoon. It marked the Dow's fifth drop in six sessions. 
Decliners outnumbered advancers on the New York Stock Exchange 
1,898-1,232. The Nasdaq composite index was off 5.48 at 2,756.27. 

</P>
<P>
	Las Vegas Seeks NHL, NBA Teams  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Las Vegas mayor Oscar Goodman spent today  
visiting NBA commissioner David Stern and NHL commissioner Gary 
Bettman, hoping the leagues will consider his city for franchises. 
Neither the NHL or NBA is considering any expansion and both 
Bettman and Stern said their leagues had no teams seeking to switch 
cities. Gambling is a particularly thorny issue with the NBA. 
Basketball betting accounts for 23 percent of the total sports 
handle in Las Vegas, according to Vegas Sports Consultants, which 
helps set betting lines for sports books. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
