<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Plummet; Dow Down 148.49 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks plummeted today, falling for the fifth  
time in the past six sessions as traders' concerns about interest 
rates intensified. Buying was scarce amid the paucity of positive 
economic news. 
</P>
<P>
	At late afternoon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 148.49 at 10,154.90 after having fallen more than 
222 points earlier in the session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow slipped more than 200 points in two separate sessions  
last week, and finished the week down 524.30, its biggest weekly 
point loss ever. Only bargain-hunting provided a short-lived uptick 
in the market on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also fell markedly today. The Standard  
&AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 13.93 at 1,269.38, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was off 41.71 at 2,720.04. 
</P>
<P>
	The downturn was particularly severe in the oil, financial  
services and computer sectors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is suffering from a vacuum of positive  
information,'' said John Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist 
at Advest Inc of Hartford, Conn. ``There's no incentives to buy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, investors have to deal with concerns of rising  
interest rates and gold prices and uncertainty regarding the value 
of the dollar vs. the Japanese yen. Although the surge in gold 
prices the past two days has helped gold mining concerns, it also 
may heighten inflation fears, Shaughnessy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board, a research group, said today that consumer  
confidence dipped in September for a third consecutive month. The 
drop was larger than economists had expected, and may be a sign 
that consumer spending will slow. That could in turn influence the 
Fed against boosting interest rates to cool off the economy when 
its policy-setting Open Market Committee meets next Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But the consumer confidence report did little to move the  
markets, which remained anxious and unsettled before the Fed 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a water-torture type of correction,'' said Alfred  
Goldman, chief market strategist for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. 
Louis, of the market's recent performance. Goldman said the Dow 
rose 46 percent from early October through last April, and has been 
in a correction ever since. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that while there is some uncertainty on Wall Street  
about interest rates, most traders expect the Federal Reserve to 
leave interest rates alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett-Packard, down 3 to 93 1/8, and General Electric, down 3  
1/16 to 116 3/4, led the Dow lower. Exxon was off 1 13/16 at 73 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank and financial services companies showed little reaction to  
the latest merger in the sector. Shares of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist were 
up 7 11/16 to 48 3/4, after Chase Manhattan said it would buy the 
brokerage operation, but Chase was off 1 1/4 to 72 7/8, and other bank 
stocks were flat. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar, whose recent weakness was a factor in the market's  
big decline last week, held steady against the Japanese yen today. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, off 1 5/8 to 76 9/16, and Microsoft, off 1 3/16 to 90 1/4, were  
among the falling technology issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna, the largest U.S. health insurer, fell 6 7/16 to 60 1/2 on  
concern the company's profits will be hurt by the purchase of 
Prudential HealthCare it bought earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-1 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 686.56 million 
shares, up from Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index fell 5.77 at 416.05.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
