<DOCNO> APW19990928.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 07:56:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Troubled Japanese Bank To Be Sold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- An international investment group plans to acquire  
debt-laden Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan Ltd. in what would be the 
first foreign acquisition of a major Japanese bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal disclosed today represents a step forward in the  
government's efforts to clean up loan problems that has suffocated 
the banking industry since Japanese property prices collapsed in 
the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Reconstruction Commission announced it had  
approved the deal, and that the investment group organized by the 
private U.S. equity firm Ripplewood Holdings LLC had signed a 
memorandum of understanding on the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripplewood, based in New York City, has specialized in buying  
struggling small-to-midsize companies and making them profitable. 
It hopes to reach a final deal for LTCB by the end of November. 
</P>
<P>
	Other proposed investors in the New LTCB include GE Capital  
Corp., Mellon Bank Corp., ABN-Amro Bank, PaineWebber Group and 
Deutsche Bank. Former U.S. Federal Reserve chairman Paul Volcker is 
a senior advisor to the group. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese companies like Chuo Trust and Banking Co. and Mitsui  
Trust and Banking Co. had been in the running to acquire LTCB. 
</P>
<P>
	LTCB, once one of Japan's biggest banks, was nationalized last  
October after regulators determined it would never recover from a 
mountain of bad loans. It was the first time the Japanese 
government had taken over a bank since World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to restore LTCB to its former status as a premier  
financial institution as quickly as possible, so it can contribute 
to the financial stability of Japan,'' said LTCB's new chairman and 
chief executive, Masamoto Yashiro. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese government will inject $2.26 billion into a  
reformed LTCB on condition that the Ripplewood group continue loans 
to the bank's troubled borrowers, according to an FCR official who 
briefed reporters on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The new owners will acquire LTCB shares by paying $9.43 million  
to the Deposit Insurance Corp., the Japanese government finance 
body which is now LTCB's sole shareholder, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yashiro, formerly a non-executive chairman of Citicorp Japan,  
said that the new bank will try to expand its individual and 
corporate business. It will remain a Japanese-oriented bank in the 
initial years, Yashiro said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said eight of the 15 top board members are expected to be  
Japanese ``because they would understand the Japanese market 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Timothy Collins, founder of Ripplewood who will join LTCB's  
board, said he hoped to play a role in Japan's economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins said that although there are structural problems in  
Japan's economy, he wanted to ``find an area to restructure the 
Japanese economy and provide strategic advice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the deal was likely to have a positive impact on  
Japan's inefficient banking industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ripplewood will take it through restructuring you haven't seen  
here, and there will be big pressure on others to follow suit,'' 
said James Fiorillo, a banking analyst at ING Barings in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	FRC chief Hakuo Yanagisawa welcomed the deal. ``Japanese  
financial institutions are far worse than Western counterparts in 
profitability,'' he said. ``New LTCB made it clear they will focus 
on fixing this problem. We hope this will become reality and affect 
(other Japanese financial institutions) positively.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LTCB and the Ripplewood group hope to reach a final agreement by  
Nov. 30, and the government may extend the period if needed. 
</P>
<P>
	The FRC, a Japanese government body overseeing banking industry  
reform, has been discussing LTCB's transfer since the middle of 
this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale is likely to speed up the process of opening Japan's  
financial industry to foreign firms, a pillar of the country's 
financial reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shows the government's commitment to creating a level  
playing field, and that it and won't even let nationalism get in 
the way of what needs to be done,'' ING Barings' Fiorillo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of LTCB's bad debt was the result of aggressive lending to  
real estate developers before property prices in Japan collapsed in 
the early 1990s. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
