<HEADLINE> Sony To Close Boca Raton Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) -- Sony Electronics is closing a factory  
that makes broadcast equipment, eliminating 200 jobs as it moves 
the work overseas to cut costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony opened the factory in 1991 in Boca Raton where it makes  
large digital broadcast studio cameras for television networks and 
commercial stations as well as professional broadcast editing 
equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, the 116,800-square-foot plant was Sony's main  
manufacturing site outside Japan for audio and visual recording 
equipment. Now, the work will be transferred to other plants, 
primarily in the United Kingdom and Japan, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Employees will be offered severance pay, retraining assistance  
and possible job transfers to Sony's nine other manufacturing 
plants around United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer electronics and entertainment company is closing  
the plant as part of a restructuring announced in March. The 
company said it would lay off 17,000 of its 170,000 employees and 
cut its manufacturing plants from 70 to 55 during the next four 
years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
