<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House, Senate Dealing on Farm Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional Republican leaders tried to  
break a logjam on an agricultural spending bill by offering 
farm-state lawmakers a compromise that would provide $8.7 billion 
to financially stressed producers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, within the week we'll have an agreement,'' Senate  
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed deal would add $1.2 billion in disaster relief to  
an aid package approved by the Senate in August and omit dairy and 
trade provisions that has delayed passage of the farm bailout for 
the past week. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear whether the Republicans could get necessary  
support for the deal in the House-Senate conference committee that 
would have to approve the final version of the spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal won a major convert on the panel, Rep. Tom Latham,  
R-Iowa, when House leaders agreed to add a provision to require 
meatpackers to start reporting prices they pay for livestock. 
</P>
<P>
	Farm groups complained that the disaster relief remains  
insufficient, and Democrats reacted angrily to word of the proposed 
agreement, complaining that they had been excluded from the 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are trying to write the bill with a few leaders and a few  
staffers. In the end, we will not be able to produce good 
legislation,'' said Rep. Marcy Kaptur, D-Ohio, a member of the 
conference committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've not seen the package. Never heard of it,'' said another  
of the panel's Democrats, Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D. 
</P>
<P>
	The House leadership floated a similar proposal last week but  
was rebuffed by farm organizations and members of the conference 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to removing any mention of dairy policy, the  
proposed deal would kill a Senate amendment that would allow sales 
of food and medicine to Cuba and make it difficult for a president 
to include such items in future embargoes. 
</P>
<P>
	The dairy dispute involves an Agriculture Department overhaul of  
milk pricing that is scheduled to take effect Friday. Lawmakers in 
the South and East want to use the spending bill to block the new 
system, as well as win congressional authority for states to get 
together to set prices. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one major farm organization, the American Farm Bureau  
Federation, urged lawmakers Tuesday to reject the proposed deal 
because it failed to include the dairy and trade provisions or 
enough money to cover farmers' weather-related losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration had raised objections to both the  
dairy and trade measures. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott was under pressure from a fellow Republican, Sen. James  
Jeffords of Vermont, to insist on the dairy measure because it 
would keep alive a New England pricing compact that will otherwise 
end this week. Jeffords is up for re-election in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	But by Tuesday afternoon, Jeffords had all but given up his  
effort. Asked what he was doing to save the New England compact, he 
replied, ``Praying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was discussion of putting the dairy issue to a separate  
vote in the Senate this week, but that appeared to be doomed with 
the threat of a filibuster by Wisconsin senators who support USDA's 
new pricing system. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing is ever over, but it appears to me that the odds of  
the (dairy) policy changing via legislation are not good,'' said 
Senate Agriculture Chairman Richard Lugar, R-Ind. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
