<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vols' Coach Downplays Distractions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A loss to Florida, a near-loss to lowly  
Memphis, the arrest of starting cornerback Dwayne Goodrich and now 
an academic fraud investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a tough 10 days for coach Phillip Fulmer and defending  
national champion Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	Fulmer insisted Tuesday the problems off the field won't be a  
distraction when Auburn (3-1 overall, 1-1 Southeastern Conference) 
visits the No. 7 Vols (2-1, 0-1). 
</P>
<P>
	``The season's just starting,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Fulmer wouldn't discuss accusations of academic fraud, which is  
the subject of an internal investigation by the university's 
general counsel. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN said it obtained internal memos that show high-level  
administrators in Tennessee's athletic department were told of four 
tutors who may have done schoolwork for at least five football 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the information was passed on to campus authorities  
charged with investigating possible rules infractions, according to 
Malcolm McInnis, NCAA compliance officer for Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	If the allegations are proven, Tennessee could face punishment  
by the NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	Four redshirt freshmen, including kick returner and NCAA  
champion sprinter Leonard Scott, were held out of the Memphis game 
on Saturday and placed on indefinite suspension as a result of the 
school's internal investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	On top of that, Goodrich, one of the team captains, was arrested  
early Sunday and charged with disorderly conduct. Police allege he 
was drunk and threatened officers who asked him to leave a 
convenience store near campus. 
</P>
<P>
	Fulmer announced Tuesday that Goodrich is suspended from  
Saturday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dwayne is a fine young man who made an error in judgment,''  
Fulmer said. ``He apologized to the team without me asking him to, 
and looks forward to having this incident behind him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodrich said he ``thoroughly respects'' Fulmer's decision.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think coach Fulmer handled it real well. We run a clean  
program here and I totally respect his decision,'' Goodrich said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee's problems off the field come as the team looks to  
regroup and regain confidence after a 23-21 loss to arch-rival 
Florida and 17-16 victory over Memphis in which the Tigers (1-3) 
outplayed the Vols. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're fortunate to be 2-1,'' Fulmer said.  
</P>
<P>
	Fulmer said the Vols' problems on the field start with him and  
include every coach and player. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're all accountable,'' he said. ``It's everybody's fault.''  
</P>
<P>
	He said the problems in the Memphis game, in which the Vols  
managed just 10 first downs and 216 yards, were a combination of 
poor play by the Vols and good defense by the Tigers. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Vols were lackluster all week in practice and played  
that way coming off the emotional loss at Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to pay attention to detail from a coaching standpoint,  
and make sure the players are listening,'' he said. ``It does no 
good for the coaches to know something if the players don't. It's 
mostly offensively. Our defense has played pretty well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the offense has struggled at times. Although the Vols  
drove 78 yards in seven plays in the waning minutes to get the 
victory over Memphis, tailback Jamal Lewis was held to a career-low 
45 yards and quarterback Tee Martin was mediocre outside the final 
drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Another factor contributing to the slow start goes beyond the  
last two weeks, Fulmer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't assume just because you're good one year you'll be  
good the next,'' he said. ``I think that was part of the problem.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
