<HEADLINE> Europe: Gold Up; Dollar Mostly Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Gold extended its sharp rebound today, closing  
above $300 an ounce in Europe to reach its highest level in almost 
a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. dollar rose against the Japanese yen but fell against  
most other major currencies in European trading today. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $301.50 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$279.90 on Monday and the highest level since Oct. 2, 1998, when it 
also finished the day at $301.50. In Zurich the bid price was 
$301.02 an ounce, up from $280.93. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebound in gold prices followed the announcement on Sunday  
by 15 central banks that they would limit their combined sales of 
bullion for five years. Gold in London had closed Friday at $268.60 
an ounce and had traded at 20-year lows approaching $250 in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, gold rose $5.75 in Hong Kong to $288.75 an ounce.  
That compared to $281.80 in New York late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.65 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.36. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar, which is recovering from a 3 1/2-year low against  
Japan's currency, nudged up to 106.23 yen today in Europe from 
106.19 yen late Monday. In afternoon trading in New York, the 
dollar bought 106.09 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro rose to $1.0498 in Europe from $1.0440 Monday and the  
British pound climbed to $1.6492 from $1.6478. In New York, the 
euro was quoted at $1.05.15 and the pound was worth $1.6480 this 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Monday: 1.5260  
Swiss francs, down from 1.5340, and 1.4631 Canadian dollars, down 
from 1.4694. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth: 1.8634 German marks, down from 1.8743; 
6.2538 French francs, down from 6.2855; 2.1004 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.1120; and 1,845.47 Italian lire, down from 1,855.55. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
