<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Co. Woes Said To Delay Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Steel companies hammered by competition from  
imports are being restrained from investing in crucial technology, 
industry observers at an engineering expo said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There continues to be a hunger and a very pressing need for  
new technology and lower cost approaches,'' said R. Lee Sholley, 
president of the Pittsburgh-based Association of Iron and Steel 
Engineers, which is holding its annual Iron and Steel Exposition in 
Cleveland this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Likewise, there continues to be an increasing amount of  
opportunity out there in the form of technology,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the question for U.S. steel producers is how to invest in  
modern, low-cost methods while holding prices low enough to be 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``This industry has a real crisis in accessing capital today,''  
said Edward R. Caine, president and chief executive officer of 
Warren, Ohio-based WCI Steel Inc. ``It's simply because of the 
cloud hung over it because of unfairly traded imports. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care how well run and managed a company is, whether  
it's marginally profitable or in Chapter 11 (bankruptcy 
reorganization), they are all facing that same issue of how do you 
attract scarce capital into a business where you've got to have 
capital to invest and be low cost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The five-day exposition features 74 technical panel discussions  
and about 500 exhibitors displaying such technologies as sensors, 
filters, pumps, bar codes and computerized manufacturing controls. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration and the U.S. steel industry have been  
closely monitoring the monthly import figures for signs of fewer 
low-priced imports from Japan, Russia and other nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the administration has been promoting free trade, it has  
been reluctant to impose tariffs sought by the industry. The 
administration said Monday it will hold a series of talks with 
Japan about last year's surge in Japanese steel shipments to the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I'd like to see is a system more like Canada has, in  
which you allow people to import into the United States, but before 
they do they need an import license,'' said John Correnti, an 
industry consultant who is the former Nucor Corp. chief executive 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone on the exhibit floor was downbeat about trade  
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think most of the issues are settled. I think there's not so  
much tension,'' said Takeshi Iwasaki, general manager of the metals 
machinery division of Mitsubishi Heavy Industries America Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the U.S. steel industry might still ``face tough years  
the coming year or two.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
