<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Notre Dame Win Is Biggest to Tiller </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Undefeated No. 11 Purdue against undefeated  
No. 4 Michigan looks, and is, a huge game. Yet Purdue coach Joe 
Tiller said it's not the biggest in his turnaround of the 
Boilermakers program. 
</P>
<P>
	That distinction rests with a victory over Notre Dame in 1997,  
Tiller's first year at Purdue. 
</P>
<P>
	``In '97 when we were able to beat Notre Dame after Purdue had  
lost to them for a dozen or more years in a row. That was a huge 
game for the program, and will probably go down as maybe the game 
that allowed us to kind of springboard into the future,'' Tiller 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``From that standpoint, (Saturday's) game is not the biggest  
that we've played in,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue and Michigan both are 4-0 and 1-0 in the Big Ten. For  
Purdue, it marks the start of a challenging string of games that 
continues with games against No. 12 Ohio State, No. 14 Michigan 
State and No. 2 Penn State on consecutive Saturdays. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an unbelievable stretch,'' Tiller said. ``It will be a  
real test for us, but I think we've got to lighten up and enjoy the 
moment, the opportunity to play this level or caliber of 
competition. ... That's a difficult draw for anybody, but that's 
the way the schedule has been set, so we plan on being there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue is playing Michigan and Ohio State back-to-back on the  
road, two teams it hasn't played since Tiller brought his spread 
offense from Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiller sees a Michigan team that has changed its offensive  
philosophy away from one that was dominated by a potent ground 
game. Statistics prove the assessment. Michigan is averaging 117.8 
yards per game rushing and 223.8 passing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see them attempting to rush as much as they have in  
the past. I see some different formations out of Michigan,'' Tiller 
said. ``There's a lot of one-back stuff showing up, people spread 
out. I don't remember those formations at Ann Arbor. I think their 
offense is diversified. ... When I look at their overall physical 
scheme, it's set to throw the ball to big, physical wide 
receivers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Wolverines have been utilizing two quarterbacks this season  
with senior Tom Brady starting and sophomore Drew Henson coming off 
the sideline. Brady is 49-of-76 for 555 yards, Henson 32-of-58 for 
340. Tiller sees little difference between the two. 
</P>
<P>
	``They almost look like clones in the sense that they're both  
tall, physical guys. They both have very strong arms. You would 
think, normally, when a team rotates quarterbacks, you see a little 
bit of change in play selection,'' Tiller said. ``As far as 
Michigan is concerned, it doesn't seem to matter which one is in, 
the offense continues to move along with the same preferences. ... 
The impressive thing is they make good decisions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue will be seeking to reach 5-0 for the first time since  
1945 and extend a 10-game winning streak that is the school's 
longest since it won 11 straight in 1928-30. 
</P>
<P>
	Drew Brees, who moves up among Purdue career leaders in passing  
statistics with every outing, has been a major factor in the 
winning streak. He was selected Big Ten offensive player of the 
week after completing 32 of 50 passes for 405 yards and three 
touchdowns in Saturday's 31-23 victory over Northwestern. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning football games is what Drew is all about,'' Tiller  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
