<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Chief Wants Aid for Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An international development program to help  
the world's poorest nations is needed to parallel the new global 
financial sytsem, World Bank President James Wolfensohn said today. 
</P>
<P>
	He said coalitions involving these nations with U.N.  
organizations, governments, multilateral institutions, the private 
sector and civil society would play a major role in shaping the new 
``development architecture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be a coalition in which we recognize that, yes, we  
must break the chains of debt,'' Wolfensohn said,'' but we must 
also have the resources to go much further and break the chains of 
poverty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfensohn addressed the annual meetings of the bank and its  
sister institution, the International Monetary Fund after being 
reappointed to serve a second five-year term as head of the 
182-nation organization. 
</P>
<P>
	IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus and Treasury Secretary  
Lawrence Summers also were speaking to hundreds of finance 
ministers and central bank governors in the cavernous ballroom of a 
Washington hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	After the global financial crisis of the past two years rocked  
markets around the world, governments, the IMF and the World Bank 
made changes to produce what they called the new global financial 
architecture. 
</P>
<P>
	These changes included requiring governments to make public more  
financial information and better regulate their banking systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfensohn said his new development architecture would ``build  
coalitions for change, coalitions with the private sector which 
will bring investment, create jobs, promote the transfer of 
technology and skills and foster social responsibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said ``bringing corruption in the glare of the sunlight''  
also was an important part of helping poor countries to develop. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told the World Bank-IMF  
meetings Monday that emerging market countries need a spare tire -- 
sound banks and alternative sources of money -- if they want to 
avoid future Asian-style currency crises or lessen their damage. 
</P>
<P>
	The global financial crisis of the past two years, Greenspan  
said, emphasized the necessity for these countries to pay attention 
to issues such as bank regulation and whether the right steps are 
being taken to build sound financial systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Improving deficiencies in domestic banking systems in emerging  
markets will help to limit the toll of the next financial 
disturbance,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said the chief lessons learned from the Asian economic  
crisis were that countries with narrow capital markets in which 
there are no alternatives to banks suffer greater economic 
disruption than those with diverse capital markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``East Asia had no spare tires,'' Greenspan said in his speech.  
``Banks, being highly leveraged institutions, have throughout their 
history periodically fallen into crisis. When there was no backup, 
they pulled their economies down with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said countries increase the cost of recovery when they  
don't act promptly to deal with a financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Global financial turmoil began in Thailand in July 1997 with a  
currency devaluation, then spread to Indonesia and South Korea 
later that year. The following summer Russia's economy collapsed 
and then Brazil had to devalue its currency in January. 
</P>
<P>
	``The failure of normal adjustment processes to contain the  
financial turmoil made this crisis longer and deeper than any of us 
had expected in its early days,'' Greenspan said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 10:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Many Unhappy With Reagan Biography </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ronald Reagan's authorized biography is coming  
under fire from Reagan's eldest child and former President Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Maureen Reagan says that based on the excerpts she read and the  
interviews she heard with biographer Edmund Morris, she has 
concluded he ``wasted an incredible and irreplaceable 
opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I have decided that I have read all the fiction about Ronald  
Reagan I intend to read -- so I think I will pass on this book,'' 
she said in a statement from Sacramento, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	George Bush denied Morris' claim in ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald  
Reagan'' that he and his wife were unwelcome ``upstairs'' in the 
Reagan White House when he was vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's ridiculous,'' he said in an interview shown today on  
NBC's ``Today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Upstairs? I mean that's a kind of English,  
upstairs-and-downstairs approach to life. ``I don't even use the 
terminology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris writes of a Christmas Eve 1988 conversation he said he  
had with the Bushes a month before Bush became president. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really love that guy, he's such a terrific fellow,'' Bush is  
quoted as saying. Morris then quotes Bush as commenting about 
Reagan and his wife, Nancy: ``I kinda wished they'd shown -- 
'y'know, a little appreciation. Didn't seem to want us upstairs in 
the White House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said in the NBC interview that he never felt unappreciated.  
``Ronald Reagan had and Nancy had friends that were closer friends 
than the Bushes. ... We never felt we were unwelcome some place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Morris' characterization of Reagan as an ``apparent  
airhead,'' Bush said: ``That is brutal and grossly unfair and 
untrue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said his working relationship with Reagan was ``heaven,  
total access, a totally relaxed relationship. From my point of view 
I couldn't have asked for a better mentor. He was a joy to work 
with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maureen Reagan is described in passages of ``Dutch'' excerpted  
by Newsweek as ``the eldest and largest of the president's 
children, her brilliant smile and button nose reminding the world 
that there once was another Mrs. Reagan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She ``sings and acts well, memorizes like a VCR and luxuriates  
in the spotlight,'' Morris wrote, saying she could have made a 
career in show business if she only had the figure of Jane Wyman, 
her mother and Reagan's first wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris was granted close access to Reagan during his second  
term. Although the book is not being released until Thursday, it 
has already created a stir with historians and former Reagan aides, 
in part because Morris inserts himself as a semi-fictional 
character. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suspect when all is said and done, given the unprecedented  
access graciously provided the author, the American people will 
conclude that the author wasted an incredible and irreplaceable 
opportunity,'' Maureen Reagan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris told CBS' ``60 Minutes'' he expects Nancy Reagan to be  
disturbed by the book because, despite his admiration for the 
ex-president, ``I do not hide the fact that Reagan was frequently 
an old, spaced-out man, inattentive to details.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book, a copy of which was obtained by The Associated Press,  
devotes about 250 pages of text to the Reagan presidency in its 874 
pages of text and notes. 
</P>
<P>
	Reagan biographer Lou Cannon told CBS that Morris' contribution  
could have been ``to tell us what went on during the presidency 
and, with very few exceptions, he doesn't.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
