<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miss America Pageant CEO Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Miss America Pageant officials, still  
reeling from a controversy over whether to allow contestants who 
have had abortions or been divorced, have a new problem: Their boss 
has been fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Pageant chief executive Robert Beck was fired Sunday, nearly two  
weeks after it was revealed that the pageant had approved new rules 
-- which have since been shelved -- that would have dropped the 
nearly 50-year ban on contestants who've been married or undergone 
abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Beck, Miss America board chairman David Frisch nor  
pageant spokesman John Healy would comment in detail on Monday's 
announcement. It came a day after the pageant board voted to 
release Beck from his three-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``While the board acknowledged Mr. Beck's contributions to the  
Miss America program during the 12 months that he served as 
president and CEO, they agreed that selecting a new chief executive 
was in the best interests of the Organization at this time,'' 
Frisch's statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Healy would not say whether Beck was fired because of the  
rules-change fiasco. The changes have been put on hold pending 
talks with state pageant officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Beck also had little to tell, saying today he was not ready to  
talk about his dismissal publicly. ``I can't, at this stage, give 
you my side of it.'' He would not say when he would make a 
statement or whether he planned to sue over the move. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just speculating, but there has to be more than the  
contract issue,'' said Libby Taylor, who runs the Miss Kentucky 
Pageant and went to court to stop the board from enacting the new 
rules. ``I'll be interested to find out what really happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ed Coleman, executive director of the Miss Memphis Pageant, said  
local pageant directors were upset with the new rules because they 
would have struck at the heart of the ``ideal'' that Miss America 
is supposed to embody. 
</P>
<P>
	Beck got the $250,000-a-year job on the strength of a resume  
that included work with the U.S. Soccer Federation Foundation and 
the national advocacy group Mothers Against Drunk Driving. He had a 
son killed by a drunken driver in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	But he came under fire after The Associated Press reported Sept.  
13 that the pageant had quietly revoked its long-standing ban on 
divorce and abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	The move was initially recommended by Steven Perskie, a pageant  
lawyer who was asked to review and update the contestant contract 
that must be signed by Miss America hopefuls. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes were made to bring the contract into compliance with  
state anti-discrimination law, according to court documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Approved by the pageant's 21-member board last June but never  
made public, the changes outraged state pageant directors, former 
winners and other Miss America pageant traditionalists. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
