<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Tiger Ron LeFlore Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Former Detroit Tigers outfielder Ron LeFlore was  
arrested following closing ceremonies at Tiger Stadium on charges 
he failed to pay $57,000 in child support to his ex-wife. 
</P>
<P>
	LeFlore, 51, was one of many Tigers greats who assembled -- in  
uniform -- for the stadium's final game Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after the lights dimmed for the last time at the stadium  
about 9 p.m., Wayne County Sheriff's deputies approached him near 
the locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't want to interfere with the final ceremonies of the  
Tigers,'' Sheriff Robert Ficano said this morning. ``We were able 
to work out the circumstances once the ceremonies were done and he 
was changed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ex-wife Deborah Lewis, who lives in the area, had called  
authorities when she learned LeFlore would be part of the closing 
ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the most pleasant thing to do, but once we have  
knowledge of his whereabouts, we have an obligation,'' Ficano said. 
``He was completely cooperative. I don't know if he was completely 
surprised, I guess he was a little surprised.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LeFlore, a speedy baserunner who played with the Tigers from  
1974-79, was named in a Wayne County Circuit Court bench warrant in 
1993, Ficano said. 
</P>
<P>
	LeFlore, now a Florida resident, spent the night in the county  
jail. Before joining the Tigers in 1974, he served time in prison 
for armed robbery. His story was the basis for a movie, ``One In A 
Million'' in 1978. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
