<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates Health Care Positions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Snapshot: An estimated 43.4 million Americans have no health  
insurance, including 11 million children. 
</P>
<P>
	Positions of Democratic and Republican presidential candidates  
on expanding health coverage: 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats:  
</P>
<P>
	Bill Bradley: Ensure universal access to affordable health  
coverage by fully or partially subsidizing premiums for children 
and adults in low- to middle-income families and by offering 
everyone a tax break for premiums. Expand Medicare by adding 
optional prescription drug benefit with $500 deductible, $25 
premium and 25 percent co-pay. Total estimated annual cost: Up to 
$65 billion, to be paid for from non-Social Security budget surplus 
and program efficiencies. Latest projections of non-Social Security 
surplus: $82 billion, 2002; $75 billion, 2003; $85 billion, 2004; 
$92 billion, 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore: Give states more money to provide health  
coverage for children. Children in families earning up to 250 
percent of poverty level would qualify for federally supported 
state coverage, up from 200 percent now. Families earning more and 
lacking insurance could buy into the state program. Goal: All 
children covered by 2005. Cost: Unspecified. Also: 25 percent 
refundable tax credit for premiums for self-employed; long-term 
care tax credit. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans:  
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer: Expand option of medical savings accounts -- tax-free  
accounts people can use for routine health bills and to save up for 
premiums for high-deductible health plans covering major expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan: Allow workers to invest money they would otherwise  
put into Medicare, so they can provide for their own health care in 
retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. George W. Bush: Expand medical savings accounts. Medicare  
means-testing a possibility for federally subsidized premiums. 
Strengthen tax incentives to small businesses that provide health 
care to employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole: Full tax deduction for health insurance for  
self-employed. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes: Expand medical savings accounts.  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Orrin Hatch: Expand medical savings accounts, allow full  
deductibility of health insurance premiums for self-employed. 
Worked with Democrats in Congress to expand health care 
protections. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Keyes: Previously supported medical savings accounts.  
</P>
<P>
	McCain: Expand medical savings accounts, offer full tax  
deductibility for self-employed health insurance and deductibility 
for long-term care. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
