<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Denounces Bank of N.Y. Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A senior aide to President Boris Yeltsin said  
Tuesday that allegations of massive Russian money-laundering 
through a New York bank were invented by the West and government 
opponents at home to tarnish Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has been reluctant to open a major investigation into  
media reports that Russians may have funneled as much as $10 
billion through the Bank of New York. On Tuesday, deputy chief of 
staff Igor Shabdurasulov added his name to the list of Russian 
media and officials who have denounced the whole case as an 
anti-Russian plot. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are grounds to believe that this scandal has to a large  
degree been inspired by circles in Russia and abroad with an aim to 
discredit Russia, humiliate it and push it farther away from making 
important decisions on the international scene,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shabdurasulov wearily dismissed media reports on the case and  
allegations of bribe-taking by Kremlin officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is extremely negative for us, but not fatal,'' he said.  
``We have coped with worse problems. We shall solve this one too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin met with U.S.  
businessmen in New York this week and urged them ``not to fuel 
scandal, but to join forces in returning the Russian money taken to 
the West,'' the Interfax news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Initial reports said the money allegedly laundered through the  
Bank of New York was connected to Russian organized crime, possibly 
with the involvement of Russian officials. But many analysts now 
believe that some of the capital flight could have been legal. 
</P>
<P>
	Mikhail Zadornov, Russia's top negotiator with international  
lenders, said Tuesday that capital flight from Russia reaches from 
$700 million to $1 billion a month. Zadornov dismissed allegations 
that the money was laundered by the mob with officials' 
involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	``After studying the documents I have received, I can definitely  
say that the origin of the money and the essence of the 
transactions are absolutely different from what the world media is 
reporting,'' he said Tuesday, Interfax reported. The report did not 
elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after the Bank of New York scandal began to emerge last  
month, the International Monetary Fund said it would delay the next 
disbursement of a loan to Russia. It said it wanted to scrutinize 
how previous loans have been used. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Mikhail Kasyanov said Tuesday that Russia might  
not receive the next $640 million of the loan until late October. 
In that case, Russia would have to resort to other sources -- likely 
dwindling Central Bank reserves -- to make a payment to the IMF due 
on Oct. 10, he said, according to Interfax. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's latest IMF loan -- $4.5 billion total -- is intended to  
help the cash-strapped government pay back previous debts to the 
fund. The money will simply be transferred from one IMF account to 
another. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
