<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US, China Break Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. and Chinese trade negotiators have broken  
off talks on a major trade deal after only one day of discussions 
although the Clinton administration says the two sides will get 
back together soon. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky met with her  
counterpart, Chinese Trade Minister Shi Guangsheng, for two hours 
Monday morning and then both sides had lower level officials go 
over specific details in various sectors in an afternoon session. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a planned meeting on Tuesday was canceled because Shi  
had to return to Beijing earlier than expected, Barshefsky said 
late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	She said there was ``nothing to be drawn either way'' from the  
fact that this week's discussions were abbreviated. ``There will be 
another meeting. We just haven't figured out the logistics of 
when,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Beijing today, Long Yongtu, China's chief negotiator on the  
talks, said both countries were ``very close'' to an agreement. But 
he said a U.S. list distributed in April of Chinese proposals to 
lower trade barriers contained ``10 to 15 mistakes'' that continue 
to be a source of dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they could work on the basis of our clarifications, I think  
we could have a deal,'' Long said in an interview with CNN. But if 
the U.S. side won't accept those clarifications, ``then I don't 
think we should have a deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Long's comments highlighted the key sticking point in the  
negotiations. U.S. negotiators are struggling to get China to 
commit to at least agree to the list of concessions China put on 
the table in April. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton rejected that offer as not good enough,  
particularly in the area of textiles, where the United States wants 
to commit to further restrictions on its imports to the United 
States beyond what would be allowed under WTO rules. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. businesses and farm groups are anxious for an agreement,  
which would remove barriers they have long complained about that 
limit their sales in China's vast market. In return for removing 
barriers to U.S. goods, China would gain the support it needs from 
the United States for membership in the 134-nation World Trade 
Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before this week's discussions were shortened to one day,  
trade observers said chances for a breakthrough had been lessened 
by the absence of Long from the delegation that traveled to 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Former U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor, who oversaw  
efforts during the Clinton administration's first term to strike a 
China WTO agreement, told a business group Monday that he viewed 
Long's absence as a negative sign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Long is not there, so we have to be somewhat concerned as  
to whether there will be an agreement,'' Kantor said during an 
appearance in Shanghai. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Mastel, global economic policy director at the New America  
Foundation, a Washington think tank, said that Long was ``the man 
who understands all the issues. It is strange that he would not be 
along if they expected to get a deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both countries had come very close to an agreement last April  
but Clinton ultimately decided that the concessions made by Chinese 
Premier Zhu Rongji did not go far enough in certain areas. 
</P>
<P>
	After a number of U.S. business groups criticized the  
administration for failure to obtain an agreement in April, the 
administration pledged to restart the negotiations with an aim of 
sending a completed agreement to Congress in June. 
</P>
<P>
	That deadline passed after China broke off further talks to  
protest the accidental NATO bombing of the Chinese embassy in 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin agreed to restart the  
talks two weeks ago with the aim of getting China into the WTO 
before late November. That's when the Geneva-based organization 
that sets the rules for world trade will launch a new round of 
global trade talks in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	For the trade concessions to take effect, Congress must approve  
them in the form of legislation granting permanent normalized trade 
relations to China. Currently, U.S. trade relations with China are 
subject to annual review. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House accused Republican congressional leaders last  
week of jeopardizing chances for a trade agreement with statements 
indicating there was little or no chance Congress would take up the 
matter this year. 
</P>
<P>
	But House Republican Leader Richard Armey responded with a  
statement saying that once the negotiations were completed, he 
looked forward ``to working hard ... to ensure congressional 
approval of WTO accession.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
