<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge: Navy Not Liable for Spouses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- A federal judge dismissed a lawsuit  
brought by a woman who says the Navy is partly responsible for 
injuries she suffered at the hands of her former husband, a sailor. 
</P>
<P>
	In a ruling made public Monday, U.S. District Court Judge  
Christopher F. Droney in Hartford ruled that the Navy doesn't have 
a special duty to protect the civilian spouses of military 
personnel from domestic abuse, even when commanders are aware of 
the violence and attempt to stop it. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Brenda M. Green argued that the  
government can't be held ``vicariously responsible'' for the 
actions of its personnel. Droney agreed, ruling that even if 
commanders knew of the potential for violence against Annette 
LaFrancis, they did not have a duty to act outside of the 
employer-employee relationship with her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	The doctrine of sovereign immunity limits lawsuits against the  
government, Droney said in dismissing the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, we are disappointed,'' said attorney Chester  
Fairlie, who represents Ms. LaFrancis. ``We believe the decision 
rings a warning bell for a military spouse who is fearful of 
abuse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. LaFrancis sought $500,000 from the Navy, claiming that the  
commanding officers of her former husband, Chief Petty Officer 
Lance LaFrancis, were negligent and failed to issue appropriate 
orders. 
</P>
<P>
	LaFrancis assaulted his wife in 1995 and she was treated a base  
hospital in Groton, the lawsuit said. Navy domestic violence 
advocates recommended anger management for him and family 
counseling, but commanders never followed through on those 
recommendations, Ms. LaFrancis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. LaFrancis said he threatened her again several months later  
and his superiors again took no action and he attacked her. She 
said she was left with back pain, headaches and post-traumatic 
stress disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy court-martialed LaFrancis and he was demoted. He was  
not discharged but left the Navy in 1996, the same year the couple 
were divorced. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
