<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swank Hotel Sues CBS Over Show Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A posh Fifth Avenue hotel has gone to court to  
try to stop CBS from using a plaza in front of the General Motors 
Building to stage its upcoming ``Early Show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sherry-Netherland Hotel, across the street from General  
Motors Building, cited crowds, noise and other potential annoyances 
and asked the court to void the zoning approval the network 
received for the plaza. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Early Show,'' starring Bryant Gumbel and Jane Clayson, is  
set to debut Nov. 1 at 7 a.m. in one of the city's busiest areas. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS plans to use the plaza in front of the building in addition  
to its ground-floor television studio ``that is, as a `tourist 
destination' where crowds (will be) able to gawk through glass at 
the goings on,'' the hotel said in papers filed Friday in state 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	In this outdoor area, ``people will be waving and shouting and  
creating that fake Beatlemania-like sensation'' and ``CBS will be 
able to stage everything from concerts to cooking demonstrations,'' 
the hotel said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hotel says that the zoning approval for CBS violates the law  
because the zoning hearing did not properly consider the impact the 
crowds and show events would have on the environment. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS spokesman Dana McClintock said, ``We don't have any comment  
except to say we intend to be good neighbors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's ``Today'' show, which featured Gumbel for years, airs from  
a ground-level studio in Rockefeller Center. ABC's ``Good Morning 
America'' opened its new storefront studio in Times Square earlier 
this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Trump, the billionaire developer who owns the General  
Motors Building, called the Sherry-Netherland's lawsuit 
``ridiculous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``CBS never heard from them during the zoning process,'' said  
Trump, who is not a party to the lawsuit. ``That would have been 
the time to raise a challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hotel's lawyer, Eva Talel, said Trump is wrong about the  
Sherry-Netherland's failure to appear at zoning proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	``He may not be aware of it, but the hotel did appear and its  
objection was recorded,'' Talel said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
