<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Bill May Curb Bounty Hunters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New restrictions would be placed on bounty  
hunters -- private individuals who hunt down bail jumpers for pay -- 
under legislation introduced in the House on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most bounty hunters are trained and responsible professionals,  
said Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark, author of the bill that has 
Democratic support. But some are rogues ``who've seen one too many 
`Dirty Harry' movie'' and claim they are trained professionals 
after merely reading a book on bounty hunting, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The tragic results are obvious in the countless cases of  
innocent citizens who are shot, beaten and terrorized,'' Hutchinson 
told a news conference. ``Unbelievably, these innocent victims have 
little recourse after suffering such abuse'' since laws enacted 
during the ``Wild West'' period give bounty hunters more power and 
authority than police officers, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At Hutchinson's side was Chinelle Moore, a single mother from  
Laurel, Md., who said five armed men identifying themselves as 
police officers knocked on her door about 5 a.m. in July 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore said she told them she knew nothing about the man they  
were seeking, but they beat her, breaking her nose, covered her 
with pepper spray and pulled a gun on her 5-year-old daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bounty hunters held us in the house against our will,''  
she said. ``They made us sit on the bed and answer questions while 
they ransacked our house and went through our drawers, our phone 
books and kept us from answering the phone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hutchinson said the bill would:  
</P>
<P>
	--Make bounty hunters and the bail bondsmen who hire them liable  
for civil rights violations. 
</P>
<P>
	--Require bounty hunters who cross state lines to report their  
intentions to local law enforcement authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	--Require the attorney general to develop model guidelines that  
state legislatures can consider enacting to regulate bounty 
hunting. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people are harmed by bounty hunters, the victims ... have  
little recourse at all,'' said Rep. Alcee Hastings, D-Fla. ``It is 
frightening to me that individuals can be given the power that 
exceeds the power of law enforcement personnel.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
