<HEADLINE> Alcatel Buys Genesys Laboratories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Alcatel of France is buying Genesys  
Telecommunications Laboratories, a San Francisco-based provider of 
computer telephone technology, for $1.5 billion in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcatel said Tuesday the acquisition complements its five U.S.  
purchases during the past year, leaving the company 
``well-positioned to benefit from the exploding demand for 
voice-data integration in the United States.'' Recent U.S. 
purchases by the maker of communications equipment have included 
DSC and Xylan. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the latest deal, Alcatel will swap 1.667 of its U.S.  
shares for each share of Genesys. The deal is expected to be 
completed in January 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Genesys specializes in computer telephone integration equipment  
and telecom management. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcatel Chairman Serge Tchuruk said the acquisition of Genesys  
should boost the French company's position in the high-growth call 
center market. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is another major step for Alcatel, which continues to  
move quickly towards high-growth markets fueled by the Internet and 
now, e-commerce,'' Tchuruk said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
