<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Warns Banks on Easing Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve is warning banks and  
directing its examiners to watch for signs that risky bank loans 
are piling up. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank took the action Tuesday, a day after Fed  
Governor Laurence Meyer warned that some banks may be counting too 
much on the economic boom continuing. Meyer's remarks, in a speech 
to bankers, were the latest among recent warnings by government 
officials about bank lending standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed action came in a supervisory letter, the means by which  
it informs its examiners and the banking industry of key policy 
directives. 
</P>
<P>
	``While loan portfolios are currently sound at the vast majority  
of banks, any trends toward laxity need to be reversed ... to 
ensure that the banking system remains strong and vibrant and 
retains the ability to lend to sound borrowers in good times and in 
bad,'' wrote Richard Spillenkothen, director of the Fed's Division 
of Banking Supervision and Regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	A few banks are extending credit to some borrowers ``based  
largely on the expectation that the current strong financial 
performance of these borrowers will continue indefinitely,'' the 
letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	It said that if examiners see signs of problems at banks, such  
as bank officials being slow to recognize problem loans, they 
should consider taking action and downgrading banks' federal 
ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech Monday to the Institute of International Bankers,  
Meyer cited ``a possible relaxation in credit discipline that our 
supervisory reviews have detected at some (U.S.) banks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While noting that bank loans remain sound overall, he said  
numbers of questionable loans ``have been rising modestly at some 
banks'' in recent months, a trend the central bank director called 
``troubling.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
