<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Falcons Look Like the Same Ol' Birds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUWANEE, Ga. (AP) -- Bob Whitfield, walking toward the meeting  
room to watch video from another Falcons loss, summed up the plight 
facing the defending NFC champions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll bet you if we go 13-3, we'll have the best record in  
football,'' Atlanta's offensive tackle said Monday. ``We've just 
got to win the rest of our games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dirty Birds may have been able to pull off such a feat.  
However, these guys look like the same ol' Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	In a mere eight months, Atlanta (0-3) has gone from Super Bowl  
to super trouble, threatening to ruin all the goodwill that built 
up during that magical run to Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Hey, is it hockey season yet?  
</P>
<P>
	``It's fun playing in front of a lot of people,'' Whitfield  
said. ``If we lose a couple of games and the people don't want to 
come out, so be it. I guess we'll have to play in front of 
nobody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons sank further into the abyss Sunday, when a St. Louis  
team that was 4-12 a year ago routed the Falcons 35-7. The game 
wasn't even as close as the score, the Rams converting on their 
first four possessions and outgaining Atlanta 311-67 in the first 
half. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looked like they were playing a different speed than we  
were,'' coach Dan Reeves said. 
</P>
<P>
	After falling behind 17-0 in each of their first two games, the  
Falcons trailed 28-0 to the Rams. The injury-depleted offense, 
averaging 9.3 points per game, struggled once again, only this time 
it was complemented by a complete breakdown on defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ran into a buzz saw in St. Louis,'' Marty Carter said.  
``Wow. It was bombs away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rams' dominance was epitomized by a three-play sequence in  
the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	With his team already leading 7-0, Kurt Warner threw a 38-yard  
touchdown pass to Torry Holt on third-and-18. After Todd Lyght 
intercepted a pass from Chris Chandler, Warner capitalized on the 
very next play with a 46-yard scoring strike to Isaac Bruce. On the 
first play of St. Louis' next possession, Marshall Faulk broke off 
a 58-yard run to set up another TD. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just gave up way too many big plays,'' Reeves said. ``On  
the road, where your defense has to play well, we just didn't get 
the job done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More troubling, the Falcons secondary ``looked like the Keystone  
Kops,'' in the words of free safety Eugene Robinson. During a bye 
week, St. Louis came up with a game plan that caught Atlanta 
completely off guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``They took chances downfield and caught us with different  
formations we didn't expect,'' Carter admitted. 
</P>
<P>
	Granted, the Falcons have been plagued by factors beyond their  
control. All-Pro running back Jamal Anderson is out for the season 
with a knee injury, while Chandler is hobbling on a sore hamstring. 
</P>
<P>
	Chandler missed one game, tried to come back too soon Sunday and  
wound up being knocked out again before halftime. He is 
questionable for next weekend's game against the Baltimore Ravens. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not very good,'' Chandler said Monday. ``I'm just trying  
to get it better before it gets worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Already worse for the Falcons is the situation on the defensive  
line, where tackles Shane Dronett and Ed Jasper are both out for 
2-to-4 weeks. Dronett pulled his right calf muscle, while Jasper 
sustained ligament damage in his left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Mentally, the entire team is suffering a severe case of  
shellshock. Although the Falcons have never put together 
consecutive winning seasons during their 34-year history, no one 
expected a start like this. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning breeds confidence,'' Reeves said. ``Losing brings  
around the wrong kind of things: people second-guessing you, people 
talking about how bad you are playing. That is all you hear and all 
you read.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Certainly, this is not what Carter had in mind when he signed  
with the Falcons as a free agent after eight mostly losing seasons 
in Tampa Bay and Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe it wouldn't be so bad if we didn't have such high  
expectations,'' he said. ``That's the most difficult thing. We're 
on every sports show, every channel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only five teams have rebounded from an 0-3 start to make the  
playoffs, and it's little consolation that the Super Bowl champion 
Broncos are also winless after three games. 
</P>
<P>
	Falcons owner Taylor Smith is confident Reeves can get things  
turned around, as he did during his first season in Atlanta. In 
1997, the Falcons were 1-7 at the midway point but won six of their 
final eight games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dan is so consistent,'' Smith said. ``He knows how to handle  
things like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He better hurry.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
