<HEADLINE> Cook Ejected in Mets' Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dennis Cook, ejected Tuesday during an argument  
in the New York Mets' 9-3 loss to Atlanta, doesn't think he should 
be suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	Cook was removed after walking Gerald Williams in the eighth  
inning, and talked to plate umpire Alfonzo Marquez as he walked 
back to the Mets' dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a difference of opinion,'' said Cook, angry with  
ball-strike calls. ``I expressed mine. He expressed his. I'm 
frustrated. I thought some of the pitches were good pitches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An argument ensued, and Cook's cap bumped the cap of Marquez,  
one of the 25 new umpires hired earlier this month. Cook also drew 
a line with dirt over the plate to point out where he thought his 
pitches were. 
</P>
<P>
	Mets manager Bobby Valentine quickly got between them.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think he made any contact with the umpire,'' Valentine  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if Cook is suspended, the penalty likely wouldn't take  
effect until next season. He probably would ask the players' 
association to appeal, delaying any suspension until after NL 
president Len Coleman holds a hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately for Cook, the Mets are home all week, so if there  
is a suspension, Coleman could try to hold a hearing in the next 
few days. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
