<HEADLINE> Intel To Build Va. Service Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) -- Intel Corp., the world's leading maker of  
computer chips, said Tuesday it will locate a $130 million Internet 
service center in Virginia that will employ 250 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel Online Services, a new subsidiary of Intel Corp., will  
house more than 8,000 servers and run the Web sites and 
electronic-commerce operations of numerous companies at the Fairfax 
County site. 
</P>
<P>
	The 73,000 square foot building near Dulles International  
Airport should be in operation by early 2000. That will make it a 
neighbor to the world's largest Internet services company, 
Dulles-based America Online. 
</P>
<P>
	The Virginia suburbs of Washington, D.C., have seen enormous  
growth in high-tech and Internet businesses in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``A large and growing proportion of the world's Internet traffic  
flows through Virginia,'' Mike Aymar, Intel vice president and 
general manager of Intel Online Services, said. ``That made 
Virginia a natural location for Intel's expanding Internet services 
hosting business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first two Internet service centers of Intel Online Services  
already are operational. One is a production plant in Santa Clara, 
Calif., and the other is a development facility in Folsom, Calif. 
The company plans to develop similar centers in Japan and England. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides being the world's largest maker of computer chips, Intel  
is also a leading manufacturer of computer, networking and 
communications products. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
