<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jones: NFL Should Expand to Houston </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- The NFL should give Houston an expansion  
team, then concentrate on finding a team to relocate to Los 
Angeles, Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Houston is ready to begin building the 32nd  
franchise, the moves need to be done as a package to ensure that 
the league gets to pick which team goes to Los Angeles, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my mind, the NFL should not do anything until we've got a  
plan that says, `OK, if we go to Houston, then this is how we go to 
LA,''' Jones said. ``That way, we're still in control of our own 
destiny. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once we make the commitment of where the expansion team goes,  
we're going to leave open a great market like Houston or LA -- a 
better market than some clubs are in. That doesn't necessarily mean 
they're going to pick up and move, but it's going to be an 
attractive situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL has made no secret of its desire to return to Los  
Angeles, the nation's second-largest TV market. Getting back to 
Houston has been a secondary concern. 
</P>
<P>
	The logical plan seemed to be to give Los Angeles a new team,  
then try finding a team willing to move to Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jones said the opposite now seems to make more sense because  
Los Angeles hasn't presented a stadium plan or an ownership group 
that the NFL likes, while Houston has had both in place for months. 
</P>
<P>
	``The economics already are in place with a good partnership  
between the city, state and proposed ownership in Houston,'' Jones 
said. ``So just from the can-do aspect of it financially, it's less 
of a hurdle to go to Houston than LA.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for the two main ownership groups vying for the Los  
Angeles franchise did not immediately return messages left by The 
Associated Press. A message also was left for the proposed owners 
in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL set a Sept. 15 deadline for Los Angeles to come up with  
an acceptable stadium and financing plan, but that date passed with 
the league continuing to talk with all interested parties. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought it was important to create an incentive for LA to  
get its act together and get it done, the result being we would 
probably put an expansion team there,'' Jones said. ``It didn't 
work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moving an existing team to Los Angeles would solve several of  
LA's problems, Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Finding an owner wouldn't be a problem, because that team  
already would have one. Neither would the franchise fee that could 
reach $600 million or more. The only remaining question would be 
finding a stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said he doesn't expect any action to be taken for Houston  
or Los Angeles when owners meet Tuesday in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that at least a handful of owners feel like we need to  
make sure that when the decision comes down that we take care of 
both cities,'' he said. ``The best chance to resolve LA-Houston 
would be to leave it open at least through the fall. My thinking is 
that is what's going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said it's unlikely the league would put expansion teams in  
both cities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the next expansion team will be the last for many,  
many years to come,'' said Jones, who hinted that the next round of 
expansion would likely be outside the United States. ``I don't want 
to create 33 teams with any decision we make over the next month.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones defended the NFL's continued devotion to Los Angeles  
despite all the problems it has encountered. 
</P>
<P>
	``If football is important to 5 or 6 percent of the people in  
LA, that's equal to 100 percent of the people in some other places 
where we are,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there is apathy there, it's a little bit of a result of not  
having a team there. I think the longer we keep a team out of 
there, the more apathy we're going to have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said the NFL is hurting itself by not having teams in Los  
Angeles and Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to be in the great population centers,'' he said. ``In  
our infinite wisdom as owners, we have somehow maneuvered so that 
we don't have franchises in these two great markets.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
