<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chase Buying Hambrecht &AMP; Quist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp., the nation's  
third-biggest bank, is buying Hambrecht &AMP; Quist for $1.35 billion, 
giving Chase the investment banking business it has coveted for 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase has long expressed a desire to become a bigger player in  
the securities business ranging from underwriting stock for new 
companies to advising older ones on mergers and acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, announced today, follows more than a year of  
speculation that Chase would partner with one of Wall Street's 
giant securities firms, such as Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. or Morgan 
Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	``We looked at them all, and this is the one the patient  
investor decided to go with,'' said James B. Lee Jr., a Chase vice 
chairman who will head the bank's investment banking arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Hambrecht &AMP; Quist caters to technology companies, and has  
underwritten the first stock offerings for companies like Netscape, 
Amazon.com and Garden.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, however, is a relatively small player on Wall  
Street, leading some investors to wonder how New York-based Chase 
will expand the business to beat rivals like Citigroup Inc., which 
owns Salomon Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee did not rule out another acquisition, saying ``We will  
continue to review all of our strategic options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But as a first step, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist will change its name to  
Chase Securities West. The 30-year-old firm will keep its 
headquarters in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel H. Case III, chairman and chief executive of Hambrecht &AMP;  
Quist, will become chairman and chief executive of Chase Securities 
West and head of Chase's global technology group. 
</P>
<P>
	To keep Hambrecht &AMP; Quist's employees from defecting, Chase is  
also establishing a $200 million incentive plan for executives who 
sign contracts to stay on. 
</P>
<P>
	BankAmerica Corp. had a problem with employees leaving after the  
No. 2 bank purchased Montgomery Securities in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	In the acquisition, Chase will pay $50 a share for each share of  
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. That is a 22 percent premium over the closing 
price Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors reacted to the bid by sending Hambrecht &AMP; Quist's  
shares up almost 19 percent, or by $7.75, to $48.81 1/4 in midday 
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, where Chase's stock dipped 
$1.12 1/2 to $73. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal has already been approved by the boards of both  
companies and is expected to close by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Hambrecht &AMP; Quist employs about 1,000 people in offices in San  
Francisco, New York, Boston, Atlanta, London, Tokyo and Tel Aviv, 
Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase Manhattan has more than $357 billion in assets with  
operations in 48 countries around the globe. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
