<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mild U.S. Support for East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRNS, Australia (AP) -- Indonesia will face ``serious  
consequences'' if it fails to ensure the success of the 
U.N.-sanctioned peacekeeping mission in East Timor and prevent more 
violence against refugees who have fled the former Portuguese 
colony into West Timor, Defense Secretary William Cohen said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview on an Australian morning news show before  
meeting with Defense Minister John Moore, Cohen said he would make 
the point to top Indonesian leaders as well as opposition figures 
when he holds talks in Jakarta on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The message I will deliver is that the Indonesian government  
has an obligation to see to it that these people who are displaced 
now in West Timor are allowed to go back to their homes in East 
Timor, that ... they prevent the militias from in any way 
interfering or harming them,'' Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked what would happen if Indonesian did not cooperate,  
Cohen said, ``It will have serious consequences to the nature of 
the relationship that Indonesia will have with the rest of the 
world.'' He mentioned diplomatic isolation and ``perhaps economic 
consequences as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen declined to say whether the United States would change its  
mind about the level of its military involvement in East Timor and 
contribute combat troops if Australia said they were needed to 
ensure the mission's success. So far, the United States has 
contributed about 260 support forces but no combat troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen, who arrived in Cairns, on Australia's northeastern coast,  
on Tuesday night local time, said the U.S. military is stretched 
too thin elsewhere in the world to be able to contribute ground 
forces to help restore order in East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States is very much stretched across the globe  
trying to make sure we contribute to peace and stability, but we 
are not the global policeman,'' Cohen said in Wednesday's TV 
interview in Cairns. 
</P>
<P>
	Later on Wednesday, Cohen was flying to the northern Australian  
city of Darwin, the jumping-off point for peacekeepers, to meet 
with Australian military officials and pay a visit to some of the 
U.S. support troops there. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lead has been taken by the Australians,'' Cohen said en  
route to Cairns. ``They are really stepping out, and we are 
providing as much support as we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the start of this week, about 260 Americans were assigned to  
the mission, most in Darwin but a handful in East Timor, Cohen 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon now is increasing its intelligence support for the  
peacekeepers but is unlikely to offer significant additional 
troops, U.S. officials traveling with Cohen said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon sent seven more intelligence officials to Darwin to  
help Australian intelligence. Also, Australia is being supported by 
the U.S. Joint Intelligence Center in Hawaii, U.S. officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	An additional 27 Americans are being dispatched, apparently to  
Darwin, ``in support of special intelligence requirements,'' the 
Pentagon said without elaborating. A six-man special communications 
team from Hawaii also is heading to the area to provide secure 
communications and ``specialized intelligence capabilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N.-sanctioned peacekeeping effort in East Timor comprises  
several thousand military personnel, mainly from Australia and 
Southeast Asian nations. Washington says it has no plans to offer 
combat forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Among additional U.S. contributions Cohen is considering:  
increased use of U.S. Air Force C-17 and C-141 transport aircraft 
for flights into Darwin or Baucau, East Timor's second city east of 
the capital Dili. Eventually the Pentagon intends to send a 
nine-member airlift control squad to Baucau for aircraft loading 
and unloading operations, U.S. officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. forces might also provide water purification equipment, and  
Cohen said he was looking for ways the United States can help ease 
the humanitarian crisis among displaced East Timorese. He mentioned 
temporary housing, food and clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States broke off military relations with Indonesia in  
early September in response to the violence triggered by an Aug. 30 
referendum in which East Timor's population voted overwhelmingly 
for independence from Indonesia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
