<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mainland Facing Small Island Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Despite recent conservation efforts,  
environmental challenges on small islands represent on a lesser 
scale the problems soon to be faced by larger countries, the U.N. 
Environmental Program said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Small island nations must deal with dramatic increases in  
population, urbanization, natural resource consumption and poverty 
-- just as larger nation do. However, small islands have less 
capacity to deal with the problems, according to three reports 
released at U.N. headquarters in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports, drafted by UNEP with support from the European  
Union, cover the Caribbean, the Western Indian Ocean and the 
Pacific Islands. They were released Tuesday to coincide with the 
close of a two-day special session of the General Assembly devoted 
to the environmental and economic troubles facing small islands. 
</P>
<P>
	Klaus Toepfer, the executive director of UNEP, praised the  
governments of small island nations for taking the lead in 
ratifying international environmental treaties, but said 
conservation has fallen far short of expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overall, the Caribbean, Pacific Islands and the Western Indian  
Ocean regions are on an unsustainable course, environmental 
degradation is threatening their very foundations,'' Toepfer said. 
Land and marine species are under grave threat and little has been 
done to reverse past environmental destruction, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But perhaps the greatest threat to small islands is global  
climate change, which scientists say will cause more severe 
hurricanes and a rise in sea levels, possibly engulfing thousands 
of oceanside communities, Toepfer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tourism, once seen as a major source of revenue for many small  
islands, actually threatens the islands' environment, if it 
generates too much solid waste, destroys environmental attractions, 
or deplete natural resources, the reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When (the report) says that the island regions will continue  
to face a steady and serious decline of environmental quality, we 
are not taken by surprise, because we know and we anticipate it,'' 
said Samoa's U.N. ambassador, Neroni Slade, who also chairs the 
Alliance of Small Island States. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports make a number of recommendations, which include  
fighting poverty, integrating natural resource management into all 
aspects of life and preparing for sea-level rise. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
