<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Presidential Primary Is Feb. 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- New Hampshire and Iowa officials hustled  
Tuesday to preserve their status as leaders in the lineup of 
presidential caucuses and primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire's first-in-the-nation presidential primary will be  
Feb. 1, a week earlier than many observers expected, Secretary of 
State Bill Gardner announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gardner said the main reason for the earlier date is that  
Delaware officials have told him they will probably hold their 
Republican primary on Feb. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire law requires the state's primary to be held a week  
before any other state's primary. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement gives other states a target date as they  
scramble to schedule their contests as close as possible to New 
Hampshire's primary and Iowa's presidential caucuses, tentatively 
set for Jan. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Hampshire primary traditionally has been in  
mid-February, eight days after the Iowa caucuses, the leadoff in 
the nominating season. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue of the lineup of primaries and caucuses is fought  
every four years because states where the fight begins get heavy 
attention from candidates and the media. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa Democratic Chairman Rob Tully and Republican Chairman Kayne  
Robinson met Tuesday and said they would seek to pressure Delaware 
officials to set their date as Feb. 15, which would allow the New 
Hampshire primary to return to Feb. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Tully would not rule out moving the Iowa caucus date even  
earlier if the decision for a Feb. 1 New Hampshire primary remained 
firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Reacting to the New Hampshire decision, Mark Pfeifle, spokesman  
for the Republican National Committee, said the primary schedule is 
``something the states should work out and Washington should not 
tell states when their delegate selection should or should not 
be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Democratic National Committee, spokeswoman Jenny Backus  
said, ``This unexpected announcement by Secretary of State Gardner 
raises some concern and certainly confuses the situation,'' she 
said. ``At this point, we have not received any formal notification 
and when we do receive it, we will refer it to our rules and bylaws 
committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The DNC decided earlier that states other than Iowa and New  
Hampshire are not allowed to hold a primary or caucus before March 
7 without a penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	South Carolina is having its Republican primary Feb. 19.  
Delaware Democrats will hold their primary four days after New 
Hampshire's, but both Vice President Al Gore and Bill Bradley have 
pledged to ignore that event. 
</P>
<P>
	That kind of pressure prompted the New Hampshire Legislature to  
change state law this year to allow the primary to be held as early 
as December. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
