<DOCNO> APW19990928.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 08:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Contests Grow at Grocery Stores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Q: I've been seeing more and more contests linked to soft  
drinks, cereals and other grocery items. Why do the manufacturers 
feel the need to compete in this way? 

</P>
<P>
	A: Companies need to grab and keep consumers' attention -- and  
contests or special promotions help them do just that. 
</P>
<P>
	There are ``value-added'' offers aimed at regular customers. The  
customer buys a product and gets the added bonus of winning a prize 
or receiving a gift. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a random chance to have their day brightened,'' says  
Mark Owens, a board member of the Promotion Marketing Association, 
a nonprofit consumer trade group based in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Value-added offers may also provide rebates, coupons for future  
purchases or offers for premium items that can be purchased at a 
reduced price or may be given away. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, not all shoppers are loyal to one particular brand.  
But if there is a contest with the chance of winning a hefty prize, 
like an all-expense paid trip to an amusement park, the shopper may 
be swayed to make a purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	There are ``skill contests,'' a type of promotion that gives  
customers an opportunity to win a prize through competition 
involving the exercise of skill in answering a question or solving 
a puzzle. 
</P>
<P>
	There are also games of chance that permit consumers to  
participate in a contest even without having to make a purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	Studies show consumers think more highly of companies that put  
money into contests. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, the ``odds of winning has to be reasonable enough  
that there's an excitement and a buzz generated,'' says Owens. 
</P>
<P>
	Stores also like promotions because they create attractive  
displays that can generate more sales. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 07:30:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chase Buying Hambrecht &AMP; Quist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp., the nation's  
third-biggest banking company, is buying the investment banking 
firm Hambrecht &AMP; Quist for $1.35 billion in cash. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, announced today, will give Chase broad securities  
underwriting capabilities and enable it to offer companies a wider 
range of financial services. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase has long expressed a desire to become a bigger player in  
the securities business ranging from underwriting stock for new 
companies to advising older ones on mergers and acquisitions. It 
has frequently been mentioned as a possible partner of even larger 
brokerage houses. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies said the deal had been approved by both boards and  
is expected to be completed by the end of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, Chase will pay $50 a share for each share of  
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. That is a 22 percent premium over H&AMP;Q's closing 
price of $41.06 1/4 in trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Hambrecht &AMP; Quist will take the Chase name and continue to be  
headquartered in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	William B. Harrison Jr., president and chief executive of Chase  
Manhattan, called the deal an important strategic move for Chase. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to offer the right financial relationships for  
companies in the new economy -- from venture capital stage to IPO to 
mature company,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel H. Case III, chairman and chief executive of Hambrecht &AMP;  
Quist, will become chairman and chief executive of Chase Securities 
West and head of Chase's global technology group. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase is also establishing a $200 million plan to encourage  
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist's key employees to stay with the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Hambrecht &AMP; Quist employs about 1,00 people in offices in San  
Francisco, New York, Boston, Atlanta, London, Tokyo and Tel Aviv, 
Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase Manhattan has more than $357 billion in assets with  
operations in 48 countries around the globe. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
