<HEADLINE> Shares Fall Across Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Shares were lower across Europe today, driven down  
partly by losses by British banks. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, Bank of Scotland was the worst performing of the  
blue-chip shares, with a drop of 50 pence to 745.5 pence, followed 
by Royal Bank of Scotland, which fell 72 pence to 1,319 pence. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares were pulled down further by the Dow Jones Industrial  
Average, which fell 152.60 points, or 1.5 percent, to 10,150.79 
before European markets closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Europewide indexes fell, with the Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592  
European companies shedding 4.00 points, or 1.3 percent, to close 
at 305.38. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in  
countries that joined the single currency, closed down 3.82 points 
at 319.56. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index fell 54.53 points to 3673.40.  
</P>
<P>
	In domestic markets, London's FTSE 100 index fell 1.2 percent,  
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index fell 2.3 percent and the Paris CAC-40 
index fell 1.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile in Italy, Milan's MIBtel index closed down 0.4  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Declines in the price of Thyseen Krupp, the German steelmaker  
and French telecommunications equipment supplier Alcatel, also 
contributed to the overall European market dip. 
</P>
<P>
	Thyssen Krupp slipped 6.6 percent, or 1.32 euros, to 18.57  
euros, after various politicians said a train project that Thyssen 
Krupp would partly operate will likely be halted because of German 
government budget constraints. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcatel shares fell 2.6 percent, or 3.40 euros, to 126.00 euros,  
after the company made a $1.8 billion all-stock offer for U.S. 
Internet-services company Genesys. Investors feared thier shares 
would be diluted by the new stock issue. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
