<HEADLINE> McCain Gets Campaign Under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNT PLEASANT, S.C. (AP) -- Standing in front of the retired  
aircraft carrier Yorktown, Sen. John McCain on Tuesday officially 
launched his presidential campaign in a state that he has said is 
crucial to his staying in the Republican race. 
</P>
<P>
	A former prisoner of war, McCain has focused resources here  
partly because of the large number of military personnel, active 
and retired, in South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	He promised to defend the nation's security at all costs.  
</P>
<P>
	``As president I won't ask how much security we can afford. I'll  
ask how much security do we need and I will find the resources to 
pay for it,'' the Arizona senator promised a crowd of about 600, 
including elementary school pupils and World War II veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	He made similar speeches to formally launch his campaign Monday  
in New Hampshire and at the U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md., 
from which he graduated. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's event at the Patriot's Point Naval and Maritime Museum  
officially launched his campaign in South Carolina, but McCain has 
been campaigning in the state for months in preparation for its 
first-in-the South GOP primary on Feb. 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Once again he said he must make a good showing here to stay in  
the race against Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican 
front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to do well here in South Carolina to continue this  
campaign,'' McCain told about 400 people at a $13-a-plate breakfast 
in Greenville. 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech in Mount Pleasant, he noted that his grandfather  
once commanded a World War II task force that included the 
Yorktown. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
