<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coke's Bid for Orangina Revised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- After failing in its first attempt to acquire the  
French soft drink brand Orangina, Coca-Cola went back before a 
government committee Tuesday, seeking approval for a revised 
takeover bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke has been trying for two years to buy Orangina from the  
French group Pernod Ricard. But the French government agency that 
governs monopolies, the Competition Council, struck down Coke's bid 
in 1998, fearing it would allow the soft drink maker to edge out 
competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Coke has toned down its offer to appease those  
concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised bid, worth $780 million, does not include Orangina's  
distribution sector, allowing for an independent partner to 
distribute Orangina, a fizzy citrus-tasting drink, in restaurants, 
hotels and cafes during the next 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Other soft drinks companies, including Pepsico Inc., currently  
rely on Orangina's distribution network in the French market. The 
French government has been concerned that these companies would 
lose their distribution outlet if Coke bought out Orangina's 
distribution arm. 
</P>
<P>
	If Coke's newest bid is approved, the company will be allowed to  
distribute Orangina in stores, making up about 80 percent of the 
French market for the drink. Coke would not get the restaurant 
distribution rights that Orangina now controls. 
</P>
<P>
	The Competition Council is expected to present its  
recommendations to the Finance Ministry in October. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say that Coke has thoroughly addressed government  
concerns about edging out Pepsi and creating a monopoly in its 
latest bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coke has most likely done enough,'' said Olivier Lebrun, a  
food and beverage sector analyst for Natexis Capital. ``Quite 
simply put, the new bid will allow Pepsi to stay alive in France.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And it will allow Coke to strengthen its interests in Europe,  
where the group has recently suffered setbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Coke withdrew its bids for the soft drink brands of  
Cadbury Schweppes in many European countries, including France, 
because concerns about monopoly were so strong. 
</P>
<P>
	And a spate of production problems that led to the marketing of  
contaminated drinks scared away customers in France and Belgium. 
Several European countries banned Coke products temporarily, and 
Coke issued a large-scale product recall. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
