<HEADLINE> 7 Indicted in Treasury Theft Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Seven people were indicted Tuesday in the alleged  
theft of $9.4 million from the state treasury. 
</P>
<P>
	Three former treasury workers, two lawyers, and two businessmen  
were charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the money was stolen through false claims made to a  
treasury fund where state checks that haven't been cashed sit 
waiting for their rightful owners, Attorney General Thomas Reilly 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They turned the state Treasury into their own private bank.  
... As they needed it, they took it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Reilly, bags of cash -- some containing between  
$300,000 to $400,000 -- were also hauled away from the treasury 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, $6.5 million has been recovered from what Reilly  
characterized as the largest theft of public money in the state's 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	Four men were originally arrested in the scandal that rocked the  
treasury earlier this year. Three more men were named in Tuesday's 
indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	They face a total of 39 charges -- from receiving stolen property  
to embezzlement to forgery. If convicted, they could face between 
two years to life in prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
