<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  X-ray Ring Found in Crab Nebula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A never-before-seen ring of X-rays has been  
discovered surrounding the heart of the massive crab nebula in 
space, NASA announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The ring was revealed by the 2-month-old Chandra X-ray  
observatory. The finding, combined with other observations, may 
provide clues as to how a powerful neutron star provides energy to 
the nebula, NASA researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The crab nebula, located about 6,000 light-years from Earth in  
the constellation Taurus, is the remnant of a star that was 
observed to explode in the year 1054. 
</P>
<P>
	``The inner ring is unique,'' said Jeff Hester of Arizona State  
University. ``It has never been seen before, and it should tell us 
a lot about how the energy from the pulsar gets into the nebula. 
It's like finding the transmission lines between the power plant 
and the light bulb.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Weisskopf, Chandra Project Scientist at NASA's Marshall  
Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala., said the pulsar inside the 
nebula ``is accelerating particles up to the speed of light and 
flinging them out into interstellar space at an incredible rate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, Hubble Space Telescope images have shown moving  
knots and wisps around the neutron star and X-ray images have shown 
the outer parts of the jet and hinted at the ring structure. With 
Chandra's new observations the ring pattern clearly appears. 
</P>
<P>
	The pulsar within the Crab nebula, discovered by radio  
astronomers in 1968, is a neutron star rotating 30 times per 
second. Neutron stars are formed when gravity crushes the central 
core of the star to densities 50 trillion times that of lead and a 
diameter of only 12 miles. They are highly magnetic and rotate 
rapidly, creating a powerful generator. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
