<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court to Decide ``Class of One'' Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *With AM-Scotus-Grandparents, Bjt    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court will consider squelching a  
Willowbrook, Ill., woman's fight against City Hall over what she 
says was retaliatory action after she sued the city. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said Tuesday it will use Grace Olech's water-service  
case to decide whether a ``class of one'' -- a person who belongs to 
no specially protected group -- can invoke the Constitution's 
guarantee of equal protection when treated differently by the 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court said yes last November and revived Mrs.  
Olech's lawsuit against Willowbrook and several officials. The case 
has not gone to trial and might never do so if the justices 
disagree with the appeals court. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Olech and her husband, now dead, used to get their water  
from a well on their property. When the well broke down in 1995, 
they asked the village to connect their home to the municipal water 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	The village agreed. But besides requiring the Olechs to pay the  
hookup costs, village officials sought a 33-foot easement both to 
service the water main and to allow for widening the street where 
they lived. 
</P>
<P>
	The Olechs refused, and after three months the village withdrew  
its 33-foot easement request and sought the standard 15-foot 
easement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Olechs sued, seeking monetary damages for the three months  
they were without water. Their lawsuit alleged the demand for a 
33-foot easement had been retaliatory, motivated by an earlier 
lawsuit the Olechs filed for flood damage caused by the village's 
negligent installation and enlargement of culverts near the Olechs' 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge threw out the lawsuit, but the 7th U.S. Circuit  
Court of Appeals reinstated it. Its relied on a previous case in 
which it allowed a lawsuit by someone ``who can prove that action 
taken by the state, whether in the form of prosecution or 
otherwise, was a spiteful effort to `get' him for reasons wholly 
unrelated to any legitimate state objective.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Willowbrook vs. Olech, 98-1288.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 03:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Exhibit Becomes Political Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Saying its ideals were ``not on the bargaining  
table,'' the Brooklyn Museum of Art denied caving in to demands 
from the mayor that it pull a dung-decorated painting of the Virgin 
Mary from an upcoming exhibition. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid conflicting assertions that a compromise had been worked  
out, Hillary Rodham Clinton joined the debate and chastised Mayor 
Rudolph Giuliani, her likely opponent in the race for a U.S. Senate 
seat next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not appropriate to penalize and punish an institution  
such as the Brooklyn Museum,'' Mrs. Clinton said Monday during an 
appearance at a Harlem school. 
</P>
<P>
	However, she said she shares ``the feeling that I know many New  
Yorkers have that there are parts of this exhibit that would be 
deeply offensive. I would not go to see this exhibit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the center of cultural and political spectacle is the British  
show, ``Sensation,'' which includes ``The Holy Virgin Mary,'' a 
painting by Chris Ofili depicting Mary with dark skin, African 
features and flowing robes. It has shellacked clumps of elephant 
dung and dozens of cutouts of female private parts from 
pornographic magazines. 
</P>
<P>
	Roman Catholic leaders have denounced the work as blasphemous,  
and Giuliani accused the first lady of supporting the use of public 
money to attack Catholicism. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor had promised to freeze $7 million in public funding to  
the museum because he considered the show -- which also features 
bisected animals and a topless woman in the place of Jesus at the 
Last Supper -- ``sick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Rubin, chairman of the museum's board of directors, met  
on Monday with city officials to try to end the fight. 
</P>
<P>
	A Giuliani administration source who spoke on condition of  
anonymity said Rubin offered: to remove the painting from the 
exhibition; to display six objectionable works separately from the 
rest of the exhibit; and to sacrifice one-fifth of the museum's 
city funding for as long as the show remains on display. The 
exhibit occupies one-fifth of the museum's floor space. 
</P>
<P>
	But the museum denied that any deal had been reached.  
</P>
<P>
	``A number of possible resolutions were looked at, but there was  
and is no agreement of any kind,'' the museum said in a statement. 
``The museum is planning to open `Sensation' on Saturday as 
scheduled and as planned. The BMA remains committed to resolving 
the dispute, but the ideals of the institution are not on the 
bargaining table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any agreement would have to be approved by the museum's board of  
trustees. A message left at the museum was not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	City Hall declared victory in the dispute, which infuriated many  
in the artistic community who say public officials should not have 
veto power over museum exhibitions. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the artist, he said in today's New York Times that the  
elephant dung is a cultural reference to his African heritage and 
that the uproar seemed ``very distant and confusing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel as though I have to defend it,'' Ofili, 31, said  
of the painting. ``The people who are attacking this painting are 
attacking their own interpretation, not mine. You never know what's 
going to offend people.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
