<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> $12.6B Foreign Aid Bill Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House-Senate negotiators have agreed to a  
compromise $12.6 billion foreign aid bill for the coming fiscal 
year, but the measure may not get President Clinton's signature 
because it falls well short of his spending demands. 
</P>
<P>
	The bargainers worked out their agreement Monday evening after  
they jettisoned language that would have forbidden aid to groups 
that promote liberalized abortion laws overseas. That represented a 
defeat for anti-abortion conservatives, and a victory for the White 
House and moderate Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	But the measure still has a long way to go before it can become  
law. The House-Senate package still falls $2 billion below the 
amount Clinton wants, and White House officials threatened to veto 
initial versions of the bill with similar reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, many Republicans say they would welcome a veto fight in  
which the president demands more spending for foreign aid, an 
intensely unpopular program with the public. 
</P>
<P>
	Current law bans the use of U.S. taxpayer funds for  
organizations that perform abortions overseas. The deleted language 
would have dropped federal aid to groups that use their own money 
to lobby overseas for the procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar international family planning dispute is delaying  
separate legislation that would authorize about $1 billion in 
delinquent U.S. payments to the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The House-Senate measure provides $385 million for international  
family planning assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill completely omits the $500 million Clinton requested for  
Israel and the Palestinians to carry out the peace accord 
negotiated last year at Wye River, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP lawmakers have said they support the peace plan, a top  
administration priority, but cannot find the money because of 
spending limits. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure also:  
</P>
<P>
	--Cuts Clinton proposals for aid to former Soviet states, global  
environmental efforts, peacekeeping operations, the Peace Corps. 
</P>
<P>
	--Provides more than Clinton wanted for UNICEF, international  
children's health, and economic aid to Israel and Egypt. 
</P>
<P>
	--Permits funds for the U.S. Army School of the Americas in Fort  
Benning, Ga., which trains foreign soldiers who have been accused 
of committing atrocities in Central America. 
</P>
<P>
	--Forbids spending for major construction projects in Kosovo, and  
requires the State Department to certify that U.S. aid to Kosovo 
will be limited to 15 percent of total international assistance to 
the Balkan nation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
