<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Treatment OK'd for Aortic Aneurysm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Thousands of Americans with the condition that  
killed actor George C. Scott last week won an easier alternative 
Tuesday to the grueling surgery that until now was the only 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Called an abdominal aortic aneurysm, the condition is like a  
time bomb in the abdomen -- a weak spot on the body's largest blood 
vessel that, if it breaks, can cause almost instantly fatal 
internal bleeding. Such burst aneurysms kill 15,000 Americans a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	To patch these aneurysms, the entire abdomen is sliced open and  
delicate organs moved aside to reach the problem. The surgery 
itself kills up to 10 percent of patients, and even those who do 
well can require months of recuperation. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Food and Drug Administration approved two  
patches -- Guidant Corp.'s Ancure system and Medtronic Inc.'s AneuRx 
-- that offer doctors their first alternative to such traumatic 
surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	The patches allow aneurysm repair during minimally invasive  
surgery that, in studies sponsored by the two companies, cut 
surgical complications in half and allowed patients to go home from 
the hospital in just two or three days instead of a week. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the patches seem to offer many patients an easier  
option -- some surgeons say they will revolutionize care -- they are 
not risk-free, the FDA warned. Some people, particularly women, may 
not be good candidates, and doctors must be specially trained to 
use the complex devices, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	The aorta is the largest blood vessel, like a river running from  
the heart to the groin with tributaries that branch off, carrying 
blood around the body. An aneurysm is a weak bulge in the aorta's 
wall. 
</P>
<P>
	If it gets big enough, the pressure of blood pounding past can  
cause it to burst. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors estimate that 1.5 million older Americans have abdominal  
aortic aneurysms, called ``AAAs.'' But because AAAs often cause no 
symptoms until they break, only about 200,000 patients are aware of 
the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast to open surgery, Tuesday's approval allows doctors  
to slice an opening into an artery in the groin, thread an aortic 
patch up that artery until it meets the aorta, and then push the 
patch to the aneurysm spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Guidant's Ancure has metal hooks that grab onto a healthy  
section of aorta to form sort of a sleeve, providing a new path so 
blood doesn't pound on the aneurysm. 
</P>
<P>
	Medtronic's AneuRx is a stent, a metal scaffolding that opens up  
until it has expanded against the aortic walls enough to hold the 
patch in place. 
</P>
<P>
	In studies of over 800 patients, the patches successfully  
repaired over 90 percent of AAAs, but with fewer surgical side 
effects, less blood loss and less recuperation time in the hospital 
than patients who had standard abdominal surgery, the FDA said. 
</P>
<P>
	Surgeons involved in the studies say the devices could  
revolutionize care, particularly since they offer an alternative 
for elderly patients who could not survive regular surgery and thus 
until now have had no option. 
</P>
<P>
	But there were risks.  
</P>
<P>
	For example, even though fewer women than men get these  
aneurysms, women actually fared worse during experiments with the 
patches. The problem appeared to be size -- doctors didn't realize 
in advance which women had arteries too small to handle threading 
up a patch. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA said a surgery team should always be available in case a  
patient failed the patch procedure and needed immediate 
open-abdomen surgery. Also troubling was that some patches leaked. 
It is unclear how risky that is, but the FDA urged proper follow-up 
monitoring of patients. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
