<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philly Republican Looks to be Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Businessman Sam Katz hopes to do this  
Election Day what other white Republicans have already done in 
multi-ethnic Los Angeles and New York: snatch City Hall back from 
the Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	If Katz wins on Nov. 2, he will become Philadelphia's first GOP  
mayor in 52 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz faces John Street, a black Democrat, in a city where there  
are seven Democrats for every two Republicans and where the 
electorate tends to vote along racial lines. Street is also trying 
to make history as the second black mayor of Philadelphia, where 40 
percent of the city's 1.4 million residents are black. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a measure of how much things have changed in the city  
where Frank Rizzo, the white police commissioner-turned-mayor, was 
a polarizing force in the 1970s and '80s, race has not emerged as 
an issue. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, a black politician who finished third in the Democratic  
primary crossed party lines this month to endorse Katz. 
</P>
<P>
	``Race in Philadelphia historically has played a significant  
role in the outcome of elections. But race relations have improved 
markedly here,'' said G. Terry Madonna, a professor of political 
science at Millersville University. ``This campaign has been 
remarkably free of race-baiting and racial overtones. Any of that 
would be counterproductive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No independent polls have been conducted, but political analysts  
say Katz has a decent shot even though Street, a former City 
Council president, is endorsed by the popular lame-duck mayor, 
Edward Rendell. 
</P>
<P>
	Rendell, who is credited with bringing the nation's  
fifth-largest city back from the brink of bankruptcy, is barred 
from seeking a third consecutive term. 
</P>
<P>
	Rendell succeeded the city's first black mayor, W. Wilson Goode,  
who held office from 1984 to 1992, during which he bombed a 
neighborhood in a confrontation with the radical group MOVE and 
presided as city finances neared financial ruin. 
</P>
<P>
	While race hasn't galvanized the campaign, neither has much  
else. Newspapers call both Katz and Street policy wonks who are 
dull compared with the gregarious, photogenic Rendell. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz, 49, is a former Democrat who made a fortune as a financial  
adviser to cities around the nation. He helped draft the recovery 
plan Rendell employed in Philadelphia and is an expert on stadium 
financing. Katz made failed primary runs for mayor in 1991 and 
governor of Pennsylvania in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Street, 55, is a former activist who traded in his fiery,  
quick-with-his-fists style of the 1980s for a buttoned-down 
approach in the '90s, honed during his tenure as City Council 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	The two have few differences on issues, with school vouchers  
being the major exception -- Katz supports them, Street does not. 
And that issue will probably be decided at the state Capitol rather 
than in City Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	Their similar ideologies, along with a lack of negative  
campaigning, are why Katz has a shot at defeating the favored 
Street, political analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz's campaign got a boost last week when black Democrat John  
White Jr. endorsed him. White, who got 21 percent of the vote in 
the Democratic primary, said he had simply decided the Republican 
Katz would be better for the city than Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Street shrugged it off.  
</P>
<P>
	``I intend to stand with the thousands of voters who voted for  
John White Jr. in the Democratic primary, because I think they will 
respond to the issues that caused them to come and vote 
Democratic,'' Street said. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz can put a GOP face on his heavily Democratic city the way  
Richard Riordan has done in Los Angeles and Rudolph Giuliani has 
done in New York. It would be a big victory for Republicans, who 
also are holding their national convention in Philadelphia next 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz said the convention and his party's historical weakness in  
Philly are not important. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not something I think about very much and it's not  
something that comes up in my meetings with voters,'' he said. 
``People want to know how you are going to make their neighborhoods 
better -- party is irrelevant to them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
