<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> KLM, Northwest Cut Dec. 31 Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- KLM Royal Dutch Airlines and its  
U.S. partner, Northwest Airlines, plan to reduce the number of 
international flights scheduled for New Year's Eve this year 
because of lukewarm demand. 
</P>
<P>
	KLM said today it now had only five intercontinental flights  
scheduled as the millennium changes, compared with 35 at the end of 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest said it would cancel five flights on Dec. 31, four  
from the United States to Amsterdam and one between Amsterdam and 
Delhi, India. The return legs of those flights scheduled for Jan. 1 
also will be canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Northwest will operate its scheduled round-trip flights  
to Amsterdam from Detroit, Boston and Minneapolis, as well as its 
service to London, Paris and Frankfurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Both airlines, which are notifying passengers affected by the  
schedule changes, noted that travel during the holiday season as a 
whole was up from 1998 levels, with demand shifting to periods 
before Dec. 31 and after Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	KLM spokesman Peter Wellhuner said that although airlines always  
see a drop-off in demand for seats on New Year's Eve, this year's 
decline was particularly steep. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's explainable if you look at the destinations,''  
Wellhuner said. ``Demand is strongest for places like the United 
States, Canada, Australia, New Zealand. These are countries where 
Dutch people have strong connections. People prefer to visit with 
their families and close friends for an event like the year 2000.'' 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
