<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Book Upsets Reagan Daughter, Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ronald Reagan's elder daughter says she won't  
be reading his authorized biography because the writer appears to 
have ``wasted an incredible and irreplaceable opportunity'' to 
explain him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have decided that I have read all the fiction about Ronald  
Reagan I intend to read -- so I think I will pass on this book,'' 
Maureen Reagan said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Former President Bush pitched in Tuesday with criticisms of his  
own, denying biographer Edmund Morris' claim in ``Dutch: A Memoir 
of Ronald Reagan'' that Bush and his wife felt unwelcome 
``upstairs'' in the Reagan White House when he was vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's ridiculous,'' he told NBC's ``Today.''  
</P>
<P>
	``Upstairs? I mean that's kind of an English ...  
upstairs-and-downstairs approach to life. I don't even use the 
terminology,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said he was ``very close to President Reagan, so I don't  
know where Mr. Morris gets that. I mean, I haven't read his book 
yet. Might not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris writes of a Christmas Eve 1988 conversation he said he  
had with George and Barbara Bush a month before Bush became 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really love that guy, he's such a terrific fellow,'' Bush is  
quoted as saying. Morris then quotes Bush as commenting about 
Reagan and his wife, Nancy: ``I kinda wished they'd shown -- y'know, 
a little appreciation. Didn't seem to want us upstairs in the White 
House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush told ``Today'' he and his wife were not the Reagans'  
closest friends, but ``we never felt that we were unwelcome 
someplace.'' Bush was not asked whether he denied the conversation 
took place. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Morris' characterization of Reagan as an ``apparent  
airhead,'' Bush said: ``That is brutal and grossly unfair and 
untrue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maureen Reagan is described in passages of ``Dutch'' excerpted  
by Newsweek as ``the eldest and largest of the president's 
children, her brilliant smile and button nose reminding the world 
that there once was another Mrs. Reagan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She ``sings and acts well, memorizes like a VCR and luxuriates  
in the spotlight,'' Morris wrote, saying she could have made a 
career in show business if she only had the figure of Jane Wyman, 
her mother and Reagan's first wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris was granted close access to Reagan during his second  
term. Although the book is not being released until Thursday, it 
has already created a stir with historians and former Reagan aides, 
in part because Morris inserts himself as a semi-fictional 
character. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suspect when all is said and done, given the unprecedented  
access graciously provided the author, the American people will 
conclude that the author wasted an incredible and irreplaceable 
opportunity,'' Maureen Reagan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris told CBS' ``60 Minutes'' he expects Nancy Reagan to be  
disturbed by the book because, despite his admiration for the 
ex-president, ``I do not hide the fact that Reagan was frequently 
an old, spaced-out man, inattentive to details.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book, a copy of which was obtained by The Associated Press,  
devotes about 250 pages of text to the Reagan presidency in its 874 
pages of text and notes. 
</P>
<P>
	Reagan biographer Lou Cannon told CBS that Morris' contribution  
could have been ``to tell us what went on during the presidency 
and, with very few exceptions, he doesn't.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
