<DOCNO> APW19990928.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 23:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Las Vegas Bids for NHL, NBA Teams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Don't look for the sports books in Las Vegas to  
be taking action any time soon on the city's chances for an NBA or 
NHL franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	It is an out bet, a long shot at best and maybe no shot at all.  
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Oscar Goodman led a contingent of city officials on a tour  
of the two leagues Tuesday, meeting with commissioners David Stern 
of the NBA and Gary Bettman of the NHL. He was greeted cordially, 
but received the same news on both fronts. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither league has any plans to expand, and neither league has  
any team seeking a new home. That would seem to be a major obstacle 
for Goodman. 
</P>
<P>
	Further complicating the matter is the gambling industry that  
flourishes in Las Vegas. Basketball betting accounts for 23 percent 
of the total sports handle there, according to Vegas Sports 
Consultants, which helps set betting lines for sports books. 
</P>
<P>
	``This trip was 100 percent successful,'' the mayor said. ``I  
wish we had the go-ahead. We don't. We took a giant step today. 
We're alive and kicking. I'm happy we took the trip. Our mission 
was to find out information and the attitude of the leagues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What Goodman accomplished was getting Stern to agree to bring up  
Las Vegas and the issue of sports gambling at the next owners 
meeting on Oct. 28. The commissioner, however, was not exactly 
encouraging on the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our historic position is documented for all to see,'' Stern  
said. ``We couldn't grant two expansion franchises until they 
eliminated NBA games from their sports lotteries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Toronto and Vancouver franchises were in danger until  
Ontario and British Colombia agreed to remove NBA games from their 
provincial lotteries. 
</P>
<P>
	Stern said there is no reason to believe that the owners have  
changed their minds, although they hadn't been asked about it for 
five years. ``My guess is it might not have changed,'' the 
commissioner said. ``I am comfortable with the NBA's historic 
position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So where does that leave Las Vegas?  
</P>
<P>
	``We have our work cut out for us,'' Goodman said. ``We have to  
see if the casinos are interested in changing present procedures. 
If not, it's up to the owners to accept us the way we are. It means 
a major change in the way we do business or changing the way the 
NBA does business. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're in the driver's seat. We're not.''  
</P>
<P>
	Currently, the only pro team in the city are the Las Vegas Stars  
of the PCL, an affiliate of the San Diego Padres. John Moores, 
owner of the Padres, is the proposed owner of any NBA or NHL 
franchise in the city. 
</P>
<P>
	The Las Vegas Thunder played in the International Hockey League  
for six years but lost its lease at the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center and 
has been unable to find an alternate site. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodman started his tour with Bettman, where the NHL  
commissioner supplied the mayor with some basic information. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are three criteria to be satisfied for a hockey team --  
ownership, arena and market,'' Goodman said. ``Our fear was how 
gambling would be looked upon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Was Vegas' gambling industry a problem for the NHL?  
</P>
<P>
	``To characterize anything as an issue would be premature,''  
Bettman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Stern later, Bettman was cordial if not encouraging.  
Reminded that he had not said no to Las Vegas, the commissioner 
smiled. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't say yes, either,'' he said. ``The process is not a  
simple yes or no. We had a good dialogue.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
