<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 07:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prisoner May Lose Parole Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court said today it will consider  
killing a Georgia prison inmate's challenge to the way the state 
handles parole requests from convicted criminals serving life 
sentences. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices said they will review a federal appeals court  
ruling that reinstated convicted murderer Robert Jones' contention 
that his rights were violated when the state decided to reconsider 
denied parole requests once every eight years. The earlier limit 
was once every three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones was sentenced to life in prison in 1982, when state  
regulations required that he first be considered for parole after 
serving seven years. If parole were not granted, the regulations 
provided for reconsideration hearings every three years thereafter. 
</P>
<P>
	After Jones was imprisoned, but before his 1989 parole hearing,  
the state Board of Pardons and Paroles amended its rules to require 
parole reconsideration hearings once every eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	After Jones was denied parole in 1989, the board scheduled him  
for a reconsideration hearing in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	But in 1991 the Atlanta-based 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals  
ruled that such changes in parole policies unfairly imposed 
after-the-fact punishment. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Jones was reconsidered for parole at three-year  
intervals, being turned down in 1992 and again in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's highest court in 1995 ruled in a California case  
that states can increase the time between parole hearings for 
prison inmates who committed their crimes when parole hearings were 
more frequent. In California, hearings that had been conducted 
every year were changed to every three years. 
</P>
<P>
	After the decision in the California case was announced, Georgia  
authorities scheduled Jones' next parole hearing for 2003 rather 
than 1998. They did so after concluding that the 1995 Supreme Court 
ruling had overturned the appeals court's 1991 ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones sued, but a federal trial judge threw out his case. The  
11th Circuit court, however, revived his lawsuit last January. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court, citing numerous differences between the  
California and Georgia regulations, said the reasoning of the 1995 
Supreme Court decision ``reaffirms the correctness of our holding'' 
in the 1991 case. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Garner vs. Jones, 99-137.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
