<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Honduras Flood Death Toll at 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- The death toll from 17 days of  
torrential rain in Honduras has risen to 13 and the storms show no 
sign of ending, the government said Tuesday. Flooding also hit 
Nicaragua, El Salvador and Costa Rica. 
</P>
<P>
	The economic damage has been devastating for Honduras, which is  
still struggling to rebuild after last year's Hurricane Mitch, 
which caused billions of dollars in damage and killed more than 
5,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 12,350 acres of banana, coffee, sugar cane, cocoa and  
basic grains are under water, 12 highways are intransitable and 727 
houses and 16 bridges have been destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	The damage has occurred throughout Honduras. Ten thousand  
Hondurans have been cut off by the storm and 7,000 have been 
evacuated, said Arturo Corrales, an official with the federal 
government's emergency commission. 
</P>
<P>
	``The evacuations will continue,'' he said. ``The situation is  
serious -- the critical stage of the (rainy season) is barely 
beginning...so the state of emergency will be extended until 
November.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Flooding problems worsened Friday when the country's main  
hydroelectric dam, El Cajon, reached its capacity, forcing 
officials to increase the water flow, which caused flooding on 
several rovers. 
</P>
<P>
	Flooding problems have also affected neighboring El Salvador,  
where five days of heavy rain have forced the evacuation of 3,000 
people and killed one person. 
</P>
<P>
	Salvadoran officials ordered the evacuation of hundreds more  
people Tuesday and declared a flood emergency for towns along the 
Lempa River as well as for poor neighborhoods in San Salvador, the 
nation's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to a shelter, because we're afraid it could become  
another Mitch,'' said Juan Perez, a 56-year resident of this town 
on the banks of the Lempa, 60 miles southeast of San Salvador. 
</P>
<P>
	Further to the south, in Costa Rica, that government's National  
Emergency Commission reported that more than 1,300 people had taken 
refuge in 24 shelters in the northern province of Guanacaste 
following flooding caused by intense rain Monday and Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Flooding cut roads in Nicaragua and cut off some communities  
along the country's border with Honduras. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have reports from all over the country of damage due to the  
rains,'' said Maj. Mayor Rogelio Flores Ortiz, head of operations 
for Nicaragua's Civil defense agency. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
