<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Sept. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Downpours Cause New Carolina Flooding  
</P>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Six inches of rain kicked off new flooding  
today in an area already saturated by Hurricane Floyd, washing out 
roads and a spillway. People were urged to evacuate two residential 
areas. The pouring rain that fell during the night cut through 
roads and made bridges in Wayne County and other areas impassable 
this morning southeast of Raleigh. In Goldsboro, 80 percent of the 
downtown streets were flooded this morning by Stony Creek, which 
flows through the middle of town, the National Guard said. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Offers Health Care Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Bradley took a bold stand on insuring the  
health of Americans today, proposing a $65 billion plan that would 
require coverage for all children, with subsidies for families that 
cannot afford it. Individuals of all ages and incomes also would be 
able to exclude from their taxable income whatever they pay for 
health premiums. ``When it comes to America's health, this is not 
the time to be timid,'' said the Democratic presidential candidate, 
adding that health insurance should be a basic birthright. 

</P>
<P>
	Visitation Rights To Be Decided  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide  
whether grandparents are entitled to visitation rights to their 
grandchildren when the children's parents object. The justices said 
they will use a case from Washington state to make their first 
venture into the area of ``grandparents' rights.'' All 50 states 
have some type of law allowing court-ordered visitation for 
grandparents. Washington's highest court struck down its state law, 
ruling that only parents are entitled to court-enforced visitation 
rights. 

</P>
<P>
	Study Checks Students' Writing  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About three-fourths of the nation's school  
children demonstrated only partial mastery of the knowledge and 
skills needed to write proficiently for their grade level, the 
Education Department reported today. Testers asked 60,000 
fourth-graders, eighth-graders and 12th-graders to write stories, 
personal essays, reports about events or experiences and persuasive 
pieces. The tests and score levels were determined by the National 
Assessment Governing Board, a body created by Congress to act as an 
independent judge of education standards. 

</P>
<P>
	HMO Bill Stresses Insurance Access  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A package of tax cuts aimed at improving  
access to health insurance was offered today by House Republican 
leaders hoping to blend the measure with bills giving people rights 
to sue managed care health plans. Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., 
said each of the bills giving patients a host of new legal rights 
is missing two key pieces: improving health care access and 
affordability for an estimated 44 million uninsured Americans. 

</P>
<P>
	CMGI To Acquire 1stUp.com  
</P>
<P>
	ANDOVER, Mass. (AP) -- CMGI Inc., an Internet holding company,  
announced it is acquiring 1stUp.com, which provides businesses with 
the ability to offer free, advertising-supported Internet access. 
1stUp.com currently offers its free Internet access to AltaVista, a 
search engine portal owned by CMGI. CMGI has been acquiring 
Internet companies in an effort to create a network large enough to 
challenge America Online Inc. and Yahoo! Inc. 

</P>
<P>
	Diet Drug Settlement Plan Rejected  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A federal judge rejected a $100 million  
settlement a company proposed to pay injury claims by hundreds of 
users of the once popular diet drug Redux. A U.S. district judge 
said he was uncertain a ``limited fund'' that Interneuron 
Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Lexington, Mass., proposed to set up to 
settle the lawsuits would be fair to all who might have claims. The 
judge also cited ``constitutional concerns'' because the deal would 
not allow claimants to opt out and seek separate trials if they 
wish. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 137 in Afternoon Trading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today as investors,  
increasingly nervous before next week's Federal Reserve meeting, 
were unable to sustain yesterday's timid rally. Just before 1 p.m. 
EDT, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 137.09 at 10,166.30. 
Declining issues on the New York Stock Exchange led advancers 
1,906-888. The Nasdaq composite index was down 47.67 at 2,714.08. 

</P>
<P>
	49ers' Young Sustains Mild Concussion  
</P>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- San Francisco 49ers quarterback Steve Young  
suffered his fourth concussion since 1995 last night, but he 
insisted this one was nothing close to as serious as his most 
recent one two years ago against Tampa Bay. Young, 37, was injured 
late in the second quarter of a 24-10 victory over the Arizona 
Cardinals. The team is scheduled to announce Young's status for 
this week's game against Tennessee this afternoon. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  



  	   	
