<HEADLINE> Swank Hotel Sues CBS Over Show Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A posh Fifth Avenue hotel has gone to court in a  
bid to stop CBS from using a plaza in front of the General Motors 
Building to stage its upcoming ``Early Show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sherry-Netherland Hotel, across the street from General  
Motors Building, cited potential annoyances and asked the court to 
void the zoning approval the network received for the plaza. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Early Show,'' starring Bryant Gumbel and Jane Clayson, is  
to debut Nov. 1 at 7 a.m. in one of the city's busiest areas. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS plans to use the plaza in front of the building in addition  
to its ground-floor television studio ``as a `tourist destination' 
where crowds (will be) able to gawk through glass at the goings 
on,'' the hotel said in papers filed Friday in state court. 
</P>
<P>
	In the area, ``people will be waving and shouting and creating  
that fake Beatlemania-like sensation'' and ``CBS will be able to 
stage everything from concerts to cooking demonstrations,'' the 
hotel said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hotel said the zoning approval for CBS violates the law  
because the zoning hearing did not properly consider the impact the 
crowds and show events would have on the environment. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS spokesman Dana McClintock said Tuesday that the network had  
no comment except that ``we intend to be good neighbors.'' 
  	   	
</P>
