<HEADLINE> White House Acknowledges Riady Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House acknowledged Tuesday that  
President Clinton had a very brief encounter in New Zealand with 
James Riady, the Indonesian businessman who has been sought for 
questioning since 1997 about campaign fund raising. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dan Burton, chairman of the House Government Reform  
Committee, wrote the White House about a Wall Street Journal report 
Friday that Riady used the economic summit meeting in New Zealand 
this month to chat with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The Journal quoted unidentified Indonesians as saying Riady  
didn't discuss anything ``sensitive'' with the president. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting of corporate executive officers with 350 people in  
the room, Clinton and Riady encountered one another ``very briefly 
along a rope line,'' said White House spokesman Jim Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton ``spent more time typing the letter than this brief  
rope-line encounter took,'' Kennedy added. ``For Representative 
Burton to spend any time inquiring into this ... is a tremendous 
waste of taxpayer dollars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy said the White House ``will respond in some appropriate  
fashion to the chairman's letter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burton wrote White House counsel Beth Nolan that ``I cannot  
understand what purpose would be served by the president meeting 
with Mr. Riady except to urge him to cooperate with federal 
investigators. ... It is my sincere hope that ... the president 
used the prestige of his office and his long-term friendship with 
Mr. Riady to convince Mr. Riady to return to the United States and 
answer all of the questions posed by Congress and the Justice 
Department so the American public can finally learn the entire 
truth about Mr. Riady's role in tampering with our presidential 
elections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A call to the office of Riady's Washington lawyer, Earl Silbert,  
was not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton provided the White House a lengthy list of questions and  
in a postscript, the congressman scrawled, ``If a subpoena is 
required -- please let me know as soon as possible!!!'' Burton asked 
for the identity of any White House officials who expressed concern 
over Clinton meeting with Riady. 
</P>
<P>
	Riady's family -- which has supported Clinton's campaigns dating  
to his years as Arkansas governor -- runs the global conglomerate 
Lippo Group. 
</P>
<P>
	The Riadys paid longtime Clinton friend Webster Hubbell $100,000  
at a time when Hubbell was under criminal investigation by 
prosecutor Kenneth Starr. Neither Hubbell nor the Riadys have 
explained why they paid Hubbell the money. 
</P>
<P>
	A top Riady family business executives in the United States,  
John Huang, began cooperating this year with the Justice 
Department's investigation of campaign fund-raising abuses in the 
1996 presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang went to work raising money for the Democratic National  
Committee in 1996 after a White House meeting with the president 
and James Riady. 
</P>
<P>
	``To date, 122 witnesses, including James Riady, have either  
fled the country or pled the 5th Amendment to avoid testifying in 
the committee's continuing investigation'' of campaign fund 
raising, Burton said in a news release. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats returned $1.6 million raised by Huang amid questions  
about the money's origin. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
