<HEADLINE> Western Digital Recalls Hard Drives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVINE, Calif. (AP) -- Western Digital Corp. has recalled 400,000  
hard disk drives because of a defect in a computer chip, the 
company said. 
</P>
<P>
	The defect can cause the hard drives -- the part of the computer  
that stores data -- to fail to power up after six to 12 months of 
use, company officials said Monday. The recalled hard drive is part 
of the WD Cavair series. 
</P>
<P>
	The recall is the latest in a string of problems, including  
recent layoffs and a plunging stock price, for the Orange 
County-based computer company. 
</P>
<P>
	Western Digital officials said it was unclear how much the  
recall would cost or how many of the affected hard drives actually 
landed in consumer hands. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, whose largest computer manufacturing costumers  
include Gateway Inc. and Compaq Computer Corp., said many of the 
disk drives are still in the hands of manufacturers and sellers. 
</P>
<P>
	``No data has been lost, and none is in danger of being lost,''  
said Charles Haggerty, Western Digital's chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	The hard drives being recalled were made between Aug. 27 and  
last Friday, and have drive capacities between 6.4 gigabytes to 
20.5 gigabytes, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers who purchased computers in the past month can check  
specification sheets on their machines to see if they include a 
Western Digital drive, officials said. The company's Web site, 
www.westerndigital.com, offers a software program that can be 
downloaded to identify any affected products. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990928.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 07:40:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Review Sidewalk Counseling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide  
whether Colorado went too far in limiting ``sidewalk counseling'' 
by anti-abortion demonstrators, an effort to protect the privacy 
rights of abortion clinic patients. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices said they will study an appeal in which three  
sidewalk counselors say the state law violates their free-speech 
rights. A decision, expected sometime in 2000, could provide 
important new guidelines for other states, and for communities 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is a 1993 Colorado law that bars people from  
counseling, distributing leaflets or displaying signs within eight 
feet of others without their consent whenever they are within 100 
feet of a health clinic entrance. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Legislature enacted the law in response to what the  
state's lawyers said was ``a history of obstructive demonstrations 
outside such clinics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Protesters constructively blockaded clinics by surrounding,  
crowding, yelling at, grabbing, pushing, shoving, hitting and 
spitting on those seeking access, triggering dangerous 
physiological responses in medical patients,'' state Attorney 
General Ken Salazar told the justices. 
</P>
<P>
	The state law was challenged by Leila Jeanne Hill, Audrey  
Himmelmann and Everitt Simpson Jr., who said they merely advised 
women of alternatives to abortion before the Colorado law made them 
fear criminal prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	Their appeal called the law an ``overbroad, content-based,  
viewpoint-discriminatory'' prior restraint on speech. 
</P>
<P>
	After Colorado courts upheld the state law, the nation's highest  
court in 1997 sent the case back so the state courts could 
reconsider it in light of a decision in which the justices allowed 
abortion protesters to confront patients on public sidewalks as 
long as they stayed at least 15 feet from clinic entrances. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge in New York had ordered protesters to stay 15 feet away  
from any clinic patient or staff member, but the Supreme Court said 
such ``floating buffer zones'' were unconstitutional in that case. 
</P>
<P>
	After restudying the Colorado dispute, a state appeals court  
again upheld the state law. It drew a distinction between the New 
York case, which involved a judge's injunction against abortion 
protesters, and a generally applicable law enacted by a state 
Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colorado Supreme Court also voted to uphold the state law in  
February, citing ``greater deference for legislative enactments 
regulating speech.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state court also drew a distinction between buffer zones of  
15 feet and eight feet. The smaller buffer zone ``allows for normal 
conversational tones.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the three Colorado abortion protesters said floating  
zones deemed to be invalid when imposed against ``adjudged 
malefactors'' also should be struck down ``if imposed by statute 
upon the general populace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Hill vs. Colorado, 98-1856.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
