<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall As Stocks Gain / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell sharply Tuesday in a selloff  
driven by fund managers apparently looking to recover losses 
created by the sudden rise in the price of gold. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell a full  
point, or $10 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, rose to 6.08 percent from 6.01 percent late 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fund managers, who had bet that gold would continue to decline  
in value, sold bonds Tuesday to cover their losses. Gold futures 
contracts climbed Tuesday to their highest level since April 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, bond prices decreased as demand fell in the wake of  
a huge $5.25 billion debt issued by Fannie Mae, the federal 
government's mortgage agency. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were down 1/8 to 7/32 point, while intermediate maturities fell 11/32 
to 5/8 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Tuesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
were unchanged at 4.85 percent, and the discount held steady at 
4.72 percent. Six-month yields fell to 4.97 percent as the discount 
fell 0.02 percentage point to 4.78 percent. One-year yields rose to 
5.18 percent as the discount rose 0.02 percentage point to 4.92 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, was unchanged at 5.31 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 11/32 to 112 3/4. The average yield to 
maturity of the index rose to 5.87 percent from 5.85 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
