<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Warns Banks on Easing Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Warning banks not to become lax in their  
lending, the Federal Reserve directed its examiners Tuesday to 
watch for signs that risky loans are piling up, something that 
could threaten the strength of the banking system. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank's action came a day after Fed Gov. Laurence  
Meyer warned that some banks may be counting too much on the 
economic boom continuing. Meyer's remarks, in a speech to bankers, 
were the latest among recent warnings by government officials about 
bank lending standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed action came in a supervisory letter, the means by which  
it informs its examiners and the banking industry of key policy 
directives. 
</P>
<P>
	``While loan portfolios are currently sound at the vast majority  
of banks, any trends toward laxity need to be reversed ... to 
ensure that the banking system remains strong and vibrant and 
retains the ability to lend to sound borrowers in good times and in 
bad,'' wrote Richard Spillenkothen, director of the Fed's Division 
of Banking Supervision and Regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	A few banks are extending credit to some borrowers ``based  
largely on the expectation that the current strong financial 
performance of these borrowers will continue indefinitely,'' the 
letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	It said that if examiners see signs of problems at banks, such  
as bank officials being slow to recognize problem loans, they 
should consider taking action and downgrading banks' federal 
ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech Monday to the Institute of International Bankers,  
Meyer cited ``a possible relaxation in credit discipline that our 
supervisory reviews have detected at some (U.S.) banks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While noting that bank loans remain sound overall, he said  
numbers of questionable loans ``have been rising modestly at some 
banks'' in recent months, a trend the central bank director called 
``troubling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Banks sometimes have been failing to put proposed loans through  
``stress tests'' designed to predict whether borrowers could 
withstand unexpected financial shocks, Meyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	James Chessen, chief economist of the American Bankers  
Association, acknowledged Monday that potentially risky loans have 
been increasing but added, ``They're still extraordinarily low.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Regulators are paid to worry,'' Chessen said after Meyer's  
speech. He said bankers have been asking prospective borrowers more 
questions than they did a year or two ago because they realize that 
the economic boom may soon slow. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the bankers' group reported the number of Americans  
overdue on credit card bills fell in the April-June quarter to a 
four-year low. The delinquency rate -- the percentage of accounts 30 
or more days overdue -- declined to 3.33 percent in the second 
quarter from 3.58 percent in the first. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
