<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phone Lines Flooded for Cancer Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Since beating breast cancer two years ago, Ellen  
Fewtrell has been adding to a file full of newspaper clippings 
about treatments. 
</P>
<P>
	She was excited Tuesday by news that volunteers have started  
signing up for the first human trials of endostatin, an 
experimental drug that has been shown to shrink tumors in mice. 
</P>
<P>
	``It definitely gives us hope,'' said Ms. Fewtrell, 34. ``I am a  
survivor, but God forbid one day I go to the doctor and I'm out of 
remission. This gives me hope that there is a chance I'll have many 
more tomorrows.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 1,400 cancer patients called special phone numbers  
Tuesday to sign up for the treatment. Between 15 and 30 people will 
be selected. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers are looking for volunteers over age 17 with solid  
tumors who have not benefited from other treatment. Patients with 
leukemia, lymphoma, myeloma or primary brain tumors are not 
eligible for the study. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is really a great breakthrough to begin the clinical  
trials,'' said Dr. David Rosenthal, spokesman for the American 
Cancer Society New England Division and a professor of medicine at 
Harvard Medical School. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cancer patients are always eager and hopeful for new news,''  
Rosenthal said. ``This has been on the radar screen since almost a 
year and a half ago as one of the new major ways of treating 
cancer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Research is being conducted by Dana-Farber/Partners Cancer Care,  
a collaboration of Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, Massachusetts 
General Hospital, Brigham and Women's Hospital and the Beth Israel 
Deaconess Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The lead researcher, Dr. Donald Kufe, cautioned that this is  
only the first phase -- to check for adverse side effects. However, 
researchers also will look for signs that the drug is halting 
progress of tumors. 
</P>
<P>
	Endostatin and a sister protein, angiostatin, work by destroying  
a tumor's ability to sprout new blood vessels. In research done by 
Dr. Judah Folkman at Children's Hospital, cancer went dormant or 
disappeared altogether in animals treated with the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Doubts cropped up last fall when it was reported that scientists  
from the National Cancer Institute had not been able to reproduce 
Folkman's results. Then, in February, an NCI team said it had 
duplicated Folkman's work by conducting the experiments at 
Folkman's laboratory. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial tests are being sponsored by EntreMed Inc., a  
Maryland-based company that licensed the right to develop 
endostatin. 
</P>
<P>
	Other trials will be conducted at the University of Texas M.D.  
Cancer Center in Houston and the University of Wisconsin 
Comprehensive Cancer Center. Fewer than 100 people are expected to 
receive the drug at the three locations. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
