<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Sept. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Offers $65B Health Care Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley  
offered a $65 billion plan today for universal access to health 
insurance that would require coverage for all children, with 
subsidies for families that cannot afford it. Under Bradley's plan, 
individuals of all ages and incomes also would be able to exclude 
from their taxable income whatever they pay for health premiums. He 
also would require parents to obtain health insurance for their 
children -- much like drivers are required to buy auto insurance -- 
and would offer full or partial premium subsidies to low-income 
families. All adults would get the option of buying into the same 
health plan provided to members of Congress. 

</P>
<P>
	House OKs Stopgap Spending Measure  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eyeing Friday's start of fiscal 2000, the  
House today approved a stopgap measure that will keep federal 
agencies functioning for three weeks as President Clinton and 
Republicans sort through spending disputes. Prior to the vote, 
Democrats blamed unyielding Republican demands for Congress' 
failure to complete most of the 13 spending bills on time, a 
failure that is nearly an annual event. 

</P>
<P>
	Massacre Reported in East Timor  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Indonesian soldiers and their militia  
allies massacred civilians even after a multinational force arrived 
to impose peace in East Timor, according to accounts emerging 
Tuesday. Wailing and weeping, mourners in the town of Baucau 
clutched at photos of two Roman Catholic nuns and seven others who 
were on a mercy mission for refugees when they were ambushed and 
killed. The missionaries were killed Saturday after delivering 
medicine and food to refugees displaced by the violence that 
followed East Timor's Aug. 30 vote for independence. 

</P>
<P>
	New Vaccine Reduces Pneumonia Risk  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A new pneumonia vaccine designed for  
infants appears to reduce severe childhood cases of the disease and 
may save hundreds of thousands of lives. Results were released 
today from a major study of the vaccine's effect on childhood 
pneumonia. Around the world, pneumonia caused by pneumococcus 
results in an estimated 600,000 deaths annually. Dr. Steven Black, 
who presented the data at an infectious-disease meeting sponsored 
by the American Society for Microbiology, estimated that the 
vaccine could prevent 450,000 of them. 

</P>
<P>
	ABC Will Stop Posting Web-User Info  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Viewers who tuned in to ABC's first-ever  
Internet news broadcast to chat electronically with anchor Sam 
Donaldson had more than their names and comments posted to the Web 
site for the world to see. ABC also disclosed the unique 
four-numbered Internet address for each person who wrote a comment 
yesterday, a decision that helps anyone trace a viewer's real-world 
identity. ABC said today the network will stop publishing each 
viewer's ``Internet protocol'' address alongside their chat-room 
comments. 

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Confidence Slips in Sept.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A report released today says consumer confidence  
weakened in September for the third consecutive month. The 
Conference Board's survey results gave Wall Street the jitters, as 
stocks tumbled in afternoon trading before recovering. It also 
suggested that Federal Reserve moves to raise interest rates are 
slowing the economy. The board said its index of consumer 
confidence, a measure of consumers' willingness to spend, dipped to 
134.2 in September, 1.8 percentage points lower than a revised 136 
reading in August. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 0.63 in Late Trading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today but the Dow Jones  
industrial average was down just 0.63 points at 10,302.76 just 
before the close. Declining issues on the New York Stock Exchange 
led advancers 2,013-980. The Nasdaq composite index was down 10.91 
at 2,750.84. 

</P>
<P>
	S. Williams Tops Sanchez-Vicario  
</P>
<P>
	MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- U.S. Open champion Serena Williams  
breezed past Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario 6-3, 6-1 in 53 minutes today 
to open the Grand Slam Cup. Williams, 17, blasted past the 
27-year-old Sanchez-Vicario, the oldest player in the eight-player 
women's field. Williams could meet her sister, Venus, in the final. 
Venus won the women's tournament last year. The tournament, which 
also includes 12 men, invites players with best records at the four 
Grand Slam events of the year. While Pete Sampras and Patrick 
Rafter are out with injuries, No. 1 Andre Agassi heads the men's 
section. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
