<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Drop; Dow Ends Off 27.86 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks staged a stunning late-session rally  
Tuesday, with the Dow Jones industrials rising nearly 200 points 
and finishing with only modest declines. The dollar's gains against 
the Japanese yen and computerized buying programs helped reverse 
the market's slide. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow finished down 27.86 at 10,275.53 after having fallen  
more than 222 points early in the afternoon. It marked the Dow's 
fifth drop in six sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also slipped slightly. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 1.11 at 1,282.20, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was off 5.50 at 2,756.25. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders became more positive when they saw the dollar make  
headway against the Japanese yen. The dollar's decline last week 
helped push the Dow down 524.30, its biggest weekly point loss 
ever. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saw the dollar getting stronger against the yen and that's  
what turned things around,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market 
analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``It was a huge psychological barrier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar edged slightly higher against the yen Tuesday, rising  
to 106.10 yen from 106.00 late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hogan said computerized buying programs also kicked in after the  
Dow fell more than 200 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time we come close to a 10 percent correction in the  
Dow, investors feel this is enough of a drop and they go back in 
and buy stocks,'' said Robert Freedman, executive vice president of 
the John Hancock Funds in Boston. ``That's what we saw happen 
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow is now down 1,050.51, or 9 percent, from its record high  
of 11,326.04 set on Aug. 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Buying was scarce for most of Tuesday amid a paucity of positive  
economic news. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board, a business research group, said consumer  
confidence dipped in September for a third consecutive month. The 
drop was larger than economists had expected, and may be a sign 
that consumer spending will slow. That could in turn influence the 
Federal Reserve against boosting interest rates to cool off the 
economy when its policy-setting Open Market Committee meets next 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But the consumer confidence report did little to move the  
markets, which remained anxious and unsettled before the Fed 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is suffering from a vacuum of positive  
information,'' said John Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist 
at Advest of Hartford, Conn. '' 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, investors have to deal with concerns of rising  
interest rates and gold prices and uncertainty about the dollar. 
Although the surge in gold prices the past two days has helped gold 
mining concerns, it also may heighten fears of inflation and higher 
interest rates, Shaughnessy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a water-torture type of correction,'' said Alfred  
Goldman, chief market strategist for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. 
Louis, of the market's recent performance. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that while there is uncertainty about interest rates on  
Wall Street, most traders expect the Fed to leave interest rates 
alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron, down 1 9/16 at 87 5/8, and General Electric, down 1 5/32  
to 118 1/2, were among the Dow's biggest losers. But J.P. Morgan, up 2 
3/16 at 118, helped the index's comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist rose 7 11/16 to 48 11/16, after  
Chase Manhattan said it would buy the brokerage operation, but 
Chase was off 5/16 at 73 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna, the largest U.S. health insurer, fell 5 3/16 to 61 3/4 on  
concerns the company's profits will be hurt by its purchase of 
Prudential HealthCare earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-6 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Consolidated volume came to 1.05 billion shares, up from 943.54  
million shares in Mondays session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.37 to 418.49  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 3.0 percent,  
Germany's DAX index was down 2.30 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was 
down 1.17 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 1.15 percent. 







  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
