<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1st Lady, Giuliani Spar Over Wage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, in Washington  
to start a fund-raising swing expected to rake in $300,000, said 
Tuesday he opposes raising the nation's minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani's remarks came as his likely Democratic rival in New  
York's Senate race, Hillary Rodham Clinton, appeared on Capitol 
Hill urging an increase in the $5.15 hourly rate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's right that any person in our country works  
full time and brings home wages that leaves that person and that 
person's family in poverty,'' Mrs. Clinton said. She said the 
buying power of the minimum wage has decreased dramatically since 
the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani, talking to reporters in a Washington hotel, said he  
worries that raising the minimum wage would hold down job creation, 
especially entry-level jobs that are allowing New Yorkers who have 
been on welfare to go to work. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point I would not be in favor of it until I saw that  
it had no impact on reducing the number of jobs,'' the Republican 
mayor said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Congressional Budget Office has estimated that a $1 increase  
in the minimum wage over two years would cost business roughly $16 
billion over five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., is pushing a proposal to increase  
the minimum wage by $1 in two installments, a 50-cent increase in 
January and another in the following year. Another proposal being 
floated in the House of Representatives would increase the rate by 
$1.30 over four years. In the still-evolving House proposal, such 
an increase would be coupled with tax breaks and other sweeteners 
for small businesses and the self-employed. 
</P>
<P>
	The appearance of Mrs. Clinton on Capitol Hill brought in droves  
of reporters and staffers to what would have been a fairly 
commonplace news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Although she was technically there as first lady, Mrs. Clinton  
used the occasion to trumpet themes she is likely to stress should 
she enter the New York Senate race: a higher minimum wage to help 
the working poor and women's and children's issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said raising the minimum wage is particularly  
important to the nation's women working full-time jobs at the 
minimum wage. The Kennedy bill would raise their incomes by $2,000 
a year, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have met a lot of people, particular women, across our  
country who have detailed to me the difference $2,000 a year would 
make in their lives and the lives of their children, how that could 
mean seven months worth of groceries or five months worth of rent 
or 10 months worth of utility,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later Tuesday, she was flying to New York to receive the  
National Breast Cancer Coalition Leadership Award. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani was in Washington to raise money on the first day of a  
three-day fund-raising tour that will also take him to Las Vegas, 
Los Angeles and Bakersfield, Calif. Washington's fund-raiser was at 
the lobbying office of former Republican National Committee 
Chairman Haley Barbour. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's campaign team has set a target of $25 million for  
the race. Giuliani's Senate exploratory committee has more than $3 
million in the bank already. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
